//   {"id":1000,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 17: Strength of acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Pure sulphuric acid turns dry blue litmus paper red.\nReason: Dilute sulphuric acid is a strong acid.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1001,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 17: Strength of acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Sodium hydroxide is very soluble in water but ammonia is just slightly soluble in water.\nReason: 1 M sodium hydroxide solution has a higher electrical conductivity than that of 1 M ammonia solution.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1002,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 17: Strength of acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: 12 M ammonia solution is a stronger alkali than 1 M sodium hydroxide solution.\nReason: Ammonia ionizes in water to give hydroxide ions.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1003,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 17: Strength of acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: If concentrated hydrochloric acid is spilt onto your hand, you should wash your hand with concentrated sodium carbonate solution.\nReason: Concentrated sodium carbonate solution is a strong alkali.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1004,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 18: Salts and neutralization","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following is NOT a neutralization reaction?","points":5,"options":["A. ZnO(s) + H2SO4(aq) → ZnSO4(aq) + H2O(l)","B. Cu(OH)2(s) + 2H+(aq) → Cu^2+(aq) + 2H2O(l)","C. H+(aq) + OH−(aq) → H2O(l)","D. Fe^3+(aq) + 3OH−(aq) → Fe(OH)3(s)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1005,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 18: Salts and neutralization","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following is/are neutralization reactions?\n(1) CH3COOH + NaOH → CH3COO-Na+ + H2O\n(2) Zn + 2H2SO4 → ZnSO4 + SO2 + 2H2O\n(3) 2HNO3 + K2CO3 → 2KNO3 + CO2 + H2O","points":5,"options":["A. (1) only","B. (2) only","C. (1) and (3) only","D. (2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"A"},
