//   {"id":1056,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 18: Salts and neutralization","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Lead(II) chloride can be prepared by titration method.\nReason: Lead(II) chloride is a white solid.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1057,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 18: Salts and neutralization","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Calcium sulphate can be effectively prepared by mixing calcium carbonate with dilute sulphuric acid.\nReason: Calcium sulphate is insoluble in water.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1058,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 18: Salts and neutralization","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Sodium hydroxide is used to neutralize the excess acid in stomach.\nReason: Sodium hydroxide is a base.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1059,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 18: Salts and neutralization","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Farmers sometimes add slaked lime to soil.\nReason: Slaked lime can neutralize the acid in soil.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1060,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 18: Salts and neutralization","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Liquid wastes from electroplating plants are treated with slaked lime before discharge.\nReason: Acids are electrolytes.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1061,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following is a correct procedure to prepare a standard solution with a pure solid?","points":5,"options":["A. Weigh the solid → Put into volumetric flask → Dissolve the solid → Add water to the mark of volumetric flask","B. Weigh the solid → Dissolve the solid → Put into volumetric flask → Add water to the mark of volumetric flask","C. Add water to the mark of volumetric flask → Weigh the solid → Dissolve the solid → Put into volumetric flask","D. Add water to the mark of volumetric flask → Weigh the solid → Put into volumetric flask → Dissolve the solid"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1062,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following substances CANNOT be used to prepare a standard solution directly?\n(1) Concentrated sulphuric acid\n(2) Solid sodium hydroxide\n(3) Liquid ammonia","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1063,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following methods can be used to prepare a standard sodium sulphate solution?\n(1) Dissolve a known mass of sodium sulphate crystal in a known volume of distilled water\n(2) Dilute a known molarity of sodium sulphate solution\n(3) Titrate standard sodium hydroxide solution with standard sulphuric acid","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1064,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"2.0 M hydrochloric acid is diluted to 0.2 M. Which of the following apparatus should be used in the dilution process?","points":5,"options":["A. Burette, volumetric flask and wash bottle","B. Pipette, conical flask and measuring cylinder","C. Pipette, volumetric flask and wash bottle","D. Burette, conical flask and pipette"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1065,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following apparatus are required to prepare standard sodium carbonate solution from anhydrous sodium carbonate?\n(1) Volumetric flask\n(2) Electronic balance\n(3) Pipette","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1066,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following apparatus should be cleaned with the solution to be held just before use in a titration experiment?\n(1) Pipette\n(2) Conical flask\n(3) Burette","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1067,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"In titrating 0.10 M sodium hydroxide solution with 0.10 M hydrochloric acid, the conical flask containing the alkali has to be first washed with","points":5,"options":["A. distilled water.","B. the alkali.","C. distilled water and then the alkali.","D. the acid."],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1068,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements about washing the apparatus before titration is/are correct?\n(1) A burette should be rinsed with distilled water first, followed by the solution it is to hold.\n(2) A conical flask should be dried thoroughly after rinsing with distilled water.\n(3) A pipette should not be rinsed with the solution it is about to deliver.","points":5,"options":["A. (1) only","B. (2) only","C. (1) and (3) only","D. (2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1069,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements about the use of a conical flask in titration are correct?\n(1) It is washed with the solution it is going to hold.\n(2) It is washed with distilled water.\n(3) A piece of white tile is placed under it during titration.","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1070,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following apparatus can transfer 28.7 cm^3 of solution most accurately?","points":5,"options":["A. Measuring cylinder","B. Burette","C. Pipette","D. Conical flask"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1071,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"In a titration experiment, 25.0 cm^3 of sodium hydroxide solution is titrated against a standard solution of sulphuric acid with phenolphthalein as an indicator. Which of the following statements concerning this experiment is/are correct?\n(1) The colour of the solution changes from colourless to pink at the end point.\n(2) The colour of the solution changes from pink to colourless at the end point.\n(3) The volume of sodium hydroxide solution is measured by a pipette.","points":5,"options":["A. (1) only","B. (2) only","C. (1) and (3) only","D. (2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1072,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Solution X is slowly added to a conical flask containing vinegar and a few drops of methyl orange. After a while, the colour of the mixture changes sharply from red to yellow. Which of the following substances can X be?\n(1) NH3(aq)\n(2) Ba(OH)2(aq)\n(3) Na2CrO4(aq)","points":5,"options":["A. (1) only","B. (2) only","C. (1) and (3) only","D. (2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1073,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following indicators are NOT suitable for the titration of ammonia solution and ethanoic acid?\n(1) Methyl orange\n(2) Phenolphthalein\n(3) Universal indicator","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (2) and (3) only","C. (1) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1074,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following titrations should use phenolphthalein to detect the end point?\n(1) Sodium hydroxide is titrated with hydrochloric acid\n(2) Sodium carbonate is titrated with nitric acid\n(3) Ethanoic acid is titrated with sodium hydroxide","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1075,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following indicators are suitable to detect the end point in the titration between 0.2 M HCl and 0.2 M NaOH?\n(1) Methyl orange\n(2) Phenolphthalein\n(3) Universal indicator","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1076,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"A dilute nitric acid is titrated against 20.0 cm^3 of 2.5 M sodium hydroxide solution. The following graph shows the change in temperature of the reaction mixture. (缺少圖片: Temperature vs Volume of dilute nitric acid graph with points P, Q, R)\nWhich of the following statements are correct?\n(1) Q is the end point of the titration.\n(2) The temperature rise at P to Q is due to the dissolution of sodium nitrate produced.\n(3) The temperature decreases at Q to R because the addition of nitric acid cools the reaction mixture.","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1077,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"In a titration experiment, 25.0 cm^3 of ammonia solution is titrated against standard hydrochloric acid with methyl orange as indicator. Which of the following colour changes at the end point is correct?","points":5,"options":["A. From yellow to orange","B. From red to orange","C. From red to colourless","D. From colourless to orange"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1078,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"One mole of an unknown acid requires two moles of NaOH for complete neutralization. Which of the following deductions is/are correct?\n(1) The unknown acid is dibasic.\n(2) The molarity of the unknown acid is twice of that of NaOH.\n(3) One mole of the unknown acid can be completely neutralized by two moles of NH3.","points":5,"options":["A. (1) only","B. (2) only","C. (1) and (3) only","D. (2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1079,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements about 25.0 cm^3 of 0.1 M sodium hydroxide solution and 25.0 cm^3 of 0.1 M ammonia solution is/are correct?\n(1) They have the same pH value.\n(2) They turn methyl orange indicator yellow.\n(3) Each of them requires 25.0 cm^3 of 0.1 M hydrochloric acid for complete neutralization.","points":5,"options":["A. (1) only","B. (2) only","C. (1) and (3) only","D. (2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1080,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following two solutions:\nSolution P: 50 cm^3 of 0.05 M HCl\nSolution Q: 25 cm^3 of 0.10 M CH3COOH\nWhich of the following statements about solutions P and Q is correct?","points":5,"options":["A. P reacts with magnesium while Q does not.","B. P and Q require the same volume of 0.1 M NaOH for neutralization.","C. P can turn blue litmus paper red while Q cannot.","D. P reacts with sodium hydrogencarbonate while Q does not."],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1081,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"25.0 cm^3 of 0.20 M sulphuric acid is completely neutralized by 15.5 cm^3 of sodium hydroxide solution. What is the resultant concentration of sodium sulphate solution?","points":5,"options":["A. 0.123 M","B. 0.247 M","C. 0.323 M","D. 0.645 M"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1082,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"What is the volume of 0.25 mol dm^−3 sulphuric acid required to neutralize 40.0 cm^3 of 0.2 mol dm^−3 sodium carbonate?","points":5,"options":["A. (0.25 × 40)/0.2 cm^3","B. (0.25 × 40 × 2)/0.2 cm^3","C. (0.2 × 40)/0.25 cm^3","D. (0.2 × 40)/(0.25 × 2) cm^3"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1083,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"25.0 cm^3 of ammonia solution was titrated with 0.05 M hydrochloric acid. The following table shows the results of titration.\nTitration 1: Final reading 2.70, Initial reading 37.70\nTitration 2: Final reading 3.60, Initial reading 35.70\nTitration 3: Final reading 11.10, Initial reading 43.30\nTitration 4: Final reading 9.80, Initial reading 42.00\nWhat is the molarity of ammonia solution?","points":5,"options":["A. 0.032 M","B. 0.064 M","C. 0.070 M","D. 0.140 M"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1084,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"In an experiment, 2.0 M sodium hydroxide solution was added to 20.0 cm^3 of 1.0 M sulphuric acid until the acid was completely neutralized. What is the concentration of sodium sulphate in the resultant solution?","points":5,"options":["A. 0.25 M","B. 0.33 M","C. 0.50 M","D. 1.00 M"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1085,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"What is the mass of magnesium that reacts completely with 25.0 cm^3 of 0.20 M hydrochloric acid?\n(Relative atomic mass: Mg = 24.3)","points":5,"options":["A. 0.06 g","B. 0.12 g","C. 0.18 g","D. 0.24 g"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1086,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"25.0 cm^3 of 1.0 M ethanoic acid and 25.0 cm^3 of 1.0 M hydrochloric acid are each titrated with sodium hydroxide solution. Which of the following will be the same for these two titrations?\n(1) Initial pH of the solution\n(2) Volume of sodium hydroxide solution required to reach the end point\n(3) pH at the end point","points":5,"options":["A. (1) only","B. (2) only","C. (1) and (3) only","D. (2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1087,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following solutions can completely neutralize 25.0 cm^3 of 0.2 M sulphuric acid?\n(1) 25.0 cm^3 of 0.2 M sodium hydroxide solution\n(2) 50.0 cm^3 of 0.2 M potassium hydroxide solution\n(3) 25.0 cm^3 of 0.2 M calcium hydroxide solution","points":5,"options":["A. (1) and (2) only","B. (1) and (3) only","C. (2) and (3) only","D. (1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1088,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"0.64 g of calcium metal is added to a beaker of water. After the reaction is completed, the solution formed is treated with 0.3 M nitric acid. What is the volume of the acid required for complete neutralization?\n(Relative atomic mass: Ca = 40.1)","points":5,"options":["A. 53 cm^3","B. 80 cm^3","C. 107 cm^3","D. 133 cm^3"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1089,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Citric acid is a tribasic acid. 10.0 cm^3 of citric acid solution requires 45.0 cm^3 of 0.10 M Ba(OH)2(aq) for complete reaction. What is the concentration of the citric acid solution?","points":5,"options":["A. 0.10 M","B. 0.15 M","C. 0.30 M","D. 0.45 M"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1090,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"A hydrochloric acid is titrated against 30.0 cm^3 of 2.0 M potassium hydroxide solution. The temperature of the mixture during titration is shown below: (缺少圖片: Temperature vs Volume of hydrochloric acid graph)\nWhat is the concentration of the hydrochloric acid?","points":5,"options":["A. 0.78 M","B. 1.00 M","C. 1.50 M","D. 1.58 M"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1091,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"When lead(II) nitrate solution is mixed with sodium sulphate solution, lead(II) sulphate is precipitated. Which of the following pairs of solutions would produce the greatest amount of precipitate?","points":5,"options":["A. 10 cm^3 of 0.5 M Pb(NO3)2(aq) + 15 cm^3 of 1.0 M Na2SO4(aq)","B. 15 cm^3 of 1.0 M Pb(NO3)2(aq) + 15 cm^3 of 1.0 M Na2SO4(aq)","C. 20 cm^3 of 1.0 M Pb(NO3)2(aq) + 20 cm^3 of 1.0 M Na2SO4(aq)","D. 25 cm^3 of 0.5 M Pb(NO3)2(aq) + 20 cm^3 of 1.0 M Na2SO4(aq)"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1092,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"A test tube contains 5.0 cm^3 of 2.0 M sodium sulphate solution. 1.0 cm^3 portions of lead(II) nitrate solution are added successively to the test tube. The following graph shows the height of the precipitate after each addition. (缺少圖片: height of precipitate vs volume of lead(II) nitrate solution added graph)\nWhat is the concentration of lead(II) nitrate solution?","points":5,"options":["A. 0.75 M","B. 1.00 M","C. 1.25 M","D. 1.50 M"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1093,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"What is the concentration of sulphate ions in a mixture of 30.0 cm^3 of 1.0 M Al2(SO4)3(aq) and 50.0 cm^3 of 0.5 M Ba(NO3)2(aq)?","points":5,"options":["A. 0.18 M","B. 0.31 M","C. 0.81 M","D. 1.13 M"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1094,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"1.5 M sulphuric acid was added to 30.0 cm^3 of 2.0 M potassium hydroxide solution until the alkali was completely neutralized. What is the concentration of potassium sulphate in the resultant solution?","points":5,"options":["A. 0.20 M","B. 0.40 M","C. 0.60 M","D. 0.80 M"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1095,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"A mixture consists of 2 mol of calcium carbonate and 3 mol of potassium hydrogencarbonate. What is the least volume of 2 M nitric acid required for the reaction to produce the greatest amount of carbon dioxide?","points":5,"options":["A. 2.5 dm^3","B. 3.0 dm^3","C. 3.5 dm^3","D. 4.0 dm^3"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1096,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"The concentration of an acid solution is 2.0 M. 10.0 cm^3 of this acid solution requires 40.0 cm^3 of 1.0 M sodium hydroxide solution for complete neutralization. What is the basicity of the acid?","points":5,"options":["A. 1","B. 2","C. 3","D. 4"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1097,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"The formula of a solid tribasic acid is H3X. 3.89 g of the acid is dissolved in 250.0 cm^3 of distilled water. 25.0 cm^3 of the dilute solution requires 18.00 cm^3 of 0.50 M sodium hydroxide solution for complete neutralization. What is the molar mass of H3X?","points":5,"options":["A. 100 g mol^−1","B. 110 g mol^−1","C. 120 g mol^−1","D. 130 g mol^−1"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1098,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"The formula of a dibasic acid is H2L. 3.60 g of the acid was dissolved in water and made up to 250.0 cm^3 of solution. 25.0 cm^3 of this solution requires 20.00 cm^3 of 0.5 M NaOH(aq) for complete neutralization. What is the molar mass of H2L?","points":5,"options":["A. 72.0 g","B. 78.0 g","C. 360 g","D. 720 g"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1099,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"0.53 g of a metal carbonate L2CO3 was dissolved in distilled water and made up to 30.0 cm^3 of solution. The solution required 20.00 cm^3 of 0.25 M sulphuric acid for complete reaction. What is the relative atomic mass of metal L?\n(Relative atomic masses: C = 12.0, O = 16.0)","points":5,"options":["A. 69.0","B. 39.0","C. 33.0","D. 23.0"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1100,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"0.57 g of a sample of hydrated sodium carbonate Na2CO3 • nH2O required 20.0 cm^3 of 0.20 M hydrochloric acid for complete neutralization. What is the number of crystallization, n, in the formula?\n(Relative atomic masses: H = 1.0, C = 12.0, O = 16.0, Na = 23.0)","points":5,"options":["A. 1","B. 5","C. 9","D. 10"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1101,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"1.05 g of a mixture of anhydrous sodium carbonate and sodium chloride was dissolved in 50 cm^3 of distilled water. The resultant solution required 28.50 cm^3 of 0.15 M sulphuric acid for complete reaction. What is the percentage by mass of anhydrous sodium carbonate in the mixture?\n(Relative atomic masses: C = 12.0, O = 16.0, Na = 23.0)","points":5,"options":["A. 21.4 %","B. 43.8 %","C. 64.3 %","D. 85.6 %"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1102,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"A metal carbonate has the chemical formula MCO3. 50.0 cm^3 of 1.5 M hydrochloric acid was added to 3.82 g of the metal carbonate. The unreacted hydrochloric acid required 26.50 cm^3 of 0.50 M sodium hydroxide for complete neutralization. What is the relative atomic mass of the metal?\n(Relative atomic masses: C = 12.0, O = 16.0)","points":5,"options":["A. 52.0","B. 55.8","C. 58.7","D. 63.6"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1103,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: A solution of 1.0 M is a standard solution.\nReason: A standard solution is a solution of accurately known molarity.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1104,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Sodium hydroxide pellets should not be used to prepare standard sodium hydroxide solution.\nReason: Sodium hydroxide is corrosive.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1105,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: A 25.0 cm^3 pipette can be used to deliver 22.5 cm^3 solution in a titration.\nReason: There is a graduation mark on a pipette.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1106,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: Before performing a titration, distilled water is used to wash a conical flask.\nReason: Water present in a conical flask will not change the number of moles of solute in the flask.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1107,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: When filling a burette with a solution, a funnel is used instead of directly filling from a beaker.\nReason: It is easier to fill a burette through a funnel than directly filling from a beaker.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1108,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chapter 19: Volumetric analysis involving acids and alkalis","type":"choice","text":"Assertion: In a titration, 1 mole of any acid always neutralizes 1 mole of any alkali.\nReason: 1 mole of hydrogen ions reacts with 1 mole of hydroxide ions.","points":5,"options":["A. Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","B. Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","C. The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","D. Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1109,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"The following hazard warning labels are displayed on the reagent bottle of an acid. (缺少圖片，文件名4. Acids and Bases) What information about this acid can be obtained from the labels?","points":5,"options":["It is very concentrated and flammable.","It is very concentrated and oxidising.","It is flammable and corrosive.","It is corrosive and oxidising."],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1110,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"500 cm³ of calcium hydroxide solution contains 3.7 g of calcium hydroxide. What is the molarity of the solution? (Relative atomic masses: H = 1.0, O = 16.0, Ca = 40.1)","points":5,"options":["0.05 M","0.10 M","0.13 M","0.26 M"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1111,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following types of apparatus should be used to measure 25.0 cm³ of the toilet cleaner?","points":5,"options":["pipette","burette","measuring cylinder","volumetric flask"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1112,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"What is the colour change at the end point of the titration?","points":5,"options":["from colourless to pink","from pink to colourless","from yellow to red","from red to yellow"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1113,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"What is the concentration of sulphuric acid in the undiluted toilet cleaner?","points":5,"options":["1.29 M","2.58 M","5.15 M","10.3 M"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1114,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"A black powder is suspected to be carbon or a mixture of carbon and copper(II) oxide. Which of the following methods can be used to identify the black powder?\n(1) adding dilute sulphuric acid to the powder\n(2) adding sodium hydroxide solution to the powder\n(3) heating the powder strongly","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1115,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"At 298 K, the pH of 0.10 mol dm⁻³ HCl(aq) is 1. Which of the following statements is correct?","points":5,"options":["At 298 K, the pH of 0.20 mol dm⁻³ HCl(aq) is 2.","At 298 K, the pH of 0.20 mol dm⁻³ HCl(aq) is 0.5.","At 298 K, the pH of 0.01 mol dm⁻³ HCl(aq) is 2.","At 298 K, the pH of 0.01 mol dm⁻³ HCl(aq) is 0.1."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1116,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"10 cm³ of 0.25 mol dm⁻³ calcium nitrate solution is mixed with 40 cm³ of 0.10 mol dm⁻³ nitric acid. What is the concentration of nitrate ions in the resulting solution?","points":5,"options":["0.18 mol dm⁻³","0.13 mol dm⁻³","0.080 mol dm⁻³","0.050 mol dm⁻³"],"answerLetter":"A"},
//   {"id":1117,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following reagents would undergo neutralisation with limewater?\n(1) HCl(aq)\n(2) Na₂SO₄(aq)\n(3) SO₂(g)","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1118,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"A salt has the formula (NH₄)₂SO₄·FeSO₄·6H₂O. Which of the following is/are the expected observation(s) when an aqueous solution of this salt is treated with aqueous sodium hydroxide solution?\n(1) formation of a dirty green precipitate\n(2) formation of a brown precipitate\n(3) evolution of a gas with a pungent odour","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1119,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following methods can be used to distinguish between 0.1 mol dm⁻³ HCl(aq) and 0.1 mol dm⁻³ CH₃CO₂H(aq)?\n(1) Add magnesium ribbon of the same length to each solution and compare the rate of evolution of gas bubbles.\n(2) Add 10 cm³ of 0.1 mol dm⁻³ NaOH(aq) to 10 cm³ of each solution and compare the temperature change.\n(3) Use each solution as electrolyte in the set-up shown on the right and compare the brightness of the bulb. (缺少圖片，文件名4. Acids and Bases)","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1120,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"A small amount of a powder can dissolve in water to form a clear solution. When this solution is mixed with K₂CO₃(aq), a white precipitate is obtained. What can the powder be?","points":5,"options":["sodium sulphate","calcium sulphate","sodium hydroxide","calcium hydroxide"],"answerLetter":"D"},
//   {"id":1121,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements concerning CH₃COOH and HCl is correct?","points":5,"options":["CH₃COOH is a stronger acid than HCl.","The pH of 0.1 M CH₃COOH(aq) is lower than that of 0.1 M HCl(aq).","Both CH₃COOH(aq) and HCl(aq) react with NH₃(aq), each giving a salt.","Both CH₃COOH(aq) and HCl(aq) react with Ag(s), each giving a colourless gas."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1122,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"A sample of 1.02 g of potassium hydrogenphthalate (C₈H₅O₄K) is dissolved completely in distilled water, and then diluted to 250.0 cm³. What is the concentration of solution of the solution obtained? (Relative atomic masses: H = 1.0, C = 12.0, K = 39.1)","points":5,"options":["0.004 M","0.010 M","0.020 M","4.080 M"],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1123,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following pairs of reactants would react in water to give out the largest amount of heat?","points":5,"options":["1 mol of HCl and 1 mol of KOH","1 mol of H₂SO₄ and 2 mol of KOH","1 mol of (COOH)₂ and 2 mol of KOH","1 mol of CH₃COOH and 1 mol of KOH"],"answerLetter":"B"},
//   {"id":1124,"subject":"化學","topic":"2A: Acids and Bases","type":"choice","text":"In which of the following processes would a colourless gas evolve?\n(1) Magnesium is added to dilute sulphuric acid.\n(2) Ammonium chloride is heated with calcium hydroxide.\n(3) Water is added to a solid mixture of citric acid and sodium hydrogencarbonate.","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
