// {"id":1343,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Standard enthalpy changes of several reactions, as denoted by x, y and z respectively, are listed in the table below: Reaction: C(s)+O2(g)->CO2(g) ΔH=x; H2(g)+1/2O2(g)->H2O(g) ΔH=y; C(s)+2H2(g)->CH4(g) ΔH=z. For the reaction CH4(g) + 2O2(g) -> CO2(g) + 2H2O(l), which of the following is a reasonable estimate of its standard enthalpy change?","points":5,"options":["x + y - z","-x - y + z","x + 2y - z","-x - 2y - z"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1344,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"In an experiment, 10.0g of KCl(s) was added to 100 cm3 of water. The mixture was then stirred until all the KCl(s) dissolved. The temperature of the mixture was found to drop by 5.5°C. What is the molar enthalpy change, in kJ mol-1, of the dissolving process of KCl(s) under the conditions of the experiment? (Specific heat capacity of the mixture = 4.2 J g-1 K-1; Density of water = 1.0 g cm-3; Relative atomic masses: K = 39.1, Cl = 35.5)","points":5,"options":["2.31","2.54","17.23","18.96"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1345,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following processes is endothermic?","points":5,"options":["H2O(l) -> H2O(s)","CuSO4(s) + 5H2O(l) -> CuSO4·5H2O(s)","2H2O(l) -> 2H2(g) + O2(g)","Ca(s) + 2H2O(l) -> Ca(OH)2(aq) + H2(g)"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1346,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"When 25 cm3 of 1.00 mol dm-3 NaOH(aq) is mixed with 25 cm3 of 1.00 mol dm-3 HCl(aq), the temperature of the mixture rises by 6°C. Which of the following reactants, when mixed under the same conditions, would give a similar temperature rise?","points":5,"options":["25 cm3 of 2.00 mol dm-3 NaOH(aq) and 25 cm3 of 2.00 mol dm-3 HCl(aq)","50 cm3 of 1.00 mol dm-3 NaOH(aq) and 50 cm3 of 1.00 mol dm-3 HCl(aq)","50 cm3 of 0.50 mol dm-3 NaOH(aq) and 50 cm3 of 0.50 mol dm-3 HCl(aq)","100 cm3 of 0.25 mol dm-3 NaOH(aq) and 100 cm3 of 0.25 mol dm-3 HCl(aq)"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1347,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Consider the standard enthalpy changes of the following reactions: I2(s) + Cl2(g) -> 2ICl(s) ΔH⦵ = +14 kJ mol-1; ICl(s) + Cl2(g) -> ICl3(s) ΔH⦵ = -88 kJ mol-1. What is the standard enthalpy change of formation of ICl3(s)?","points":5,"options":["-81 kJ mol-1","-74 kJ mol-1","+74 kJ mol-1","+81 kJ mol-1"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1348,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following methods can be used to distinguish between 0.1 mol dm-3 HCl(aq) and 0.1 mol dm-3 CH3CO2H(aq)? (1) Add magnesium ribbon of the same length to each solution and compare the rate of evolution of gas bubbles. (2) Add 10 cm3 of 0.1 mol dm-3 NaOH(aq) to 10 cm3 of each solution and compare the temperature change. (3) Use each solution as electrolyte in the set-up shown on the right and compare the brightness of the bulb.","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1349,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"The standard enthalpy changes of combustion of some substances are shown below: H2(g) = -286 kJ mol-1, C(graphite) = -394 kJ mol-1, CH3CH2OH(l) = -1371 kJ mol-1. The standard enthalpy change of formation at 298K of CH3CH2OH(l) is","points":5,"options":["-275 kJ mol-1","+275 kJ mol-1","+691 kJ mol-1","-3017 kJ mol-1"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1350,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following pairs of reactants would react in water to give out the largest amount of heat?","points":5,"options":["1 mol of HCl and 1 mol of KOH","1 mol of H2SO4 and 2 mol of KOH","1 mol of (COOH)2 and 2 mol of KOH","1 mol of CH3COOH and 1 mol of KOH"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1351,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"For which of the following reactions must its enthalpy change be determined by INDIRECT methods?","points":5,"options":["Zn(s) + CuSO4(aq) -> ZnSO4(aq) + Cu(s)","2C(s) + O2(g) -> 2CO(g)","CH3CH2OH(l) + 3O2(g) -> 2CO2(g) + 3H2O(l)","MgO(s) + 2HCl(aq) -> MgCl2(aq) + H2O(l)"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1352,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Under standard conditions, complete combustion of 0.050 mol of propane (C3H8) gives 111 kJ of heat. Which of the following is the standard enthalpy change of formation of propane? (Standard enthalpy change of formation of H2O(l) = -286 kJ mol-1, standard enthalpy change of formation of CO2(g) = -394 kJ mol-1)","points":5,"options":["-106 kJ mol-1","+106 kJ mol-1","-569 kJ mol-1","+569 kJ mol-1"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1353,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"The enthalpy changes of three reactions under certain conditions are shown below: B2H6(g) + 3O2(g) -> B2O3(s) + 3H2O(l) ΔH = -2170 kJ mol-1; B(s) + 3/4O2(g) -> 1/2B2O3(s) ΔH = -635 kJ mol-1; H2(s) + 1/2O2(g) -> H2O(l) ΔH = -286 kJ mol-1. Which of the following is the enthalpy change of formation of B2H6(g) under the same conditions?","points":5,"options":["+42 kJ mol-1","+614 kJ mol-1","+677 kJ mol-1","+1249 kJ mol-1"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1354,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"In an experiment, standard HCl(aq) was added from a burette to a known volume of NaOH(aq) placed in an expanded polystyrene cup. The graph below shows the temperatures of the mixture in the cup during the process: (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[269, 453, 778, 757]]). What is the greatest temperature rise of the mixture in the cup as estimated from the graph above?","points":5,"options":["2.0 °C","4.6 °C","6.2 °C","6.6 °C"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1355,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following reactions: (1) CO2(g) + CaO(s) -> CaCO3(s) ΔH1; (2) NH3(g) + HBr(g) -> NH4Br(s) ΔH2; (3) HF(g) + NaOH(aq) -> NaF(aq) + H2O(l) ΔH3; (4) NaHCO3(aq) + HCl(aq) -> NaCl(aq) + CO2(g) + H2O(l) ΔH4. Which of the following represents enthalpy change of neutralisation?","points":5,"options":["ΔH1","ΔH2","ΔH3","ΔH4"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1356,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following combinations is / are correct? (1) 2H2O(l) -> 2H2(g) + O2(g) Enthalpy change of reaction: positive; (2) 2CO(g) + 2O2(g) -> 2CO2(g) Enthalpy change of reaction: positive; (3) 2Na(s) + 2H2O(l) -> 2NaOH(aq) + H2(g) Enthalpy change of reaction: negative","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1357,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following processes are exothermic? (1) placing calcium oxide in water (2) placing a zinc strip in a copper(II) sulphate solution (3) passing hydrogen chloride gas into a sodium hydroxide solution","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1358,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: The standard enthalpy change of formation of a compound must be a negative value. 2nd statement: Under standard conditions, a compound must be energetically more stable than its constituent elements.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1359,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"In an experiment for studying the enthalpy change of a reaction, the variation of the temperature of the content in the reaction container with time was plotted in a graph as shown below: (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[263, 368, 764, 741]]). The reaction starts at the third minute. Which of the following combinations is correct?","points":5,"options":["The greatest temperature rise of the content: 51°C, Enthalpy change of the reaction: negative","The greatest temperature rise of the content: 41°C, Enthalpy change of the reaction: negative","The greatest temperature rise of the content: 51°C, Enthalpy change of the reaction: positive","The greatest temperature rise of the content: 41°C, Enthalpy change of the reaction: positive"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1360,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following information: 2H2O(l) -> 2H2(g) + O2(g) ΔH⦵ = +x kJ mol-1. Which of the following statements is / are correct? (1) The standard enthalpy change of formation of H2O(l) is -0.5x kJ mol-1. (2) The standard enthalpy change of formation of H2O(l) is +0.5x kJ mol-1. (3) The standard enthalpy change of combustion of H2(g) is -x kJ mol-1.","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1361,"subject":"化學","topic":"8. Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following processes are endothermic? (1) melting of wax (2) cracking of heavy oil (3) adding zinc powder to CuSO4(aq)","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1362,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following changes will NOT increase the initial rate of the reaction between 50 cm3 of 1 M HCl(aq) and excess calcium carbonate granules?","points":5,"options":["using 100 cm3 of HCl(aq) instead of 50 cm3 of HCl(aq)","using 2M HCl(aq) instead of 1M HCl(aq)","using 25 cm3 of 2M HCl(aq) instead of 50 cm3 of 1M HCl(aq)","using calcium carbonate powder instead of calcium carbonate granules"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1363,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"In which of the above conical flasks does the reaction proceed at the fastest rate? (缺少圖片，文件名: 表格數據)","points":5,"options":["W","X","Y","Z"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1364,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following apparatus should be used when carrying out the above experiment in addition to the conical flasks? (1) syringe (2) stop watch (3) measuring cylinder","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1365,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: Catalysts are used in many industrial processes. 2nd statement: Catalysts would not affect the percentage of the product in the equilibrium mixture.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1366,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"A scientist extracted a sample of 'nitrogen' from air by removing the oxygen and carbon dioxide. The scientist then compared the mass of a known volume of the 'nitrogen' sample (m1) with that of the same volume of pure nitrogen (m2) under the same set of conditions. The experiment was repeated a number of times. It was found that m1 was consistently greater than m2. Which of the following gases is likely to be present in the 'nitrogen' obtained to account for the result that m1 is greater than m2?","points":5,"options":["neon","argon","methane","water vapour"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1367,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following methods can be used to distinguish between 0.1 mol dm-3 HCl(aq) and 0.1 mol dm-3 CH3CO2H(aq)? (1) Add magnesium ribbon of the same length to each solution and compare the rate of evolution of gas bubbles. (2) Add 10 cm3 of 0.1 mol dm-3 NaOH(aq) to 10 cm3 of each solution and compare the temperature change. (3) Use each solution as electrolyte in the set-up shown on the right and compare the brightness of the bulb.","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1368,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"The set-up shown below is used in an experiment to study the rate of the reaction: CaCO3(s) + 2HCl(aq) -> CaCl2(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g). (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[181, 437, 856, 651]]). The conical flask is shaken to overturn the vial in order to start the reaction. The initial rate of the reaction with respect to the gas liberated is determined. The experiment is then repeated with only one of the conditions changed while the others remain unchanged. Under which of the following situations would the initial rate be the same as that in the original experiment?","points":5,"options":["using 10 cm3 of 1 mol dm-3 HCl(aq)","using 5 cm3 of 2 mol dm-3 HCl(aq)","using 5 cm3 of 1 mol dm-3 HCl(aq) which is preheated to 50°C","using powdered CaCO3(s) of the same mass"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1369,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"0.40g of an impure sample of zinc granules reacts with excess dilute sulphuric acid to give 100 cm3 of hydrogen, measured at room temperature and pressure. Assuming that the impurities in the zinc granules do not react with sulphuric acid, what is the percentage by mass of zinc in the sample? (Relative atomic masses: H = 1.0, Zn = 65.4, molar volume of gas at room temperature and pressure = 24 dm3)","points":5,"options":["25","34","68","73"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1370,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"In which of the following reactions, is/are the transition metal species NOT acting as a catalyst? (1) action of acidified MnO4-(aq) on SO32-(aq) at room temperature (2) action of Ni(s) on a mixture of H2C=CH2(g) and H2(g) at high temperature (3) action of Pt(s) on a mixture of CO(g) and O2(g) at high temperature","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1371,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Some brands of washing powder contain enzymes. Which of the following statements about the action of the enzymes is/are correct? (1) The activity of the enzymes increases with temperature. (2) The enzymes facilitate the removal of specific kinds of dirt. (3) The enzymes reduce the surface tension of water.","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1372,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"What is the theoretical volume of carbon dioxide that can be obtained, at room temperature and pressure, when 1.2g of Na2CO3(s) reacts with 50 cm3 of 1.0M HNO3? (Molar volume of gas at room temperature and pressure = 24 dm3; Relative atomic masses: H = 1.0, C = 12.0, N = 14.0, O = 16.0, Na = 23.0)","points":5,"options":["272 cm3","544 cm3","600 cm3","1200 cm3"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1373,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"The concentration-time graph for a certain chemical reaction in a closed vessel of fixed volume is shown below: (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[275, 341, 761, 595]]). Which of the following chemical equations correctly represents the reaction?","points":5,"options":["P(g) -> Q(g)","Q(g) -> P(g)","P(g) -> 2Q(g)","Q(g) -> 2P(g)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1374,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"For which of the following can their progress of reaction be followed by colorimetry? (1) 2MnO4-(aq) + 5C2O42-(aq) + 16H+(aq) -> 2Mn2+(aq) + 10CO2(g) + 8H2O(l) (2) SO32-(aq) + 2H+(aq) -> SO2(aq) + H2O(l) (3) Br2(aq) + HCO2H(aq) -> 2Br-(aq) + CO2(g) + 2H+(aq)","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1375,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: Increasing reaction temperature can increase the yield for all reversible chemical reactions. 2nd statement: Increasing reaction temperature can shorten the time needed to attain equilibrium for all reversible chemical reactions.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1376,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"In an experiment to study the rate of the following reaction, a small amount of powdered calcium carbonate was added to excess hydrochloric acid and the volume of gas liberated was recorded. CaCO3(s) + 2HCl(aq) -> CaCl2(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g). The graph below shows the volumes of gas liberated (V) at different times (t) during the experiment: (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[364, 406, 662, 547]]). The experiment was repeated under the same conditions using the same mass of calcium carbonate granules instead of powdered calcium carbonate. Which of the following graphs would best represent the results obtained in the repeated experiment? (缺少圖片，文件名: 圖表)","points":5,"options":["A","B","C","D"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1377,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"H2O2(aq) decomposes into H2O(l) and O2(g) in the presence of MnO2(s). Two experiments are performed to study this decomposition under the same conditions, except that 50 cm3 of 2M H2O2(aq) is used in Experiment (1), while 100 cm3 of 1M H2O2(aq) is used in Experiment (2). Which of the following combinations is correct? Rate of formation of O2(g) at the start, Total volume of O2(g) formed","points":5,"options":["Experiment (1) > Experiment (2), Experiment (1) = Experiment (2)","Experiment (1) > Experiment (2), Experiment (1) > Experiment (2)","Experiment (1) = Experiment (2), Experiment (1) = Experiment (2)","Experiment (1) = Experiment (2), Experiment (1) > Experiment (2)"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1378,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following pairs of chemicals, upon mixing under the same temperature, has the highest rate of gas formation?","points":5,"options":["0.10g of Zn powder and 100 cm3 of 1.0M HCl(aq)","0.10g of Zn granules and 200 cm3 of 1.0M HCl(aq)","0.10g of Zn granules and 200 cm3 of 1.0M H2SO4(aq)","0.10g of Zn powder and 100 cm3 of 1.0M H2SO4(aq)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1379,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: At room conditions, the volume of 1 mol of SO2(g) is larger than that of 1 mol of N2(g). 2nd statement: The number of atoms constituting 1 mol of SO2(g) is greater than that constituting 1 mol of N2(g).","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1380,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"In an experiment, 0.03 mol of Mg(s) is allowed to react with 20.0 cm3 of 1.0M HCl(aq). Which of the following graphs best represents the results of the experiment? (缺少圖片，文件名: 圖表)","points":5,"options":["A","B","C","D"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1381,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements are correct? (1) Magnesium oxide dissolves faster in 1 M HCl(aq) than in 1 M CH3CO2H(aq). (2) Powdered marble dissolves faster in 1 M HCl(aq) than granular marble does. (3) H2O2(aq) decomposes faster in the presence of MnO2(s) than without MnO2(s).","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1382,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following reaction: Br2(aq) + HCOOH(aq) -> CO2(g) + 2HBr(aq). Which of the following can be measured in order to follow the progress of the reaction? (1) the volume of gas formed (2) the turbidity of the reaction mixture (3) the colour intensity of the reaction mixture","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1383,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements concerning the rate of the reaction is correct? (缺少圖片，文件名: 表格數據)","points":5,"options":["It depends on [A(aq)], and also depends on [B(aq)].","It increases with [A(aq)], but does not increase with [B(aq)].","It increases with [B(aq)], but does not increase with [A(aq)].","It does not depend on [A(aq)], and also does not depend on [B(aq)]."],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1384,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Of which of the following reactions can the rate be studied by the above set-up? (缺少圖片，文件名: 圖表)","points":5,"options":["CaCl2(aq) + H2SO4(aq) -> CaSO4(s) + 2HCl(aq)","Na2CO3(aq) + 2HCl(aq) -> 2NaCl(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g)","2FeSO4(aq) + 2H2SO4(l) -> Fe2(SO4)3(aq) + 2H2O(l) + SO2(g)","Na2S2O3(aq) + 2HCl(aq) -> S(s) + SO2(aq) + H2O(l) + 2NaCl(aq)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1385,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"A certain mass of a sample of Ag2O(s) is strongly heated in a test tube. Which of the following shows the relationship of the mass of the contents (m) in the test tube with time (t) from the start of heating? (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[191, 280, 846, 529]])","points":5,"options":["A","B","C","D"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1386,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"100 cm3 of 1.0 M HCl(aq) reacts with excess zinc granules giving curve A in the graph below. (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[302, 623, 728, 782]]). Which of the following changes may give curve B?","points":5,"options":["Increase the temperature by 5°C.","Use the same mass of zinc powder instead of zinc granules.","Use 200 cm3 0.80 M HCl(aq) instead of 100 cm3 of 1.0 M HCl(aq).","Use 50 cm3 of 1.50 M HCl(aq) instead of 100 cm3 of 1.0 M HCl(aq)."],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1387,"subject":"化學","topic":"9. Rate of Reaction","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following two reactions: (I) 1.0 g of Na2CO3(s) + 100.0 cm3 of 1.0 M HCl(aq); (II) 1.0 g of Na2CO3(s) + 100.0 cm3 of 1.0 M CH3COOH(aq). Which of the following statements are correct if the two reactions are performed under the same experimental conditions? (Relative atomic masses: C = 12.0, O = 16.0, Na = 23.0) (1) The decrease in mass for the two reaction mixtures is the same. (2) The initial rate of Reaction (I) is higher than that of Reaction (II). (3) The heat given out for the two reactions is the same.","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1388,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following system at equilibrium: A(g) + 2B(g) ⇌ 2C(g) ΔH = +200 kJ mol-1. What would be the effect on the rates of the forward and backward reactions if the temperature of the system were lowered? forward reaction rate, backward reaction rate","points":5,"options":["decreases, increases","decreases, no change","decreases, decreases","increases, decreases"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1389,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"A mixture of N2O4(g) and NO2(g) is allowed to attain equilibrium in a gas syringe at room temperature: N2O4(g) ⇌ 2NO2(g) (light brown ⇌ dark brown). The gas mixture in the syringe is compressed rapidly. Which of the following statements correctly describes the expected observation?","points":5,"options":["The colour of the mixture becomes paler.","The colour of the mixture becomes darker.","The colour of the mixture becomes paler instantaneously and then darker.","The colour of the mixture becomes darker instantaneously and then paler."],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1390,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following is/are characteristic(s) of chemical equilibrium? (1) When a catalyst is added to an equilibrium mixture, the equilibrium position changes. (2) When equilibrium is attained, the rate of forward reaction and that of backward reaction are equal. (3) Equilibrium can be attained from either direction of the reaction.","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1391,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"In a 1 dm3 closed container, 1 mole of X2(g) undergoes decomposition to form X(g) until equilibrium is attained. The chemical equation concerned is shown below: X2(g) ⇌ 2X(g). Which of the following graphs correctly shows the variation in concentrations of X2(g) and X(g) with time? (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[108, 177, 967, 635]])","points":5,"options":["A","B","C","D"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1392,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: Increasing reaction temperature can increase the yield for all reversible chemical reactions. 2nd statement: Increasing reaction temperature can shorten the time needed to attain equilibrium for all reversible chemical reactions.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1393,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Refer to the following reversible reaction: X2(g) + 3Y2(g) ⇌ 2XY3(g). A mixture of X2(g) and Y2(g) was introduced into a 2.0 dm3 closed vessel kept at a fixed temperature. When the system attained equilibrium, the vessel contained 0.4 mol of X2(g), 0.3 mol of Y2(g) and 0.4 mol of XY3(g). Which of the following is the numerical value of Kc for the above reaction at this temperature?","points":5,"options":["3.3","6.7","14.8","59.3"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1394,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Refer to the following reversible reaction: X2(g) + 3Y2(g) ⇌ 2XY3(g). Which of the following combinations shows the effects of a catalyst on the rate of forward reaction, rate of backward reaction and the yield of XY3(g)?","points":5,"options":["Rate of forward reaction: increased, Rate of backward reaction: increased, Yield of XY3(g): Unchanged","Rate of forward reaction: unchanged, Rate of backward reaction: unchanged, Yield of XY3(g): Unchanged","Rate of forward reaction: increased, Rate of backward reaction: decreased, Yield of XY3(g): Increased","Rate of forward reaction: decreased, Rate of backward reaction: increased, Yield of XY3(g): Decreased"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1395,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Consider the information below: Equilibrium constant at 25°C: (1) A(aq) + B(aq) ⇌ C(aq) + D(aq) K1; (2) C(aq) + D(aq) ⇌ E(aq) + F(aq) + G(aq) K2; (3) E(aq) + F(aq) + G(aq) ⇌ A(aq) + B(aq) K3. Which of the following combinations is correct? Relationship of K1, K2 and K3, Unit of K3","points":5,"options":["K3 = 1/(K1×K2), mol dm-3","K3 = 1/(K1×K2), mol-1 dm3","K3 = K1×K2, mol dm-3","K3 = K1×K2, mol-1 dm3"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1396,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"The following system attained equilibrium at a certain temperature: 2SO2(g) + O2(g) ⇌ 2SO3(g). Which of the following statements is / are correct when the volume of the system is decreased while the temperature remains unchanged? (1) The value of Kc increases. (2) The equilibrium position shifts to the right. (3) The rate of decomposition of SO3(g) increases.","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1397,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: At chemical equilibrium state, the forward reaction rate equals zero. 2nd statement: At chemical equilibrium state, the reactants would not react to give the products.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1398,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following reaction at a certain temperature: 2XY2(g) ⇌ X2(g) + 2Y2(g) Kc = 0.60 mol dm-3. An equilibrium mixture was obtained at this temperature as shown below: (缺少圖片，文件名: image[[96, 667, 943, 760]]). What is n?","points":5,"options":["1.5","3.0","0.15","0.30"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1399,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"In a closed container and at a certain temperature, the following equilibrium was attained: COCl2(g) ⇌ CO(g) + Cl2(g). Which of the following statements is / are correct? (1) CO(g) and Cl2(g) must be of the same concentration. (2) The rate of decomposition of COCl2(g) is equal to the rate of formation of CO(g). (3) The equilibrium constant Kc for the reaction increases when the volume of the container increases.","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1400,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following equilibrium reaction system in a closed container of fixed volume: CO(g) + H2O(g) ⇌ CO2(g) + H2(g) ΔH < 0. Which of the following, when applied to the system, would lead to an increase in the rate of formation of H2? (1) adding CO(g) (2) increasing the temperature (3) adding a suitable catalyst","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1401,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"The following reaction has attained equilibrium in a fixed volume container: CO(g) + H2O(g) ⇌ CO2(g) + H2(g) ΔH = -41.1 kJ mol-1. Which of the following is correct if the temperature of the system is increased?","points":5,"options":["The pressure of the system remains unchanged.","Both the rates of forward and backward reaction increase.","The equilibrium constant of the reaction remains unchanged.","The respective yields of CO2(g) and H2(g) increase to the same extent."],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1402,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following equilibrium system: Br2(aq) + H2O(l) ⇌ HOBr(aq) + H+(aq) + Br-(aq). Which of the following can turn the colour of the system paler?","points":5,"options":["passing HCl(g) into the system","passing HBr(g) into the system","adding NaBr(s) to the system","adding NaOH(s) to the system"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1403,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"How many moles of Y(l) would be present in the container when equilibrium is attained? (缺少圖片，文件名: 圖表)","points":5,"options":["0.44","0.61","0.71","0.83"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1404,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"When equilibrium is attained, which of the following would increase the number of moles of Y(l)? (1) removing Z(l) from the reaction mixture (2) increasing the volume of the container (3) increasing the temperature of the reaction mixture","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1405,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following equilibrium system: 2CrO42-(aq) + 2H+(aq) ⇌ Cr2O72-(aq) + H2O(l). Which of the following statements are INCORRECT? (1) [CrO42-(aq)] must be equal to [Cr2O72-(aq)]. (2) Both the forward reaction and the backward reaction have stopped. (3) The number of moles of CrO42-(aq) must be double the number of moles of Cr2O72-(aq).","points":5,"options":["(1) and (2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only","(1), (2) and (3)"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1406,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"Consider the following equilibrium system in a certain liquid medium at 25°C: CH3COCH3 + HCN ⇌ (CH3)2C(OH)CN ΔH > 0. Which of the following statements is correct (assuming the total volume of the system remains unchanged)?","points":5,"options":["Adding (CH3)2C(OH)CN would increase the equilibrium constant Kc.","Increasing the temperature would increase the concentration of (CH3)2C(OH)CN.","The concentration of CH3COCH3 must be equal to the concentration of (CH3)2C(OH)CN.","After adding HCN and when a new equilibrium is attained, the concentration of HCN would be restored to the value before the addition of HCN."],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1407,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"choice","text":"The equilibrium constant Kc for the reaction N2O4(g) ⇌ 2NO2(g) at 70°C is 0.13 mol dm-3. In a 5.0 dm3 closed container kept at 70°C, there is a mixture of 0.20 mol of N2O4(g) and 0.30 mol of NO2(g) at a certain moment. Which of the following combinations is correct at that moment? Reaction quotient Qc / mol dm-3, Rate of the reaction","points":5,"options":["0.09, backward > forward","0.09, forward > backward","0.45, backward > forward","0.45, forward > backward"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1408,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: Carbon dioxide and silicon dioxide have similar physical properties. 2nd statement: The atoms of carbon and silicon have the same number of electrons in their outermost shells.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1409,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: The melting point of the non-metals in Period 3 of the Periodic Table decreases from sulphur to argon. 2nd statement: The relative atomic mass increases from sulphur to argon in Period 3 of the Periodic Table.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1410,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Silicon and carbon react to form silicon carbide. The crystal structure of silicon carbide is similar to that of diamond. Silicon carbide is very hard because","points":5,"options":["it has a high melting point.","silicon atoms and carbon atoms form triple bonds.","it has a giant network structure with strong covalent bonds.","both silicon and carbon atoms have four outermost shell electrons."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1411,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following oxides would form an acidic solution when added to water?","points":5,"options":["carbon dioxide","silicon dioxide","aluminium oxide","lithium oxide"],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1412,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Silicon is an element in Group IV of the Periodic Table. The oxide of silicon has the chemical formula SiO2. Which of the following statements about silicon and its oxide is correct?","points":5,"options":["Silicon is a good conductor of heat.","Silicon exists as simple molecules.","SiO2 is a hard material at room temperature.","SiO2 dissolves in water to give an acidic solution."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1413,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following is NOT a characteristic property of transition metals?","points":5,"options":["They form coloured compounds.","They exhibit variable oxidation numbers in their compounds.","They react with dilute hydrochloric acid to give hydrogen gas.","They exhibit catalytic property in elemental state or as compounds."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1414,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: Both aluminium oxide and magnesium oxide exhibit similar acid-base properties. 2nd statement: Both aluminium oxide and magnesium oxide are ionic oxides.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1415,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following graphs (not drawn to scale) correctly shows the variation in electrical conductivity of the elements in the third period of the Periodic Table at room temperature? (缺少圖片，文件名: 四幅圖)","points":5,"options":["A","B","C","D"],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1416,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: Aluminium oxide is soluble in water. 2nd statement: Aluminium oxide is an amphoteric oxide.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
// {"id":1417,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements concerning the Periodic Table is correct?","points":5,"options":["The melting point of the Group I elements increases down the group.","The boiling point of the Group VII elements increases down the group.","The elements are arranged in the order of increasing relative atomic mass.","The electrical conductivity of the third period elements increases from left to right."],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1418,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: The melting point of silicon is higher than that of aluminium. 2nd statement: The number of electrons in a silicon atom is greater than that in an aluminium atom.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1419,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following trends involving Na, Mg and Al is INCORRECT?","points":5,"options":["Melting point of metal : Al > Mg > Na","Electronegativity of metal : Al > Mg > Na","Metal reactivity with water : Na > Mg > Al","Base strength of metal oxide : Al2O3 > MgO > Na2O"],"answerLetter":"D"},
// {"id":1420,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: P4O10(s) can react with NaOH(aq). 2nd statement: P4O10(s) is an acidic oxide.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1421,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following graphs (not drawn to scale) shows the variation in melting points of the elements in the third period of the Periodic Table? (缺少圖片，文件名: 圖表)","points":5,"options":["A","B","C","D"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1422,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements concerning silicon dioxide solid is correct?","points":5,"options":["There are single covalent bonds between silicon atoms and oxygen atoms.","It is insoluble in sodium hydroxide solution.","It has a simple molecular structure.","It conducts electricity at room temperature."],"answerLetter":"A"},
// {"id":1423,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following statements is correct?","points":5,"options":["The boiling point of argon is lower than that of neon.","The boiling point of nitrogen is lower than that of oxygen.","The melting point of silicon is lower than that of sodium.","The melting point of aluminium is lower than that of magnesium."],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1424,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"Which of the following processes can illustrate the characteristics of transition metals? (1) mixing AgNO3(aq) and NaCl(aq) (2) mixing FeSO4(aq) and Br2(aq) (3) mixing CuSO4(s) and H2O(l)","points":5,"options":["(1) only","(2) only","(1) and (3) only","(2) and (3) only"],"answerLetter":"B"},
// {"id":1425,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"choice","text":"1st statement: The molar volume of bromine is larger than that of fluorine at room temperature and pressure. 2nd statement: The molecular size of bromine is larger than that of fluorine.","points":5,"options":["Both statements are true and the 2nd statement is a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","Both statements are true but the 2nd statement is NOT a correct explanation of the 1st statement.","The 1st statement is false but the 2nd statement is true.","Both statements are false."],"answerLetter":"C"},
//   {"id":1427,"subject":"化學","topic":"1. Planet Earth","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q7 (e) Suggest a test to show the presence of a potassium-containing compound in the fertiliser. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Flame test - gives a lilac flame."},
//   {"id":1428,"subject":"化學","topic":"1. Planet Earth","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q1 (b) Water is the most abundant compound on the Earth's surface. It is very important to life on Earth.<br>(b) Nearly 98% of the water on Earth is sea water, which is not fit for human consumption. The diagram below shows the set-up used in a simple distillation experiment for obtaining water from sea water. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：308,306,767,574）<br>(i) Outline the underlying principle of this simple distillation experiment.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Water boils at about 100°C, but the salts in sea water are non-volatile. The steam formed condenses on the cold surface of the condenser / cool down to give liquid water."},
//   {"id":1429,"subject":"化學","topic":"1. Planet Earth","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q1 (b) (ii) Insoluble solid S was placed into the flask before heating. Why?","points":30,"answerLetter":"To prevent bumping / to prevent frothing / splash / overflow due to overheating of water."},
//   {"id":1430,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"SP Q1 (a) State whether each of the following statements is true or false. Explain your answer in each case. (6 marks) (a) The melting point of sodium chloride is much higher than that of methane because the ionic bonding in sodium chloride is much stronger than the covalent bonding in methane.","points":30,"answerLetter":"False. Since the non-directional electrostatic attraction between Na+ and Cl- in NaCl is stronger than the weak van der Waals' force holding the methane molecules, the melting point of sodium chloride is much higher than that of methane. In fact, the covalent bonds between the atoms in methane molecules (C-C, C-H bonds) are stronger than the ionic bonds within sodium chloride lattices."},
//   {"id":1431,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"SP Q7 Complete the table below by (a) drawing a three-dimensional diagram for the structure of each solid substance, and (b) giving an explanation of whether the solid substance is an electrical conductor. (6 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：diamond and graphite structure diagrams）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Diamond would not conduct electricity since each carbon atom forms four covalent bonds with other carbon atoms, and all the valence electrons are localized in covalent bonds. There are no delocalized electrons or mobile ions to carry electric charge. Graphite would conduct electricity since carbon atoms in graphite only form three bonds with others. The unpaired electrons are delocalized within the layers of carbon atoms. The delocalized electrons are free to move from one 6-membered C ring to the next within a layer. The delocalized electrons can help to conduct electricity."},
//   {"id":1432,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"PP Q2 (a) Wine in an opened bottle will become unpalatable if left to stand for some time. Suggest why this is so. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Some components of wine (substances with a pleasant odour) can be oxidised by oxygen in air to give products that have a flat taste. / Ethanol in wine can be oxidised by oxygen in air to give ethanol / ethanoic acid."},
//   {"id":1433,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"PP Q2 (b) One common way of preserving wine in an opened bottle is to inject argon, a gas which is chemically unreactive, into the bottle and then stopper the bottle. (3 marks)<br>(i) Explain why argon is chemically unreactive.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The outermost shell of an argon atom is a stable octet structure. Ar does not readily form bonds with other atoms."},
//   {"id":1434,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"PP Q2 (b) (ii) State the principle behind the use of argon in preserving wine.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Ar is denser than air. It displaces air from the bottle, and thus prevents the wine from contact with air."},
//   {"id":1435,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"PP Q2 (b) (iii) Helium gas is also chemically unreactive. Suggest why helium is NOT used for preserving wine in an opened bottle.","points":30,"answerLetter":"He is less dense than air. It will not displace air / it will easily diffuse from the bottle."},
//   {"id":1436,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"PP Q2 (c) Another way of wine preservation involves pumping air out from an opened bottle of wine and then stopper the bottle. Suggest ONE possible drawback of preserving wine in this way. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The substances with a pleasant odour are volatile organic compounds. Pumping air out from the bottle may also remove these substances."},
//   {"id":1437,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"PP Q3 (a)(i) Nitrogen reacts with magnesium to give magnesium nitride (Mg3N2). (3 marks) (i) Draw the electron diagram of magnesium nitride, showing electrons in the outermost shells only. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Mg3N2 electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1438,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"PP Q3 (b)(i) Consider the nitrogen compound NCl3. (3 marks) (i) Draw the electron diagram of NCl3, showing electrons in the outermost shells only. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：NCl3 electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1439,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q1 (c) What is meant by the term 'isotope'? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Atoms with the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons. / Atoms with the same atomic number but different mass numbers."},
//   {"id":1440,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q1 (d) Calculate the relative atomic mass of neon. (2 marks) (Isotope abundance: 20Ne 90.48%, 21Ne 0.27%, 22Ne 9.25%)","points":30,"answerLetter":"20×0.9048 + 21×0.0027 + 22×0.0925 = 20.19"},
//   {"id":1441,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q1 (e) Give one daily application of neon. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Gas for filling luminous advertisement tubes / neon tubes / neon signs / neon lights."},
//   {"id":1442,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q1 (a) Water is the most abundant compound on the Earth's surface. It is very important to life on Earth. (a) Draw the electron diagram for a water molecule, showing electrons in the outermost shells only. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：water molecule electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1443,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q8 Both caesium (Cs) and sodium (Na) are elements in Group I of the Periodic Table. Caesium reacts with chlorine to form caesium chloride. (a) Write the chemical equation for the reaction of caesium with chlorine. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"2Cs + Cl2 → 2CsCl"},
//   {"id":1444,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q8 (b) Solid caesium chloride has a giant ionic structure. (3 marks) (i) Draw a diagram to show the structure of caesium chloride. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：CsCl structure diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1445,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q8 (b) (ii) Explain why solid caesium chloride is brittle. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"In CsCl, ions are strongly held by ionic bond. Relative movement of the ions can bring ions of the same charge close to each other, and will result in repulsion. So CsCl(s) is brittle."},
//   {"id":1446,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q8 (c) Predict, with ONE reason, whether sodium or caesium is more reactive towards chlorine. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cs(s) is more reactive than Na(s). The reactivity of Group 1 metals increases down the group. / The electron in the outermost shell of Cs is weakly bounded by the nucleus as compared with that of Na."},
//   {"id":1447,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q1 Graphite is a form of carbon and has a layer structure. Graphene is an individual single layer of graphite. (a) (i) Explain why graphene can be easily peeled off. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Layers of graphite are only held together by van der Waals' forces."},
//   {"id":1448,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q1 (a) (ii) Explain whether graphene can conduct electricity. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Graphene can conduct electricity because it has delocalised electrons."},
//   {"id":1449,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q1 (a) (iii) Draw the electron diagram for a molecule of the compound formed by complete combustion of graphene, showing electrons in the outermost shells only. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：CO2 electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1450,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q1 (b) Based on the fact that graphene can be easily peeled off from graphite, a student concluded that graphite should have a low melting point due to its layer structure. Explain whether you agree with this conclusion. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Not agree. Graphene layer has a giant covalent structure. / A large amount of energy is needed during melting to destroy the large amount of strong covalent bonds between atoms."},
//   {"id":1451,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q1 (c) Fullerene (such as C60) is another form of carbon. Briefly describe the structure of C60, and suggest why it is soluble in some organic solvents. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"C60 has a spherical structure. C60 has a simple molecular structure. The van der Waals' forces between C60 molecules are of comparable strength as those in molecules of organic solvents."},
//   {"id":1452,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q1 Argon and chlorine are elements in the same period of the Periodic Table. (a) Draw the electron diagram for a molecule of argon, showing electrons in all shells. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Ar atom electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1453,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q1 (b) What is the type of intermolecular force in chlorine gas? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Van der Waals' forces"},
//   {"id":1454,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q1 (c) Complete the table below by stating the natural source and the method of extraction from the source for each element. (4 marks)<br>Argon: Natural source - The atmosphere / Air; Method of extraction - Fractional distillation of liquefied air.<br>Chlorine: Natural source - Rock salt / Sea water / Ocean; Method of extraction - Electrolysis of sea water.","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1455,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q1 (a) Refer to the following information of phosphorus (P) and chlorine (Cl). (P: atomic number 15, relative atomic mass 31.0; Cl: atomic number 17, relative atomic mass 35.5) State the electronic arrangement of a phosphorus atom. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"2,8,5"},
//   {"id":1456,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q1 (b) All chlorine atoms have the same atomic number. Explain why some chlorine atoms have different mass numbers. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Chlorine exists as isotopes. / There are chlorine atoms with same number of protons but different number of neutrons. / All chlorine atoms have 17 protons. Some chlorine atoms have 18 neutrons and some have 20."},
//   {"id":1457,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q1 (a) Barium (Ba) is an element in Group II of the Periodic Table. Its chemical properties are similar to those of calcium. (a) Describe the bonding in barium. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"It is the metallic bond between delocalised electrons and barium ions."},
//   {"id":1458,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q3 (c) Describe the formation of dative covalent bond using H3O+ as example. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The O atom in H2O has lone pairs of electrons. H+ does not have electrons in its outermost shell. Dative covalent bond formed between the O atom in H2O and H+ by sharing electron pair."},
//   {"id":1459,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q1 (a) Lithium occurs naturally in two isotopes, 6Li and 7Li. It can form lithium nitride (Li3N) when burnt in air. (a) (3 marks) (i) Calculate the percentage abundance of 6Li in nature. (Relative atomic mass: Li = 6.9)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Let x be the abundance of 6Li in nature. 6.0x + 7.0(1-x) = 6.9, x = 0.1. Percentage abundance of 6Li in nature is 10%."},
//   {"id":1460,"subject":"化學","topic":"2. Microscopic World I","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q1 (a) (ii) Draw the electron diagram for lithium nitride, showing electrons in the outermost shells only. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Li3N electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1461,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"SP Q3 X, Y and Z are three different metals. The table below lists the results of three experiments carried out using the metals or their oxides. (7 marks)<br>(a) What is the colourless gas formed when X is added to cold water? Suggest a test for the gas.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Hydrogen gas was formed when X is added to cold water. The gas gives a 'pop' sound when a burning splint is applied."},
//   {"id":1462,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"SP Q3 (b) Name the type of reaction that occurs when the oxide of Y is heated with carbon powder.","points":30,"answerLetter":"redox reaction"},
//   {"id":1463,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"SP Q3 (c) Arrange the three metals in order of increasing reactivity. Explain your answer.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Increasing reactivity: Z < Y < X. Only metal X among the three can react with cold water to give hydrogen gas, therefore only X is at a higher position than hydrogen in the electrochemical series. Also, only metal X cannot be reduced by carbon, so it is the most reactive one among the three. Metal Y undergoes displacement reaction with copper(II) sulphate, so Y is a stronger reducing agent than copper. It is at a position higher than that of copper in the electrochemical series. Since metal Z cannot displace the copper(II) ions, so metal Z is at a position lower than copper in the electrochemical series."},
//   {"id":1464,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"SP Q3 (d) Why is a colourless gas formed when X is added to copper(II) sulphate solution?","points":30,"answerLetter":"There are water molecules H2O(l) in the copper(II) sulphate solution. X reacts with water to give colourless hydrogen gas."},
//   {"id":1465,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q5 (a) In order to prepare 50 dm3 of 0.1 M CuSO4(aq), an inexperienced electroplating worker added the required exact amount of CuSO4·5H2O(s) to water in a plastic container. He then stirred the mixture with an iron rod until the CuSO4·5H2O(s) dissolved completely. Finally, he sent a sample of the solution to the Quality Control Laboratory for analysis, but found that the concentration of CuSO4(aq) was lower than 0.1 M. (a) With the aid of a chemical equation, explain why the concentration of the CuSO4(aq) prepared was lower than 0.1 M. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Displacement reaction occurs when the iron rod is dipped into the copper(II) sulphate solution. Some copper(II) ions are reduced to copper metal and deposited onto the surface of the iron rod. Cu2+(aq) + Fe(s) → Cu(s) + Fe2+(aq) / CuSO4(aq) + Fe(s) → Cu(s) + FeSO4(aq)"},
//   {"id":1466,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q9 The diagram below shows an experimental set-up for investigating the factors affecting rusting. (a) What would be observed if an iron nail in the above set-up rusts? (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：rusting experiment set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Blue colouration would be observed near the iron nail which rusts."},
//   {"id":1467,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q9 (b) Suggest which of the iron nails in the above set-up would NOT rust during the experiment. Explain your answer. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Both iron nail B and iron nail C would not rust. For iron nail B, as Mg is higher than iron in the metal reactivity series, the magnesium ribbon protects the iron nail from rusting by sacrificial protection. For iron nail C, as it is sealed with grease and cannot contact with water and air (oxygen), so rusting cannot occur."},
//   {"id":1468,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q7 (a) Thermite reactions broadly refer to exothermic oxidation-reduction reactions between a metal powder and a metal oxide. (a) (i) Complete and balance the chemical equation for the following thermite reaction: Fe2O3(s) + Al(s) → Fe(l) + Al2O3(s) (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Fe2O3(s) + 2Al(s) → 2Fe(l) + Al2O3(s)"},
//   {"id":1469,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q7 (b) Copper powder CANNOT be used to replace aluminium powder in carrying out the thermite reaction with iron(III) oxide. Explain why. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Copper is less reactive than iron / copper has a lower affinity for oxygen than iron. / Copper is a weaker reducing agent than iron. / Copper is lower than iron in the chemical reactivity series. So Cu(s) cannot reduce Fe2O3(s)."},
//   {"id":1470,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q7 (c) The extraction of iron from its ores also involves the reduction of iron oxides. (2 marks) (i) Suggest why aluminium is NOT used as the reducing agent in iron extraction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Aluminium is more expensive than iron."},
//   {"id":1471,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q7 (c) (ii) Suggest ONE reducing agent commonly used in iron extraction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Coke / Carbon / Charcoal / Carbon monoxide / CO"},
//   {"id":1472,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q4* With reference to the methods of obtaining copper, magnesium and silver from their oxides, deduce the order of reactivity of these three metals. (5 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Silver can be obtained by heating oxide of silver directly, while copper and magnesium cannot be obtained by similar method. By heating with charcoal, oxide of copper can be reduced to copper, while magnesium cannot be obtained by similar method. Magnesium can only be obtained by electrolysis of its oxide in molten state. As more stable is the metal oxide, the more reactive is the metal. So, the order of reactivity is: magnesium > copper > silver."},
//   {"id":1473,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q3 Aluminium and iron are commonly used construction materials. (a) Suggest why iron was used earlier than aluminium in history. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Iron is less reactive than aluminium."},
//   {"id":1474,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q3 (b) A compound contains iron and oxygen only. In an experiment for determining the empirical formula of this compound, 2.31 g of the compound was heated with carbon monoxide. Upon complete reaction, carbon dioxide and 1.67 g of iron were formed. (4 marks) (i) Calculate the empirical formula of this compound.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Mass of O = 2.31 - 1.67 = 0.64 g. Moles Fe = 1.67/55.8 = 0.03, moles O = 0.64/16 = 0.04. Fe : O = 0.03 : 0.04 = 3 : 4. Empirical formula = Fe3O4."},
//   {"id":1475,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q3 (b) (ii) Write the chemical equation for the reaction involved in the experiment.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Fe3O4(s) + 4CO(g) → 3Fe(s) + 4CO2(g)"},
//   {"id":1476,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q3 (b) (iii) As carbon monoxide is poisonous, suggest one necessary safety precaution in carrying out the experiment.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Perform the experiment in a fume cupboard."},
//   {"id":1477,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q3 (c) Explain why a galvanised iron object does not easily rust even if the zinc layer is broken. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Zn is more reactive / a stronger reducing agent than Fe. For galvanised iron object with the zinc layer broken, iron will be protected from corrosion as zinc will be preferentially oxidised."},
//   {"id":1478,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q3 (d) Explain why anodisation can prevent aluminium objects from corrosion. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The surface of the aluminium object is oxidised to Al2O3(s) / aluminium oxide. Al2O3(s) is impermeable to water / oxygen, thus corrosion of aluminium is inhibited."},
//   {"id":1479,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q1 (c) A compound of phosphorus and chlorine has a relative molecular mass smaller than 250. It contains 22.6% of phosphorus by mass. (3 marks) (i) Deduce the molecular formula of the compound.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Moles P : Cl = (22.6/31) : (77.4/35.5) = 0.729 : 2.18 = 1 : 3. Empirical formula = PCl3. (31+35.5×3)n < 250, 137.5n < 250, n < 1.818, n=1. Molecular formula is PCl3."},
//   {"id":1480,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q1 (c) (ii) Draw the electron diagram for the compound, showing electrons in the outermost shells only. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：PCl3 electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1481,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q2 The set-up of an experiment for studying the movement of ions is shown below. (a) Explain why the filter paper is soaked with K2SO4(aq) instead of water. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：ion movement experiment set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"To increase the electrical conductivity of the filter paper / To increase the number of mobile ions / To provide mobile ions / K2SO4(aq) is an electrolyte / Allow ions to pass through / K2SO4(aq) acts as a salt bridge."},
//   {"id":1482,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q2 (b) State the colour of FeSO4(aq). (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"pale green / green / light green"},
//   {"id":1483,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q2 (c) Explain what would be observed around the middle of the filter paper when the circuit is closed for a period of time. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Dark blue colour appears around the middle of the filter paper. Fe2+(aq) ions move towards negative pole / move to the right and Fe(CN)63-(aq) ions move towards positive pole / move to the left, forming a blue compound."},
//   {"id":1484,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q2 (d) The experiment is repeated, but the two poles of the cell have been reversed at the very beginning. Explain what would be observed around the middle of the filter paper when the circuit is closed for a period of time. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The colour around the middle of the filter paper remains unchanged / white / colourless. Fe2+(aq) ions and Fe(CN)63-(aq) ions do not migrate towards each other. / Fe2+(aq) ions and Fe(CN)63-(aq) ions move to opposite sides. / K+(aq) and SO42-(aq) migrate towards each other but do not form coloured compounds."},
//   {"id":1485,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q2 (a) Water pipes used to carry drinking water are commonly made of copper instead of iron. Although lead-containing solder can be used to join these water pipes, such use is prohibited. (a) Suggest one chemical property of copper that makes it more suitable than iron for making water pipes. Explain your answer. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Copper is not so easily oxidised / corroded as iron. Copper has a lower tendency to lose electrons than iron."},
//   {"id":1486,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q2 (b) (i) Suggest one reason of adding lead to soldering materials. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"It is to lower the melting point of soldering materials."},
//   {"id":1487,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q2 (b) (ii) Explain why lead-containing solder is prohibited in making these water pipes. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Lead is / Compounds of lead are toxic / poisonous."},
//   {"id":1488,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q1 (b) Lithium occurs naturally in two isotopes, 6Li and 7Li. It can form lithium nitride (Li3N) when burnt in air. (b) In an experiment, 1.25 g of lithium nitride is formed when a piece of lithium is burnt in air. (3 marks) (i) Write a chemical equation for the reaction involved.","points":30,"answerLetter":"6Li + N2 → 2Li3N"},
//   {"id":1489,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q1 (b) (ii) Calculate the mass of lithium that reacted with nitrogen. (Relative atomic masses: Li = 6.9, N = 14.0)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Let y g be the mass of lithium that reacted with nitrogen. y/6.9 = 3 × (1.25/34.7), y = 0.746 g."},
//   {"id":1490,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q1 (c) Name another compound which will also be formed when lithium is burnt in air. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Lithium oxide / Lithium peroxide"},
//   {"id":1491,"subject":"化學","topic":"3. Metals","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q5 (b) Electroplating and rust prevention are common applications of electrochemistry. (b) Suggest a method, besides painting or electroplating, that can prevent underground iron-made pipelines from rusting. Explain your answer. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Connect zinc/magnesium blocks (through connecting wires) to the surface of the pipelines. / Sacrificial protection. Zinc/Magnesium can release electrons more readily than iron. / Zinc/Magnesium is more reactive than iron. / Zinc/Magnesium has greater reducing power than iron. / Zinc/Magnesium is higher than iron in the ECS. OR Connect the negative electrode of a D.C. source (through connecting wires) to the surface of the pipelines (and the positive electrode to a platinum electrode) / Cathodic protection. The electrons provided by the D.C. source prevent iron from releasing electrons."},
//   {"id":1492,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"SP Q2 Polyethene is used in making shopping bags and its monomer is ethene. (6 marks) (a) Draw the electronic diagram of ethene, showing electrons in the outermost shells only. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：ethene electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1493,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"SP Q2 (b) Name the type of polymerisation involved in the production of polyethylene. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"addition polymerization"},
//   {"id":1494,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"SP Q2 (c) State ONE property of polyethylene that makes it suitable for making shopping bags. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Polyethene is flexible. / Polyethene is light. / Polyethene is chemically unreactive. / Polyethene is water-proof. / Polyethene has a high tensile strength. / Polyethene has a low density."},
//   {"id":1495,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"SP Q2 (d) (i) Suggest ONE way to dispose of polyethylene wastes. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Landfilling / Incineration / Recycling"},
//   {"id":1496,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"SP Q2 (d) (ii) Give ONE advantage and ONE disadvantage of the way you have suggested in (i). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"For landfilling: Advantage - It is simple. / The cost is low. / Landfilling does not produce toxic gases which causes air pollution. / Methane produced can be used to generate power. Disadvantage - Most plastics are non-biodegradable and chemically inert. They cannot be decomposed even for hundreds of years. / It is impractical when there is a shortage of landfill site. / Underground water may also be polluted. For incineration: Advantage - Incineration can greatly reduce the volume of wastes. / Requires less land for landfill. Disadvantage - Burning of polyethene produces carbon dioxide causing greenhouse effect. / Incomplete combustion of polyethene produces carbon particles, carbon monoxide, particulates and unburned hydrocarbons as air pollutants. For recycling: Advantage - Saves resources like petroleum. / Reduces the volume of solid waste. / Less air pollutants are produced. Disadvantage - Sorting out different plastics is time-consuming. / It involves a high transport cost."},
//   {"id":1497,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"SP Q12 Ethyl ethanoate is an ester. It can be prepared by heating a mixture of ethanoic acid and ethanol under reflux in the presence of a catalyst. (8 marks) (a) What is the catalyst used in the preparation? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Concentrated sulphuric acid."},
//   {"id":1498,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"SP Q12 (b) Draw a labelled diagram of the set-up used for heating the mixture under reflux. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：reflux set-up diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1499,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"SP Q13 Outline a synthetic route, in not more than three steps, to accomplish each of the following conversions. For each step, give the reagent(s), the conditions and the structure of the organic product. (6 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：conversion schemes）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1500,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q5 The fuel used in the torch for the Beijing 2008 Olympic Games was an alkane X with the following composition by mass: C, 81.8%; H, 18.2%. (a) Deduce what X could be. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"C : H = (81.8/12) : (18.2/1) = 6.82 : 18.2 = 3 : 8. Alkane has the general formula CnH2n+2. X is propane / C3H8."},
//   {"id":1501,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q5 (b) Suggest an industrial process for obtaining X. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Fractional distillation of the petroleum gaseous fraction. / Cracking of naphtha / heavy oil (or any appropriate petroleum fraction) followed by fractional distillation of the products."},
//   {"id":1502,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q5 (c) Kerosene was once used as a fuel for the Olympic torch. State ONE advantage of using each of the following substances as fuel for the torch. (2 marks) (i) X","points":30,"answerLetter":"X: C3H8 easily undergoes complete combustion to give CO2 and H2O. The products pose little harm to the environment."},
//   {"id":1503,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q5 (c) (ii) kerosene","points":30,"answerLetter":"Kerosene: kerosene undergoes incomplete combustion to give a luminous flame. The flame can be more easily seen."},
//   {"id":1504,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q6 The table below lists some information about six hydroxy compounds A,B,C,D,E and F. (a) Give the systematic name of E. (1 mark) (E = HOCH2CH2CH2OH)","points":30,"answerLetter":"propane-1,3-diol / 1,3-propanediol"},
//   {"id":1505,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q6 (b) Account for the variation in boiling points of A, B and C. (2 marks) (A: CH3OH, B: CH3CH2OH, C: CH3CH2CH2OH)","points":30,"answerLetter":"All three compounds have a hydroxyl group / are monohydric alcohols. The boiling point of these compounds depends on the strength of van der Waals forces between molecules. The strength of van der Waals forces in alcohols increases with the carbon chain length / molecular size. Boiling point increases in the order: A < B < C."},
//   {"id":1506,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q6 (c) Explain why the density of C is greater than that of D. (2 marks) (C: CH3CH2CH2OH, D: CH3CH(OH)CH3)","points":30,"answerLetter":"For isomeric compounds with the same functional group, the strength of intermolecular force is affected by the shape of the molecules. The structure of CH3CH2CH2OH allows the molecules to have a greater area of contact than those of CH3CH(OH)CH3. CH3CH2CH2OH has a greater density. / The structure of CH3CH(OH)CH3 makes the formation of H-bonds less effective. CH3CH(OH)CH3 has a smaller density."},
//   {"id":1507,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q6 (d) Three identical steel balls are added separately to three identical vertical glass tubes each containing the same volume of D, E and F as shown in the diagram. In which tube will the steel ball take the longest time to reach the bottom? Explain your answer. (You are required to consider the intermolecular attraction forces involved.) (4 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：steel ball diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"F. The rate at which the steel balls drop depends on the viscosity of the liquid / the resistance (frictional force) experienced by the ball. This is related to the intermolecular attraction of the liquids. In the three compounds, the intermolecular attraction is predominately H-bond. The no. of H-bonds formed per molecule is 1 in D, 2 in E and 3 in F. / F forms the greatest number of hydrogen bonds per molecule. : F is the most viscous and the ball will drop most slowly. / F has the highest b.p. among the three compounds. Its intermolecular attraction is strongest. : The ball will drop most slowly in F."},
//   {"id":1508,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q11 Outline a synthetic route, with no more than three steps, to accomplish the following conversion. For each step, give the reagent(s), reaction conditions and structure of the organic product. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：conversion scheme）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) LiAlH4/ether; (2) H3O+; (3) excess conc. H3PO4 (or conc. H2SO4); heat / Al2O3(s); heat"},
//   {"id":1509,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q12 The structural formula shown below can represent two compounds with the same melting point and same solubility in water. (a) (3 marks) (i) Draw a three-dimensional structure for each of the two compounds.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：enantiomers structures）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1510,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q12 (a) (ii) State ONE difference in physical properties of these compounds. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"They turn the plane of polarisation of a beam of plane polarised light in opposite directions. / One of the compounds is leavorotatory while the other is dextrorotatory. / Crystals of the two compounds have different appearance."},
//   {"id":1511,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"PP Q12 (b) Both compounds can undergo polymerisation under suitable conditions. Draw the repeating unit of the polymer formed from one of these compounds. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：polymer repeating unit）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1512,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q2 Poly(ethenyl ethanoate) is a polymer. Its monomer is ethenyl ethanoate. (a) Ethene is the raw material used in making ethenyl ethanoate. Ethene can be produced from hydrocarbons of higher molecular mass by an important industrial process. (2 marks) (i) Name this industrial process.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cracking. / Catalytic cracking. / Thermal cracking."},
//   {"id":1513,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q2 (a) (ii) Explain why this process is important.","points":30,"answerLetter":"This process can produce small molecules from large hydrocarbons to meet the industrial demand."},
//   {"id":1514,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q2 (b) Draw the structure of poly(ethenyl ethanoate). (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：poly(ethenyl ethanoate) structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1515,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q2 (c) (i) Draw the structure of ethyl ethanoate. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：ethyl ethanoate structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1516,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q2 (c) (ii) Suggest a chemical test to show how to distinguish between ethenyl ethanoate and ethyl ethanoate. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Bromine test - ethenyl ethanoate can decolourise orange bromine solution immediately while ethyl ethanoate cannot. / Acidified potassium permanganate solution test - ethenyl ethanoate can decolourise purple acidified potassium permanganate solution while ethyl ethanoate cannot."},
//   {"id":1517,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q10 Suggest THREE measures for reducing the emission of air pollutants upon using fossil fuels. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Install catalytic converters in car. / Use unleaded petrol. / Replace diesel with LPG for vehicles. / Use LPG for vehicles/mini-bus/bus/taxi. / Install scrubbers in power plant. / Using Ultra Low Sulphur Diesel. / Use electrostatic precipitator."},
//   {"id":1518,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q12 Cinnamon, which can be used as flavouring, contains cinnamaldehyde (C9H8O). (a) Draw the trans-isomer for the above structure. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：trans-cinnamaldehyde structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1519,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q12 (b) Explain why ethyl ethanoate is a better solvent than water for dissolving cinnamaldehyde. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cinnamaldehyde is a non-polar compound which can dissolve in a relatively non-polar organic solvent like ethyl ethanoate. However, water is a polar solvent. / Both cinnamaldehyde and ethyl ethanoate are relatively non-polar compounds. Their molecules can be attracted by weak intermolecular forces."},
//   {"id":1520,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q12 (c) In an experiment to extract cinnamaldehyde from cinnamon, a solution containing only ethyl ethanoate and cinnamaldehyde is obtained after a series of steps. In order to separate these two compounds, simple distillation can be carried out. Draw a diagram for the set-up involved, and label the name of the distillate collected. (Boiling points: cinnamaldehyde = 248°C, ethyl ethanoate = 77°C) (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：simple distillation set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1521,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q12 (d) Outline a synthetic route, with no more than three steps, to accomplish the following conversion. For each step, give the reagent(s), reaction conditions (as appropriate) and the structure of the organic product. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：conversion scheme）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1522,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q14 The diagram below shows the conversion of an oil molecule X to a fat molecule Y. (a) (2 marks) (i) Given that all alkyl groups in both X and Y are straight chains, label the chiral carbon(s) by using ★ in the above diagram. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：X and Y structures）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1523,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q14 (a) (ii) With reference to (i), explain whether a change in optical activity is involved in the above diagram. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Yes. X has one chiral carbon and hence optically active, while Y does not has chiral carbons and hence optically inactive. Thus, there is a change in optical activity for the conversion."},
//   {"id":1524,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q14 (b) One of the products in the alkaline hydrolysis of Y has a cleansing property. Explain the cleansing property of this product. (4 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The C17H35COO- ion has an ionic head (COO-) and a hydrocarbon tail (C17H35). The hydrocarbon tail dissolves in grease droplets / is hydrophobic, while the ionic head dissolves in water / is hydrophilic. The ionic heads of the grease droplets repel from each other and the dints inside these droplets are then removed."},
//   {"id":1525,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q15 Use electron diagrams to illustrate, step by step, how CH4 reacts with Br2 under sunlight to form CH3Br. (Show electrons in the outermost shells only.) (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：electron diagrams for free radical substitution）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1526,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q3 Compound W contains carbon, hydrogen and oxygen only. The relative molecular mass of W is 88.0. Complete combustion of 1.32 g of W gives 2.64 g of carbon dioxide and 1.08 g of water. (a) Deduce the molecular formula of W. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Mass of C = 2.64 × (12/44) = 0.72 g; mass of H = 1.08 × (2/18) = 0.12 g; mass of O = 1.32 - 0.72 - 0.12 = 0.48 g. Mole ratio C : H : O = (0.72/12) : (0.12/1) : (0.48/16) = 0.06 : 0.12 : 0.03 = 2 : 4 : 1. Empirical formula = C2H4O. n × (24+4+16) = 88, n = 2. Molecular formula = C4H8O2."},
//   {"id":1527,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q3 (b) Given that W has only one functional group, draw TWO possible structures of W. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：two possible structures of C4H8O2）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1528,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q4 (a) The structure of a dibasic acid with chemical formula H2C2O4 is shown. (a) Give the systematic name of this dibasic acid. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：oxalic acid structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Ethanedioic acid."},
//   {"id":1529,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q6* Briefly describe how polypropene can be produced from naphtha. (4 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cracking of naphtha gives a mixture of hydrocarbons which include propene. Fractional distillation of the gaseous products can separate propene from other hydrocarbons. Polymerisation of propene at elevated temperatures / >45°C, high pressure / >5 atm / in the presence of a suitable catalyst / Ziegler-Natta catalyst gives polypropylene."},
//   {"id":1530,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q14 An unsaturated fat F is a component of a vegetable oil. (a) State the reagents needed for converting F to a saturated fat. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：F structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"H2, Ni / Pd / Pt"},
//   {"id":1531,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q14 (b) (i) Write the chemical equation involved for the formation of soap from F. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：saponification equation）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1532,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q14 (b) (ii) In the presence of an acid, the soap formed in (i) can react with methanol to give compound G, which can be used as a biodiesel. Draw the structure of G. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：biodiesel structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1533,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q14 (c) With reference to their relative molecular masses and physical properties, explain why G can be used as a fuel for cars, but F cannot. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"G has a smaller relative molecular mass than F, so G can be vaporized more easily than F. G has a smaller relative molecular mass than F, and so the molecular size of G is smaller than that of F. The intermolecular attraction / van der Waals' forces between G are weaker than that between F, G can be vaporized more easily than F. G burns more completely than F."},
//   {"id":1534,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q15 Consider the conversions of organic compounds shown below. (a) Suggest a chemical test to distinguish between X and Y. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：conversion scheme）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add acidified K2Cr2O7: X – no change; Y – from orange to green. / Add acidified KMnO4: X – no change; Y – from purple to colourless. / Add 2,4-DNP: X – formation of orange precipitate; Y – no change. / Add CH3COOH/H+/heat: X – no change; Y – fruity smell substance formed."},
//   {"id":1535,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q15 (b) Suggest what reagent R might be. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"LiAlH4 / NaBH4"},
//   {"id":1536,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q15 (c) The mixture Z contains two alkenes with the same structural formula. Draw the respective structures of these two alkenes, and state their isomeric relationship. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：geometric isomers）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Geometrical isomerism / cis/trans-isomerism."},
//   {"id":1537,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q15 (d) The alkenes in (c) can react with HCl to form an optically active chloroalkane. Write the structural formula of this chloroalkane. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：optically active chloroalkane）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1538,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q3 Both polyethene (PE) and 'Saran' can be used to make food wrap, but 'Saran' is more suitable than PE in making food wrap for use in microwave ovens. (a) The monomer of PE is ethene. Suggest a chemical test to show that ethene is an unsaturated compound. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add Br2(aq) / acidified KMnO4(aq) / neutral or alkaline KMnO4(aq). Reddish brown Br2(aq) decolourised / Purple KMnO4(aq) decolourised / Purple KMnO4(aq) turns brown."},
//   {"id":1539,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q3 (b) 'Saran' can be formed from the polymerisation of the compound shown below. (3 marks) (i) State the systematic name of this compound. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：1,1-dichloroethene structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"1,1-dichloroethene"},
//   {"id":1540,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q3 (b) (ii) Name the type of polymerisation involved in forming 'Saran'. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"addition polymerization"},
//   {"id":1541,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q3 (b) (iii) Draw the structure of 'Saran', showing at least THREE repeating units. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Saran polymer structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1542,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q3 (c) In terms of intermolecular force, explain why 'Saran' is more suitable than PE in making food wrap for use in microwave ovens. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Saran' is more heat resistant. It is because the polar attraction force between 'Saran' polymer chains is stronger than that between PE."},
//   {"id":1543,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q3 (d) When incinerated, why would food wrap made from 'Saran' cause more serious pollution problem than food wrap made from PE? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Incineration of food wrap made from 'Saran' will produce toxic gases while that made from PE will not."},
//   {"id":1544,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q6 (a) Petrol is a commonly used motor car fuel. It can be obtained from petroleum by fractional distillation. (a) (5 marks) (i) Explain, from molecular level, why petrol can be obtained from petroleum by fractional distillation. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Components having different boiling points can be separated from each other by fractional distillation. The longer the carbon chain, the higher is the boiling point."},
//   {"id":1545,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q6 (a) (ii) Other than directly obtaining petrol from fractional distillation of petroleum, suggest a way for producing extra petrol. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cracking of heavy oil / heavy hydrocarbons"},
//   {"id":1546,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q6 (b) Motor cars powered by petrol emit air pollutants such as nitrogen monoxide and carbon monoxide. Installing a certain device in motor cars can convert these two oxides to less harmful substances. (4 marks) (i) Name this device. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Catalytic converter"},
//   {"id":1547,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q12 Benzamide, benzoic acid and benzyl bromide are commonly used organic compounds. (a) In an experiment, benzoic acid is prepared from benzamide in two steps. (5 marks) (i) Name the type of reaction involved in Step 1. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"alkaline hydrolysis"},
//   {"id":1548,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q12 (a) (ii) Draw the structure of X. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：sodium benzoate structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1549,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q12 (a) (iii) Suggest what Y would be. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"HCl(aq) / H2SO4(aq)"},
//   {"id":1550,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q12 (a) (iv) Suggest why X is more soluble than benzoic acid in water. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"X (sodium benzoate) is an ionic compound which has stronger interactions with water. / Benzoic acid exists as molecules which have weaker intermolecular interactions with water. / X is an ionic compound while benzoic acid exists as molecules."},
//   {"id":1551,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q12 (a) (v) Describe briefly how a dry benzoic acid sample can be obtained after Step 2. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Filter the mixture to obtain the solid benzoic acid. Wash it with deionised water and then dry in oven."},
//   {"id":1552,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q14 Butter contains a small amount of the triglyceride of butanoic acid. (a) Draw the structure of the triglyceride of butanoic acid. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：tributyrin structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1553,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q14 (b) An organic acid Q is an isomer of butanoic acid. State the systematic name of Q. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"methylpropanoic acid"},
//   {"id":1554,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q14 (c) The structure of Z, another isomer of butanoic acid, is shown. (3 marks) (i) Using ★, label ALL chiral centre(s) in the above structure of Z. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Z structure with chiral centre）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1555,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q14 (c) (ii) Suggest a chemical test to show how to distinguish between Q and Z. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add acidified K2Cr2O7: Q – no change; Z – from orange to green. / Add acidified KMnO4: Q – no change; Z – from purple to colourless. / Add 2,4-DNP: Q – no change; Z – formation of orange ppt. / Add CH3CH2OH/H+/heat: Q – fruity smell compound formed; Z – no change. / Add CO32-: Q – formation of gas (CO2); Z – no change."},
//   {"id":1556,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q14 (d) Margarine, a butter substitute, can be made from vegetable oils. What chemical reaction is involved in the production of margarine from vegetable oils? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"hydrogenation / addition of hydrogen"},
//   {"id":1557,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q6 The steps involved in the reaction of methane with bromine forming CH3Br can be shown by the following diagram. Only electrons in the outermost shells are shown. (a) Name the type of the reaction for the formation of CH3Br from methane and bromine. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"substitution reaction"},
//   {"id":1558,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q6 (b) State the condition needed for the reaction to occur. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Light / hv / ultra-violet / UV / heat / radical initiator"},
//   {"id":1559,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q6 (c) State the expected observation for the reaction. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Orange / brown colour fades away. / Orange / brown colour changes to colourless slowly."},
//   {"id":1560,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q6 (d) With reference to its electronic structure, explain why the species Br has a high reactivity. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Br atom does not have the stable noble gas electronic configuration. / Br atom does not have the stable octet electronic configuration. / The electronic configuration of Br atom does not fulfill the octet rule."},
//   {"id":1561,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q6 (e) The reaction of methane with bromine can also form other single-carbon-containing organic compounds. (2 marks) (i) Suggest one such compound.","points":30,"answerLetter":"CH2Br2 / CHBr3 / CBr4"},
//   {"id":1562,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q6 (e) (ii) Suggest a condition so that the reaction of methane with bromine can form more CH3Br but less other organic compounds. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Use large excess amount of CH4 / Br2 is the limiting reactant."},
//   {"id":1563,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q8 (a) Natural gas is an important energy source for electricity generation. It contains mainly methane CH4. (a) Write the general formula of the molecules in the homologous series that methane belongs to. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"CnH2n+2"},
//   {"id":1564,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q8 (c) Some regions tend to generate electricity more by natural gas but less by coal. Give TWO reasons from environmental protection consideration. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Natural gas burns more completely but coal does not. / Burning coal would produce soot / carbon monoxide but burning natural gas would not. Compared with natural gas, coal contains more impurities. / Burning coal would produce more pollutants, such as SO2, metal compound dust."},
//   {"id":1565,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q12 You are provided with , inorganic reagents and organic solvents. Outline a synthetic route, with no more than three steps, to obtain the following compound. For each step, give the reagent(s), reaction conditions (as appropriate) and structure of the organic product. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：synthetic route）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1566,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q13* Using C2H5CH(OH)CH3 as an example, write a paragraph to illustrate 'enantiomerism'. Suitable diagram(s) should be included in your answer. (5 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：enantiomers diagrams）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Enantiomerism is a type of stereoisomerism, i.e. isomerism due to the difference in spatial arrangement, which is generally caused by the presence of one or more chiral centres, i.e. an atom in the molecule which has at least 4 different substituents, in a molecule. Such kind of molecules will result in a pair of isomers known as enantiomers, which are mirror images of each other, and they are non-superimposable. The above properties of a pair of enantiomers lead to optical activity of rotating the plane of polarization of plane-polarized light."},
//   {"id":1567,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q3 The diagram below shows an experimental set-up in which the glass wool soaked with octane is heated occasionally and the broken unglazed porcelain is heated strongly. Some gases are collected in the test tube over water. (a) Name the type of reaction that occurs in the boiling tube. Suggest one importance of this type of reaction in industry. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：cracking apparatus）","points":30,"answerLetter":"cracking. To produce petrol / to produce alkenes / to produce smaller hydrocarbons from larger hydrocarbons / to convert heavy oil to petrol."},
//   {"id":1568,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q3 (b) Explain why, instead of a large piece of unglazed porcelain, broken unglazed porcelain is used in this experiment. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The reaction will be faster when using broken unglazed porcelain instead of a large piece of unglazed porcelain due to larger surface area."},
//   {"id":1569,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q3 (c) Suppose that during the experiment, octane changes to ethane gas and propene gas only and they can be collected in the test tube. (3 marks) (i) Write the balanced equation for the reaction of changing octane to ethane and propene.","points":30,"answerLetter":"C8H18 → C2H6 + 2CH3CH=CH2 / C8H18 → C2H6 + 2C3H6"},
//   {"id":1570,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q3 (c) (ii) The gases collected in the test tube are shaken thoroughly with a few drops of Br2 (in CH3CCl3) solution. (1) State the expected observation.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Orange / (reddish) brown Br2 solution turns to colourless / decolorises."},
//   {"id":1571,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q3 (c) (ii) (2) Draw the structure of the product formed from the reaction between propene and Br2. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：1,2-dibromopropane structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1572,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q3 (d) When no more gas can be collected, what should be done to end the experiment for safety consideration? Explain your answer. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The delivery tube should be taken out of the water level before removing the heating source, otherwise sucking back will happen / the boiling tube will be cracked."},
//   {"id":1573,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q5 Polymer B shown below can be used as water absorbing material in diapers. It can be formed from the polymerisation of compound A. (a) Draw the structure of compound A and state its systematic name. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：polymer B and monomer A structures）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1574,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q5 (b) State the type of polymerisation for the formation of B from A. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Addition"},
//   {"id":1575,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q5 (c) Suggest why the relative molecular mass of B is expressed using a range of values instead of a single fixed value. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"B is a mixture of polymer molecules with different lengths. / Polymer molecules are of different length / carbon chains / n values."},
//   {"id":1576,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q5 (d) It is known that the reaction of polymer B with NaOH(aq) forms polymer C which can absorb water better. Draw the structure of C. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：polymer C structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1577,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q6 (a) Citric acid is a tribasic acid found in lemon. It is a white solid and soluble in water. (a) In the structure of citric acid shown below, circle ALL ionisable hydrogen atom(s) making it a tribasic acid. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：citric acid structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1578,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q12 Outline a synthetic route, with no more than three steps, to accomplish the following conversion. For each step, give the reagent(s), reaction conditions (as appropriate) and structure of the organic product. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：conversion scheme）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Step 1: alkaline hydrolysis / NaOH(aq) / heat. Step 2: esterification / conc. H2SO4 / heat with appropriate alcohol."},
//   {"id":1579,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q13 The structure of acetophenone is shown. Heating a mixture of acetophenone and NaBH4 in methanol solvent under reflux can give two isomeric compounds P and Q. P and Q have the same melting point and same solubility in methanol. (a) Draw a labelled diagram of the set-up for heating the mixture under reflux. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：reflux set-up diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1580,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q13 (b) Suggest a reducing agent, other than NaBH4, that can also reduce acetophenone. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"LiAlH4 / H2 (catalyst - Pt / Pd / Ni)"},
//   {"id":1581,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q13 (c) What kind of isomers are P and Q? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Enantiomers / optical isomers / They are isomers that exhibit enantiomerism."},
//   {"id":1582,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q13 (d) State one different physical property between P and Q. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Optical activity or P and Q rotate plane-polarised light to opposite directions to the same degree / extent."},
//   {"id":1583,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q13 (e) Suggest a chemical test to show how acetophenone and P can be distinguished. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add acidified K2Cr2O7: acetophenone - no change; P - from orange to green. / Add 2,4-DNP: acetophenone - formation of orange ppt.; P - no change. / Add CH3COOH/H+/heat: acetophenone - no change; P - pleasant odor substance formed. / Add Na: acetophenone - no change; P - formation of gas (H2)."},
//   {"id":1584,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q3 (a) & (b) Answer the following questions. (a) Explain why propene can form a polymer, but propane cannot. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"A propene molecule has C=C bond (for addition polymerization) whereas propane molecule has not."},
//   {"id":1585,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q3 (b) Explain why HO2C(CH2)4CO2H can form a polymer with H2N(CH2)6NH2, but CH3(CH2)4CO2H cannot. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"HO2C(CH2)4CO2H has two CO2H groups to react with NH2 group but CH3(CH2)4CO2H has only one CO2H group. Each HO2C(CH2)4CO2H molecule can react with two H2N(CH2)6NH2 molecules to form a chain but CH3(CH2)4CO2H cannot."},
//   {"id":1586,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q8 Combustion of petrol increases the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, and may contribute to global warming. Combustion of petrol also emits poisonous air pollutants. (a) Write a chemical equation for the complete combustion of octane (C8H18), a component in petrol. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"2C8H18 + 25O2 → 16CO2 + 18H2O"},
//   {"id":1587,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q8 (b) Draw the electron diagram for a molecule of carbon dioxide, showing electrons in the outermost shells only. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：CO2 electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1588,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q8 (c) Give one reason FOR and one reason AGAINST the following statement: 'Switching from using petrol-driven cars to using electric cars can help alleviate global warming.' (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"FOR: Using carbon capture techniques, the CO2 produced in power stations can be trapped, thus the emission of CO2 into the atmosphere will be reduced. AGAINST: The electricity used in powering cars is mainly produced by burning of fossil fuels, and the CO2 so produced will still be emitted into the atmosphere."},
//   {"id":1589,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q8 (d) Carbon monoxide is one of the poisonous air pollutants emitted from the combustion of petrol. Under what condition would carbon monoxide be formed during the combustion of petrol? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"limited supply of air or oxygen"},
//   {"id":1590,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q8 (e) (2 marks) (i) Name a device that can be installed in petrol-driven cars so as to reduce the emission of carbon monoxide.","points":30,"answerLetter":"catalytic converter"},
//   {"id":1591,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q8 (e) (ii) Suggest one air pollutant in car exhaust which cannot be removed by the device in (i).","points":30,"answerLetter":"particulates / suspended particulates / sulphur dioxide"},
//   {"id":1592,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q9* Four unlabelled reagent bottles each contains one of the colourless liquids listed below: HOCH2CH2CH2OH, CH3COCH3, CH3CH2CO2H, CH2=CHCO2H. Suggest chemical tests to distinguish the four liquids. (5 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Acidified K2Cr2O7(aq) test: Only HOCH2CH2CH2OH will produce a colour change from orange to green. Br2(in organic solvent) test: Only CH2=CHCO2H will produce a colour change from brown / orange to colourless. Add each liquid into water, and then perform Mg / Zn test: Only CH3CH2CO2H or CH2=CHCO2H reacts to give a colourless gas hydrogen. CH3COCH3 gives negative results in all the above three chemical tests."},
//   {"id":1593,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q12 Consider the following conversions: C5H10O → C5H12O → 3-bromopentane (optically active → optically inactive). (a) Write the structural formula of C. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"CH3CH2CH(Br)CH2CH3"},
//   {"id":1594,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q12 (b) (3 marks) (i) Deduce the structural formula of B.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The -OH group in B after reacting with HBr will change to the -Br group in C, and there is no chiral carbon due to no optical activity. Thus the structure of B is CH3CH2CH(OH)CH2CH3."},
//   {"id":1595,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q12 (b) (ii) Name the type of reaction for the conversion of B to C.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Substitution"},
//   {"id":1596,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q12 (c) (3 marks) (i) Deduce the structural formula of A. Label on this structural formula all chiral centre(s), if any, by using ★.","points":30,"answerLetter":"A has a C=C double bond as there are 2 hydrogen atoms less in A as compared with B. Moreover, A is optically active and it has a chiral carbon. A has the structure CH2=CHCH(OH)CH2CH3."},
//   {"id":1597,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q12 (c) (ii) State the reagent(s) required for the conversion of A to B.","points":30,"answerLetter":"H2 / Pd (heat) or H2 / Pt (heat) or H2 / Ni (heat)"},
//   {"id":1598,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q13 Outline a synthetic route, with no more than three steps, to accomplish the following conversion. For each step, give the reagent(s), reaction conditions (as appropriate) and the structure of the organic product. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：conversion scheme）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1599,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q4 Petroleum is an important source of hydrocarbons. (a) Describe the origin of petroleum. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Petroleum is formed when large quantities of dead marine organisms (such as planktons and algae), that are buried underneath sedimentary rock and subjected to intense heat and pressure for a long time."},
//   {"id":1600,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q4 (b) D, E and F are isomeric alkenes containing four carbon atoms. D and E are cis-trans isomers. (2 marks) (i) Draw the structure of E (trans-isomer). (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：trans-but-2-ene structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1601,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q4 (b) (ii) State the systematic name of one possible structure of F. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"but-1-ene / 2-methylpropene / methylpropene"},
//   {"id":1602,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q4 (c) (i) Suggest how ethene can be converted to ethane. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Pass excess H2 to ethene in the presence of Pt/Pd/Ni. / Catalytic hydrogenation"},
//   {"id":1603,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q4 (c) (ii) Suggest a chemical test to distinguish between ethane and ethene. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Ethene turns Br2 (in CH3CCl3) from brown / orange to colourless while ethane does not. / Ethene turns KMnO4/H+ from purple to colourless while ethane does not. / Ethene turns KMnO4/OH- from purple to brown (precipitate) while ethane does not. / Combustion Test - Ethene gives more sooty flame while ethane gives less sooty flame."},
//   {"id":1604,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q9* Tetrafluoroethene undergoes polymerisation to form a polymer called 'Teflon'. Using this example, describe this type of polymerisation. (5 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Unsaturated compounds / Compounds with C=C bonds can undergo addition polymerisation. No small molecules will be eliminated during addition polymerisation. High temp / High Pressure / Catalyst is used. Structure of the monomer: CF2=CF2. Structure of the repeating unit: -CF2-CF2- OR the polymer: -[CF2-CF2]n-."},
//   {"id":1605,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q10 Outline a synthetic route, with no more than three steps, to accomplish the following conversion. For each step, give the reagent(s), reaction conditions (as appropriate) and structure of the organic product. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：conversion scheme）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1606,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q12 Aspirin is a pain-killer. Its structure is shown. (a) State one medical application of aspirin other than pain-killing. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：aspirin structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Reduce fever / inflammation / risk of heart attack / Rheumatoid arthritis"},
//   {"id":1607,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q12 (b) Explain why a suspension of aspirin and water can become clear when sodium hydrogencarbonate powder is added. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"-COOH group of aspirin reacts with hydrogencarbonate ions in water to give a soluble sodium salt / soluble ions / soluble -COO-."},
//   {"id":1608,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q12 (c) (3 marks) (i) Draw the structures of these two organic products. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：hydrolysis products of aspirin）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1609,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q12 (c) (ii) Explain why the conversion of aspirin to these two organic products can hardly reach 100% even though the mixture of aspirin and dilute acid is heated under reflux for a long time. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Hydrolysis of ester in acidic medium is a reversible reaction / and if the reaction mixture is heated under reflux for a long time, it attains equilibrium position and reactants and products co-exist in the system."},
//   {"id":1610,"subject":"化學","topic":"5+11. Fossil Fuels, Carbon Compounds and Chemistry of Carbon Compounds","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q12 (d) Ibuprofen is also a pain-killer. Its structure is shown. There exists enantiomerism in ibuprofen. Draw the three-dimensional structures for the pair of enantiomers. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：ibuprofen enantiomers）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1611,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"SP Q4 A student used the set-up shown below to conduct a microscale experiment on electrolysis. (6 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：microscale electrolysis set-up）<br>(a) (i) The initial colour of the drop shown above was green. State the colour change of the liquid around carbon rod A after a current was passed through the circuit for some time. Explain your answer with the help of a half equation.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The colour of the liquid changed from green to blue. Both hydrogen ions and sodium ions moved towards rod A during electrolysis. However, H+(aq) ions would be preferentially discharged as H+(aq) ions occupy a lower position than Na+(aq) ions in the electrochemical series. At rod A, 2H+(aq) + 2e- → H2(g). Since the concentration of H+(aq) near rod A decreased and became lower than that of OH-(aq), the solution became alkaline and hence the colour of universal indicator turned blue."},
//   {"id":1612,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"SP Q4 (a) (ii) A gas was liberated at carbon rod B. What was the gas? Explain its formation.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The gas was oxygen. Both hydroxide and sulphate ions moved towards rod B. However, OH-(aq) ions would be preferentially discharged to oxygen as OH-(aq) ions occupy a higher position than SO42-(aq) ions in the electrochemical series. At rod B, 4OH-(aq) → O2(g) + 2H2O(l) + 4e-."},
//   {"id":1613,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"SP Q4 (b) Some objects readily available in daily life contain carbon rods which can be used in this experiment. Suggest ONE such object.","points":30,"answerLetter":"pencils"},
//   {"id":1614,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"PP Q3 (a)(ii) Magnesium nitride reacts with water to give magnesium hydroxide and ammonia. Write the chemical equation for this reaction. Explain whether or not this reaction is a redox. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Mg3N2 + 6H2O → 3Mg(OH)2 + 2NH3. No. There is no change in oxidation number of any atom."},
//   {"id":1615,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"PP Q8 The photograph below shows a laptop computer which is powered by Direct Methanol Fuel Cell (DMFC). The operation of DMFC is based on the following reaction under an acidic condition: 2CH3OH(aq) + 3O2(g) → 2CO2(g) + 4H2O(l). (a) Write half-equations for the anodic and cathodic reactions when DMFC is producing a current. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Anodic reaction: CH3OH(aq) + H2O(l) → CO2(g) + 6H+(aq) + 6e-; Cathodic reaction: O2(g) + 4H+(aq) + 4e- → 2H2O(l)."},
//   {"id":1616,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"PP Q8 (b) A concentrated aqueous methanol solution is used as the fuel in DMFC. (2 marks) (i) Suggest why pure methanol is NOT used.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Methanol does not conduct electricity. It is not suitable to be used as the reaction medium for the electrochemical reaction. / H2O is involved in the half-equations. / Acid is involved in the electrochemical reaction."},
//   {"id":1617,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"PP Q8 (b) (ii) Circle TWO of the following hazard warning labels that should be displayed on the container of a concentrated aqueous methanol solution. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：hazard warning labels）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1618,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"PP Q8 (c) Would you expect DMFC to be widely used in powering laptop computers? Explain your answer. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Accept both 'Yes' and 'No' answers. For 'No' answers: Electrical sockets can be found in most places. DMFC laptop computers will only be used in places where electric sockets are not available. / The cost for the manufacture of methanol is higher than that for the generation of electricity in most places. For 'Yes' answers: The use of DMFC laptop computers will become prevalent when stringent environmental laws are enforced as the disposal of DMFCs causes less harm to the environment than other rechargeable cells / methanol is a greener fuel than hydrocarbons. / DMFC laptop computers will be commonly used in field work where electric sockets are not available."},
//   {"id":1619,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q3 Consider the information concerning the lemon cells shown in the diagrams below. (a) What is the function of the lemons in these cells? (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：lemon cells diagrams）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Provide H+ / ions / electrolyte for the chemical cell."},
//   {"id":1620,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q3 (b) By completing the table below, arrange metal X, metal Y and copper in increasing order of reducing power. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：table）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Reducing power increasing: Copper < Metal Y < Metal X."},
//   {"id":1621,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q3 (c) For Cell 1, write the half equation for the change that occurs at: (2 marks) (i) metal X strip (X is a group II metal)","points":30,"answerLetter":"X → X2+ + 2e-"},
//   {"id":1622,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q3 (c) (ii) copper strip","points":30,"answerLetter":"2H+ + 2e- → H2"},
//   {"id":1623,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q3 (d) For Cell 2, would the metal Y strip be the positive electrode if the copper strip is replaced with a silver strip? Explain your answer. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"No, the metal Y strip would be the negative electrode. It is because silver is lower than copper in the electrochemical series, so silver should be lower than Y in the electrochemical series."},
//   {"id":1624,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q5 (b) & (c) In order to prepare 50 dm3 of 0.1 M CuSO4(aq), an inexperienced electroplating worker added the required exact amount of CuSO4·5H2O(s) to water in a plastic container. He then stirred the mixture with an iron rod until the CuSO4·5H2O(s) dissolved completely. Finally, he sent a sample of the solution to the Quality Control Laboratory for analysis, but found that the concentration of CuSO4(aq) was lower than 0.1 M. (b) The worker used the prepared CuSO4(aq) to coat a layer of copper on a metallic object by electrolysis. He used an unreasonably high voltage, and found that some bubbles were formed on the object and the copper layer easily flaked off. (3 marks) (i) Explain why copper can be coated on the metallic object by electrolysis. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Copper is lower than hydrogen in the electrochemical series. / Cu2+ is discharged preferentially than H+ when a current is applied."},
//   {"id":1625,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q5 (b) (ii) Suggest what the bubbles were, and explain why the copper layer easily flaked off. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Hydrogen gas / H2. The hydrogen gas bubbles hinder the deposition of copper on the surface of the metallic object, hence causing the copper metal deposited easily flaked off."},
//   {"id":1626,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q5 (c) Draw a labelled diagram of the experiment set-up used in a laboratory for coating a layer of copper on a metallic object by electrolysis. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：electroplating set-up diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1627,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q9 The diagram below shows the set-up used in an investigation on the electrolysis of concentrated potassium iodide solution. (a) State and explain the expected observation around carbon electrode A during the electrolysis. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：electrolysis of KI set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Brown colour is observed. Due to the high concentration of KI in the solution, I- ions are preferentially discharged to give I2 which dissolves in KI(aq) to give brown I3- ions."},
//   {"id":1628,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q9 (b) The solution near carbon electrode B gradually turned blue. (3 marks) (i) Explain this observation.","points":30,"answerLetter":"H+ ions are discharged and are reduced to H2 at electrode B. The amount of OH- ions increases at electrode B as H+ is being consumed. So universal indicator turns blue under alkaline conditions."},
//   {"id":1629,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q9 (b) (ii) Would there be any change in observation if carbon electrode B is replaced by a copper electrode in the investigation? Explain. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Accept both 'yes' and 'no' answers. No: B is the negative electrode. Copper will not lose electrons to give Cu2+ at the negative electrode / Copper cannot undergo reduction at the negative electrode. Yes: Copper and carbon have different electrical conductivity. Therefore the solution near electrode B turns blue more quickly. / The current in the external circuit changes."},
//   {"id":1630,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q10 The diagram below shows the structure of a hydrogen-oxygen fuel cell using concentrated potassium hydroxide solution as the electrolyte. (a) An oxygen cylinder can be used to provide oxygen for the above fuel cell. From the hazard warning labels shown below, circle the label that should be displayed on the oxygen cylinder. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：hazard warning labels）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1631,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q10 (b) Write the half equation for the change occurring at each of the following electrodes when this fuel cell is producing a current. (2 marks) electrode D, electrode E","points":30,"answerLetter":"Electrode D: H2(g) + 2OH-(aq) → 2H2O(l) + 2e-; Electrode E: O2(g) + 2H2O(l) + 4e- → 4OH-(aq)."},
//   {"id":1632,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q10 (c) Some people have the view that cars powered by hydrogen-oxygen fuel cells are more environmentally friendly than those powered by petrol. Comment on this view from each of the following aspects: (2 marks) (i) source of fuel","points":30,"answerLetter":"Accept both 'agree' and 'disagree' answers. Agree: The hydrogen gas can be obtained from renewable source (with one proper example, i.e. hydrogen from chloralkali process). Disagree: The hydrogen gas used is produced from fossil fuel such as steam reforming of natural gas. / Electrical energy is consumed in the production of hydrogen from water."},
//   {"id":1633,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q10 (c) (ii) the car emissions","points":30,"answerLetter":"Agree: Only water is produced from the hydrogen-oxygen fuel cells. / No CO2 / SO2 / NOx / CO / unburnt hydrocarbon in the exhaust."},
//   {"id":1634,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q8 The diagram below shows a set-up in which electrons are flowing through the electric wires. Moreover, one of the electrodes in beaker A is forming ions. (a) State an expected observation at each of the following electrodes: (2 marks) (i) electrode W, (ii) electrode X<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：electrochemical cell diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(i) The electrode dissolves / becomes smaller / becomes thinner gradually. (ii) Colourless gas / bubbles given out."},
//   {"id":1635,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q8 (b) Write the half equation for the expected change at each of the following electrodes: (2 marks) (i) electrode Y, (ii) electrode Z","points":30,"answerLetter":"(i) 4OH- → 2H2O + O2 + 4e-; (ii) Ag+ + e- → Ag."},
//   {"id":1636,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q8 (c) Complete the following table by filling in 'anode' or 'cathode' to describe the electrodes. (1 mark) electrode W, electrode Z","points":30,"answerLetter":"electrode W: anode, electrode Z: cathode."},
//   {"id":1637,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q8 (d) Predict, with reason, what would happen if the MgSO4(aq) in beaker A is replaced by ethanol. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Electrons would not flow through the electric wires / no observable changes on all electrodes no reaction occurs because ethanol is not an electrolyte / cannot conduct electricity."},
//   {"id":1638,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q9 (b) Consider each of the experiments below and answer the questions that follow. (b) Acidified potassium permanganate solution is added to sodium sulphite solution. (3 marks) (i) State the expected colour change.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Purple acidified potassium permanganate solution is decolourised / turns into colourless."},
//   {"id":1639,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q9 (b) (ii) For the reaction leading to the colour change, (1) state the name of the type of reaction; and (2) write the ionic equation for the reaction. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Redox / oxidation-reduction / reduction of acidified potassium permanganate. (2) 2MnO4-(aq) + 5SO32-(aq) + 6H+(aq) → 2Mn2+(aq) + 5SO42-(aq) + 3H2O(l)."},
//   {"id":1640,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q2 (b) For each of the following experiments, state the expected observation, and write the chemical equation(s) for the reaction(s) involved. (b) adding sodium sulphite solution to acidified potassium dichromate solution until in excess (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The solution changes from orange to green. Cr2O72-(aq) + 3SO32-(aq) + 8H+(aq) → 2Cr3+(aq) + 3SO42-(aq) + 4H2O(l)."},
//   {"id":1641,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q4 Lead-acid accumulator is a secondary cell containing sulphuric acid. It is commonly used in starting up motor vehicle engines. (a) What is meant by the term 'secondary cell'? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"A cell that can be recharged."},
//   {"id":1642,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q4 (b) Suggest why a lead-acid accumulator is suitable for starting up motor vehicle engines. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"It can provide a high current / voltage / power to start up the engine."},
//   {"id":1643,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q4 (c) State one environmental impact that would be imposed from the disposal of lead-acid accumulators. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Lead / Lead compounds are toxic. / Sulphuric acid is corrosive / irritant."},
//   {"id":1644,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q4 (d) A student diluted a sample of concentrated sulphuric acid for making a lead-acid accumulator. (5 marks) (i) Describe how concentrated sulphuric acid can be diluted in a laboratory. State a safety precaution needed during the dilution process. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Pour a small amount of the concentrated sulphuric acid to a large amount of water. Wear goggle / face shield / safety spectacles / safety glasses / gloves."},
//   {"id":1645,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q4 (d) (ii) 5.00 cm3 of the solution in the lead-acid accumulator made contains 2.48 g of sulphuric acid. Calculate the molarity of the sulphuric acid in the solution. (2 marks) (Molar mass of sulphuric acid = 98.1 g)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Number of mole of sulphuric acid = 2.48/98.1 = 0.0253. Molarity = 0.0253/0.005 = 5.06 (M)."},
//   {"id":1646,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q7 Refer to the set-up for electroplating an object shown in the diagram. (a) Explain why oily dints on the object should be removed before electroplating. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：electroplating set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Oily dirt hinders the conduction of electricity / hinders the plating of copper on the object."},
//   {"id":1647,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q7 (b) Copper(II) sulphate is an electrolyte. What is meant by the term 'electrolyte'? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Electrolyte is a compound that conducts electricity when melted or dissolved in water. / Electrolyte is a substance that consists of mobile ions when melted or dissolved in water. / Electrolyte is a substance that undergoes decomposition when electricity is passing through it."},
//   {"id":1648,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q7 (c) List ALL the ions existing in the solution. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cu2+, SO42-, H+, OH-."},
//   {"id":1649,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q7 (d) Explain why copper(II) ions are preferentially discharged during the electroplating process. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Copper(II) ion has higher oxidizing power than hydrogen ion. / Copper(II) ion undergoes reduction more readily than hydrogen ion."},
//   {"id":1650,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q7 (e) Write the half equation of the change that occurs at the anode. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cu → Cu2+ + 2e-"},
//   {"id":1651,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q7 (f) State the observable change, if any, in the solution during the electroplating process. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"No observable change"},
//   {"id":1652,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q7 (g) It is known that 2.28×1022 electrons have passed through the external circuit during the electroplating process. Calculate the mass of copper that would theoretically be plated on the object. (Relative atomic mass: Cu = 63.5; Avogadro's constant = 6.02×1023 mol-1) (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Number of mole of electrons involved = (2.28×1022)/(6.02×1023) = 0.0379. Mass of copper formed = (0.0379×63.5)/2 = 1.20 (g)."},
//   {"id":1653,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q8 Consider the experimental set-up shown below. (a) In the above experiment, the bulb lights up when the SrBr2(s) becomes molten. (2 marks) (Atomic number of Sr = 38) (i) State the observation at carbon electrode X.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：electrolysis of SrBr2 set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Reddish brown gas observed."},
//   {"id":1654,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q8 (a) (ii) Write a half equation for the change that occurs at carbon electrode Y.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Sr2+ + 2e- → Sr"},
//   {"id":1655,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q8 (b) Explain why the experiment should be performed in a fume cupboard. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Bromine gas formed is toxic / poisonous. Bromine is toxic. A toxic gas is formed."},
//   {"id":1656,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q8 (c) Zinc-carbon cells are used in the above experiment. The equation below shows the reaction that occurs in the zinc-carbon cells when the bulb lights up. 2MnO2(s) + 2NH4Cl(aq) + Zn(s) → Mn2O3(s) + 2NH3(aq) + H2O(l) + ZnCl2(aq) (3 marks) (i) Deduce, in terms of change in oxidation number, the oxidising agent in a zinc-carbon cell.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Oxidation number of Mn decreases / changes from +4 to +3. Therefore MnO2(s) is the oxidising agent."},
//   {"id":1657,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q8 (c) (ii) Write a half equation for the change that occurs at the cathode in a zinc-carbon cell. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"2MnO2(s) + 2NH4+(aq) + 2e- → Mn2O3(s) + 2NH3(aq) + H2O(l) or 2NH4+(aq) + 2e- → 2NH3(aq) + H2(g)."},
//   {"id":1658,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q1 (c)(ii) Barium (Ba) is an element in Group II of the Periodic Table. Its chemical properties are similar to those of calcium. An experiment was carried out to study the change in electrical conductivity of the mixture formed when a dilute H2SO4(aq) was added gradually to a fixed volume of a dilute Ba(OH)2(aq). The graph below shows the results of the experiment. (3 marks) Explain the change of electrical conductivity in the following stages: (1) From A to B<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：conductivity graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"When H2SO4(aq) is added, BaSO4(s) and H2O(l) are formed, the concentration of mobile ions in the mixture decreases."},
//   {"id":1659,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q1 (c)(ii) (2) From B to C","points":30,"answerLetter":"Excess H+(aq) and SO42-(aq) ions are introduced into the solution. The concentrations of H+(aq) and SO42-(aq) ions in the solution increase. The concentration of mobile ions in the solution increases when H2SO4(aq) is in excess."},
//   {"id":1660,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q4 The diagram below shows a set-up for the electrolysis of a colourless solution of 1 M K2SO4(aq) containing phenolphthalein indicator. (a) State, with explanation, the expected observation around the following electrodes during the electrolysis: (3 marks) (i) electrode A<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：electrolysis set-up with indicator）","points":30,"answerLetter":"OH-(aq) ions are preferentially discharged to give a colourless gas oxygen."},
//   {"id":1661,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q4 (a) (ii) electrode B","points":30,"answerLetter":"H+(aq) ions are preferentially discharged to give a colourless gas hydrogen. The solution turns pink as [OH-(aq)] > [H+(aq)] when H+(aq) ions are consumed."},
//   {"id":1662,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q4 (b) Write the equation of the overall reaction in the electrolysis. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"2H2O → 2H2 + O2"},
//   {"id":1663,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q4 (c) Explain whether there are any changes in the expected observation around the following electrodes during the electrolysis if the 1 M K2SO4(aq) is replaced with 1 M H2SO4(aq): (3 marks) (i) electrode A","points":30,"answerLetter":"No change. OH-(aq) ions are still preferentially discharged to give a colourless gas oxygen."},
//   {"id":1664,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q4 (c) (ii) electrode B","points":30,"answerLetter":"No change. H+(aq) ions, the only cations, are discharged to give a colourless gas hydrogen. No colour change in the solution / The solution will not turn into pink as it is still acidic, despite the decrease in [H+(aq)] / as H+(aq) is in excess."},
//   {"id":1665,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q6 (c) Concentrated sulphuric acid is a reagent commonly found in laboratories. (c) With the help of, a chemical equation, state the observation when hot concentrated sulphuric acid reacts with copper. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Copper dissolves. / The solution turns blue. / A colourless / choking gas evolves. Cu + 2H2SO4 → CuSO4 + 2H2O + SO2."},
//   {"id":1666,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q5 (a) Electroplating and rust prevention are common applications of electrochemistry. (a) The diagram below shows an incomplete set-up. Add suitable drawings and labels to the diagram for electroplating of silver onto the knife. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：electroplating diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"All 3 labels correct: 2 marks; Any 1 label correct: 1 mark. Accept drawing of battery with correct poles / only + and - signs at the correct positions / electron flows in correct direction in the external circuit."},
//   {"id":1667,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q8 Refer to the experimental set-up as shown below. (b) When concentrated HCl(aq) is dropped into KMnO4(s), a yellowish green gas is formed. (2 marks) (i) What is the yellowish green gas?<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：gas generation set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"chlorine / Cl2(g)"},
//   {"id":1668,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q8 (b) (ii) Explain whether the reaction forming the yellowish green gas is a redox reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"It is a redox reaction: O.N. of Cl changes from -1 to 0 / of Mn changes from +7 to +2 / Cl transfers electrons to MnO4- / O.N. of Mn and Cl change at the same time / MnO4- is reduced and Cl- is oxidised."},
//   {"id":1669,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q8 (c) With the aid of an ionic equation, state the expected observation when the yellowish green gas reaches the filter paper. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The filter paper turns yellowish brown. 2I- + Cl2 → 2Cl- + I2."},
//   {"id":1670,"subject":"化學","topic":"7. Redox Reactions, Chemical Cells and Electrolysis","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q8 (d) In consideration of laboratory safety, explain where the experiment should be performed. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The experiment should be performed in a fume cupboard as chlorine gas is toxic / toxic gas is released."},
//   {"id":1671,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"SP Q5 In an experiment to determine the enthalpy change of combustion of ethanol, a calorimeter containing 200.0 g of water was used. Burning 0.185 g of ethanol caused the temperature of the water in the calorimeter to rise by 6.0°C. (6 marks) (a) Draw a labelled diagram of the set-up used in the experiment.","points":30,"answerLetter":"（缺少圖片，文件名：calorimeter set-up diagram）"},
//   {"id":1672,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"SP Q5 (b) Assuming that the heat capacity of the calorimeter is negligible, calculate the enthalpy change of combustion of ethanol, in kJ mol-1, under the conditions of the experiment. (Specific heat capacity of water = 4.2 J g-1 K-1)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Heat released = mcΔT = 200 × 4.2 × 6.0 = 5040 J. No. of moles of ethanol burnt = 0.185 / (12.0×2 + 1.0×6 + 16.0) = 4.02×10-3. Enthalpy change of combustion = -5.04 / (4.02×10-3) = -1254 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1673,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"SP Q5 (c) State ONE other assumption made in your calculation.","points":30,"answerLetter":"There is no heat loss to the surroundings. / There is complete combustion of ethanol. / The heat transfer is complete."},
//   {"id":1674,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"PP Q7 (a) A student carried out an experiment to determine the enthalpy change of the reaction of calcium oxide with water. The set-up used is shown in the diagram below. The experimental results are as follows: mass of CaO(s) used = 3.0 g; volume of water in the cup = 50.0 cm3; initial temperature of water = 28.2°C; highest temperature attained = 46.7°C. (5 marks) (i) Calculate the enthalpy change, in kJ mol-1, of the reaction of calcium oxide with water under the conditions of the experiment. (Assume: density of water = 1.0 g cm-3 and specific heat capacity of the Ca(OH)2(aq) formed = 4.2 J g-1 K-1; the polypropylene cup, thermometer and stirrer used all have negligible heat capacity.)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：calorimeter set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. of moles of CaO(s) used = 3.0 / (40.1+16) = 0.053. Heat liberated = 53 × 4.2 × (46.7-28.2) = 4118 J. ΔH = -4118 / 0.053 = -77.0 kJ mol-1. (Acceptable range: -72.6 to -77.0 kJ mol-1)"},
//   {"id":1675,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"PP Q7 (a) (ii) According to the literature, ΔH° for this reaction is -82.2 kJ mol-1. Suggest ONE reasonable explanation for the discrepancy between the literature value and the value obtained in (i).","points":30,"answerLetter":"PP is not a perfect heat insulator; heat is lost to the surroundings. / Some CaO(s) may have reacted with H2O(l) in air."},
//   {"id":1676,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"PP Q7 (b) The diagram below shows the design of a can of self-heating coffee beverage. When the bottom of the can is pushed, the rod will pierce the aluminium foil and cause mixing of the water and calcium oxide. The coffee beverage in the can will then be heated up. (4 marks) (i) With reference to the properties of the materials involved, explain why (I) a polypropene container is used to contain the calcium oxide, and (II) an aluminium container is used to contain the coffee beverage.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：self-heating can diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(I) PP is a poor conductor of heat. Using PP container to hold CaO(s) will protect hands from skin burns. / PP can withstand the high temperature caused by the reaction of CaO(s) with H2O(l). (II) Compounds of Al are non-toxic. They will not cause food poisoning. / Al is a good conductor of heat. The heat liberated from the reaction of CaO(s) with H2O(l) can readily be transmitted to the coffee beverage. / Aluminium is covered by a layer of unreactive Al2O3(s), which prevents the metal from corrosion."},
//   {"id":1677,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"PP Q7 (b) (ii) Suggest ONE reasonable explanation for using calcium oxide in this type of self-heating beverage can.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The reaction of CaO(s) and H2O(l) is highly exothermic, and CaO(s) is an inexpensive material."},
//   {"id":1678,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q8 Potassium hydrogencarbonate (KHCO3) can be used to bake bread. Upon heating, KHCO3 decomposes into K2CO3, H2O and CO2. (a) Explain the purpose of using KHCO3 in bread baking. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"CO2 gas produced makes the bread rise / spongy."},
//   {"id":1679,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q8 (b) Write the chemical equation for the decomposition of KHCO3 upon heating. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"2KHCO3 → K2CO3 + H2O + CO2"},
//   {"id":1680,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q8 (c) The enthalpy change of decomposition of KHCO3(s) can be determined indirectly from the enthalpy changes of the following two reactions: KHCO3(s) + HCl(aq) → KCl(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g) — Reaction(1); K2CO3(s) + 2HCl(aq) → 2KCl(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g) — Reaction(2). In an experiment to determine the enthalpy change of Reaction (1), 3.39 g of KHCO3(s) was added to excess HCl(aq) in an expanded polystyrene cup. The experimental data obtained are shown below: Initial temperature of the reacting solution: 25.8°C; Final temperature: 20.2°C; Mass of the resulting solution: 27.5 g; Specific heat capacity of the contents: 4.3 J g-1 K-1; Molar mass of KHCO3: 100.1 g. (4 marks) (i) Assuming that the heat capacity of the cup used is negligible, calculate the enthalpy change of Reaction (1) from the above data.","points":30,"answerLetter":"q = 27.5 × 4.3 × (25.8-20.2) = 662.2 J. ΔH = +662.2×10-3 ÷ (3.39/100.1) = +19.6 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1681,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q8 (c) (ii) In another experiment performed under the same conditions, the enthalpy change of Reaction (2) was found to be -49.1 kJ mol-1. Calculate the enthalpy change of decomposition of KHCO3(s) under the experimental conditions.","points":30,"answerLetter":"ΔH = 19.6 - (-49.1 × 1/2) = +44.15 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1682,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q5 (d) According to the literature, the standard enthalpy changes of formation of K2CO3(s), KHCO3(s), CO2(g) and H2O(l) are as follows: K2CO3(s): -1146 kJ mol-1, KHCO3(s): -959 kJ mol-1, CO2(g): -394 kJ mol-1, H2O(l): -286 kJ mol-1. (2 marks) (i) Using the given information, calculate the standard enthalpy change of decomposition of KHCO3(s).","points":30,"answerLetter":"ΔH = 1/2[-1146 -394 -286 - (-959×2)] = +46 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1683,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q5 (d) (ii) Suggest why the answers obtained from (c)(ii) and (d)(i) are different.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Not performing the experiment in standard conditions. / Heat transfer with the surroundings. / The heat capacity of the container was neglected."},
//   {"id":1684,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q5 (a) The following experiment was carried out to determine the enthalpy change of solution of ammonium nitrate: NH4NO3(s) → NH4NO3(aq). A certain volume of water was placed in an expanded polystyrene cup. The temperature of the water was measured at half-minute intervals. Right at the third minute, 2.0 g of NH4NO3(s) was added. The solution was stirred and its temperature was measured for an additional 7 minutes. The recordings of temperature are shown in the graph below. (4 marks) (i) From the graph, estimate the greatest temperature drop of the solution in the cup.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：temperature-time graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(26.6 - 19.8) = 6.8°C"},
//   {"id":1685,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q5 (a) (ii) The mass of the NH4NO3(aq) obtained was found to be 21.8 g. Calculate the enthalpy change of solution of ammonium nitrate, in kJ mol-1, under the experimental conditions. (Assume that the heat capacity of the expanded polystyrene cup is negligible, and the specific heat capacity of the NH4NO3(aq) obtained is 4.3 J g-1 K-1.)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Heat absorbed = mcΔT = 21.8 × 4.3 × 6.8 = 637.4 J. No. of moles of NH4NO3(s) = 2.0/80 = 0.025. ΔH = +637.4/0.025 = +25.5 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1686,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q7 (a) Thermite reactions broadly refer to exothermic oxidation-reduction reactions between a metal powder and a metal oxide. One example is the reaction of finely divided iron(III) oxide with aluminium powder. This reaction results in a very high temperature, and is commonly used in the welding of rail tracks for trains. At this very high temperature, the molten iron formed joins the rail tracks together. (2 marks) (i) Complete and balance the chemical equation for the following thermite reaction: Fe2O3(s) + Al(s) → Fe(l) + Al2O3(s).","points":30,"answerLetter":"Fe2O3(s) + 2Al(s) → 2Fe(l) + Al2O3(s)"},
//   {"id":1687,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q7 (a) (ii) Sketch a labelled enthalpy level diagram for this reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"（缺少圖片，文件名：enthalpy level diagram）"},
//   {"id":1688,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q6 (a)(iii) Petrol is a commonly used motor car fuel. It can be obtained from petroleum by fractional distillation. (a) (iii) Octane (C8H18) is a component of petrol. Using octane as an example, state the meaning of the term 'standard enthalpy change of combustion' with the aid of a chemical equation. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The enthalpy change when one mole of a compound burns completely under standard conditions / 25°C and 1 atm. C8H18(l) + 25/2 O2(g) → 8CO2(g) + 9H2O(l)."},
//   {"id":1689,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q6 (b)(ii) Motor cars powered by petrol emit air pollutants such as nitrogen monoxide and carbon monoxide. Installing a certain device in motor cars can convert these two oxides to less harmful substances. (4 marks) (ii) The equation for the reaction involved in the conversion is shown below: 2CO(g) + 2NO(g) → 2CO2(g) + N2(g). The standard enthalpy changes of formation of NO(g), CO(g) and CO2(g) are as follows: NO(g): +90.3 kJ mol-1, CO(g): -110.5 kJ mol-1, CO2(g): -394.0 kJ mol-1. Calculate the standard enthalpy change of the above reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"ΔH° = 2(-394) - 2(-110.5) - 2(90.3) = -747.6 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1690,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q8 (b) Natural gas is an important energy source for electricity generation. It contains mainly methane (CH4). (b) The combustion of methane is an exothermic reaction. Its chemical equation is shown below: CH4(g) + 2O2(g) → CO2(g) + 2H2O(l). (5 marks) (i) Complete the table below by stating all the covalent bond(s) that are broken and formed during the combustion of methane.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Covalent bond(s) broken: C-H and O=O. Covalent bond(s) formed: C=O and H-O."},
//   {"id":1691,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q8 (b) (ii) Suggest why the combustion is exothermic in terms of the breaking and forming of covalent bonds.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The total energy released in the bond forming process is larger than the total energy absorbed in the bond breaking process."},
//   {"id":1692,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q8 (b) (iii) Calculate the standard enthalpy change of combustion of methane. (Standard enthalpy changes of formation: CH4(g) = -74.8 kJ mol-1; CO2(g) = -393.5 kJ mol-1; H2O(l) = -285.9 kJ mol-1)","points":30,"answerLetter":"ΔHc° = ΔHf°[CO2(g)] + 2ΔHf°[H2O(l)] - ΔHf°[CH4(g)] = (-393.5) + 2(-285.9) - (-74.8) = -890.5 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1693,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q7 The enthalpy change of formation of MgCO3(s) can be obtained using an indirect method. Firstly, the enthalpy change for the reaction of MgCO3(s) with H2SO4(aq), and that of Mg(s) with H2SO4(aq) are respectively determined experimentally. After that, the enthalpy change of formation of MgCO3(s) can be obtained through calculation with given enthalpy changes of formation of CO2(g) and H2O(l). (a) According to definition, under which condition could the 'heat change' of a reaction be regarded as the 'enthalpy change'? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Constant pressure"},
//   {"id":1694,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q7 (b) Explain why, instead of a direct method, an indirect method is used to obtain the enthalpy change of formation of MgCO3(s). (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"It is very difficult for Mg(s), C(s) and O2(g) to react directly to form MgCO3(s). / MgCO3(s) cannot be formed from its elements. / There will be side products. / MgO will be formed. / CO2 will be formed."},
//   {"id":1695,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q7 (c) In order to determine experimentally the enthalpy change for the reaction of MgCO3(s) with H2SO4(aq), an accurate mass of MgCO3(s) was firstly allowed to react with excess H2SO4(aq) in a polystyrene foam cup. The maximum rise in temperature of the mixture was then found. After calculation, the enthalpy change for the reaction can be obtained. (2 marks) (i) Suggest one possible error for the above experimental procedure.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Heat loss to surrounding. / PS cup absorbs heat. / Thermometer absorbs heat."},
//   {"id":1696,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q7 (c) (ii) Explain whether the enthalpy change for the reaction of CaCO3(s) with H2SO4(aq) can be obtained using a similar experimental procedure.","points":30,"answerLetter":"No, because insoluble CaSO4 will be formed. (and the reaction is stopped). / No, because CaSO4 solid will be formed. (and the reaction is stopped)."},
//   {"id":1697,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q7 (d) Using the information given below, calculate the standard enthalpy change of formation of MgCO3(s). (3 marks) Standard enthalpy change for the reaction of MgCO3(s) with H2SO4(aq) = -50 kJ mol-1; Standard enthalpy change for the reaction of Mg(s) with H2SO4(aq) = -467 kJ mol-1; Standard enthalpy change of formation of CO2(g) = -394 kJ mol-1; Standard enthalpy change of formation of H2O(l) = -286 kJ mol-1.","points":30,"answerLetter":"MgCO3(s) + H2SO4(aq) → MgSO4(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g) ΔH = -50; Mg(s) + H2SO4(aq) → MgSO4(aq) + H2(g) ΔH = -467; C(s) + O2(g) → CO2(g) ΔH = -394; H2(g) + 1/2 O2(g) → H2O(l) ΔH = -286; Mg(s) + C(s) + 3/2 O2(g) → MgCO3(s) ΔH = y. y - 50 = -467 - 394 - 286, y = -1097 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1698,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q7 Ethyne is a gaseous hydrocarbon with molecular formula C2H2. (a) Suggest why the enthalpy change of formation of C2H2(g) CANNOT be determined directly by experiment. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The reaction between carbon and hydrogen does not only give ethyne."},
//   {"id":1699,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q7 (b) Hess's law can be used to find enthalpy changes which CANNOT be determined directly by experiment. State Hess's law. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The total enthalpy change of a chemical reaction is independent of the pathway between the initial and final states."},
//   {"id":1700,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q7 (c) Based on the enthalpy changes of combustion ΔHc of C2H2(g), C(graphite) and H2(g) to construct an enthalpy change cycle and applying Hess's law can give the enthalpy change of formation of C2H2(g). (5 marks) (i) Draw, with labels, this enthalpy change cycle. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"（缺少圖片，文件名：enthalpy cycle diagram）"},
//   {"id":1701,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q7 (c) (ii) The standard enthalpy changes of combustion ΔHc° of C2H2(g), C(graphite) and H2(g) are given below: C2H2(g): -1300 kJ mol-1, C(graphite): -394 kJ mol-1, H2(g): -286 kJ mol-1. (1) State the standard conditions for 'standard enthalpy change'. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"298 K and 1 atm"},
//   {"id":1702,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q7 (c) (ii) (2) Calculate the standard enthalpy change of formation of C2H2(g). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Standard enthalpy change of formation of C2H2(g) = 2×(-394) + (-286) - (-1300) = +226 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1703,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q6 Energy exists in various forms. (a) Glucose (C6H12O6) is one important energy source for living things. (4 marks) (i) Write a chemical equation for the conversion of carbon dioxide gas and liquid water to solid glucose and oxygen gas.","points":30,"answerLetter":"6CO2(g) + 6H2O(l) → C6H12O6(s) + 6O2(g)"},
//   {"id":1704,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q6 (a) (ii) The following standard enthalpy changes of formation are given: CO2(g) = -394 kJ mol-1, H2O(l) = -286 kJ mol-1, C6H12O6(s) = -1274 kJ mol-1. Calculate the standard enthalpy change of the conversion in (i) above.","points":30,"answerLetter":"ΔH = -1274 - 6×(-394 -286) = -1274 - 6×(-680) = -1274 - (-4080) = +2806 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1705,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q6 (a) (iii) Green plants can convert carbon dioxide and water to glucose and oxygen. State the transformation of energy in this conversion.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Light energy / solar energy → chemical energy"},
//   {"id":1706,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q6 (b) Burning heptane (C7H16) releases energy. The enthalpy change of combustion of heptane was determined using the set-up shown below: (4 marks) Step (I): The aluminium can with a fixed mass of water was heated by burning methanol. The temperature of water increased by 18.5°C after 1.58 g of methanol was burnt. Step (II): The aluminium can with the same mass of water in Step (I) was heated by burning heptane. The temperature of water increased by 25.8°C after 1.02 g of heptane was burnt. (i) Given that, under the conditions of experiment, the enthalpy change of combustion of methanol is -715 kJ mol-1, calculate the enthalpy change of combustion of heptane, in kJ mol-1, under the same conditions. (Relative molecular masses: methanol = 32.0, heptane = 100.0)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：combustion calorimeter set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Let C be the heat capacity of the calorimeter. -715 × (1.58/32.0) = -C × 18.5 … (1); ΔH × (1.02/100.0) = -C × 25.8 … (2); ΔH = -4826.8 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1707,"subject":"化學","topic":"Chemical Reactions and Energy","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q6 (b) (ii) Besides heat loss, suggest another source of error in the experiment.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Incomplete combustion. / Some methanol or heptane evaporates."},
//   {"id":1708,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"SP Q10 P(g) reacts with Q(g) irreversibly to give R(g). A mixture of P(g) and Q(g) is allowed to react in a closed container of volume 1 dm3 kept at a constant temperature. The graph below shows the changes in concentrations of P(g), Q(g) and R(g) in the container with time. (5 marks) (a) With reference to the above graph, deduce the chemical equation for the reaction in terms of P(g), Q(g) and R(g).<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：concentration-time graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"P(g) + 2Q(g) → R(g). At 0 min: [P]=0.50, [Q]=0.50, [R]=0.00; at 40 min: [P]=0.25, [Q]=0.00, [R]=0.25. Hence, 1 mole of P reacts with 2 moles of Q to give 1 mole of R."},
//   {"id":1709,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"SP Q10 (b) If the mixture of P(g) and Q(g) is allowed to react at the same temperature but in a closed container of volume 2 dm3 instead, will the time required for the reaction to complete remain the same? Explain.","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. The rate of reaction depends on the concentration of the reactants in the system. With the reaction taking place in a closed container of increased volume, the concentration of reactants in the system decreases. There is a lower chance of the collision of reactants and the number of effective collisions decreases. The rate of reaction is slower and hence, it would take a longer time for the reaction to complete."},
//   {"id":1710,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"PP Q10 The equation below shows the reaction of potassium permanganate with sodium ethanedioate under acidic conditions: 2MnO4-(aq) + 5C2O42-(aq) + 16H+(aq) → 2Mn2+(aq) + 10CO2(g) + 8H2O(l). A student conducted an experiment to study the rate of this reaction. The results are shown in the graph below. (a) Suggest ONE physical method that can be used to monitor the concentration of MnO4-(aq) ions in the reaction mixture. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：rate graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Colorimetry / using colorimeter"},
//   {"id":1711,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"PP Q10 (b) Based on the experimental results, the student suggested that one of the products might have catalysed the reaction. (4 marks) (i) What evidence from the above graph supports the student's suggestion? Explain your answer.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The rate of consumption of MnO4-(aq) ions is slow at the beginning (from 0 to 180 s) and then increases rapidly (from 200 to 340 s). It is likely to be due to the building up of the concentration of the product which catalyses the reaction."},
//   {"id":1712,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"PP Q10 (b) (ii) Suggest how the student can show whether or not Mn2+(aq) is a catalyst for this reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Repeat the experiment with a few drops of Mn2+(aq) firstly added to the reaction mixture. Consumption of MnO4-(aq) ions will be faster at the beginning if Mn2+(aq) is a catalyst."},
//   {"id":1713,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q11 In an experiment, 50 cm3 of 2.0 M HCl(aq) was added to a conical flask containing 2.0 g of zinc powder. The curve in the graph below shows the volume, measured at room temperature and pressure, of the hydrogen gas liberated in the first few minutes of the experiment. The dotted line in the graph is the tangent to the curve at the start of the reaction. (a) The initial rate' of a reaction is defined as the instantaneous rate at the start of the reaction. With reference to the graph above, calculate the initial rate of the reaction with respect to the volume of hydrogen gas liberated. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：gas volume-time graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Initial Rate = 60/4 = 15 cm3/min"},
//   {"id":1714,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q11 (b) Explain qualitatively the effect on the initial rate of the reaction of replacing the 2.0 M HCl(aq) with 2.0 M H2SO4(aq). (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"HCl is a monobasic acid, while H2SO4 is a dibasic acid. Initial rate increases if H2SO4 is used. / Initial rate increases as the concentration of H+ increases when using 2.0 M H2SO4."},
//   {"id":1715,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q11 (c) Upon completion of reaction, all the zinc powder was used up. Calculate the theoretical volume of hydrogen gas liberated, measured at room temperature and pressure. (3 marks) (Molar volume of gas at room temperature and pressure = 24 dm3; Relative atomic mass: Zn = 65.4)","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. of mol of Zn = 2/65.4 = 0.0306 mol. Volume of H2 formed = 0.0306 × 24000 = 734 cm3."},
//   {"id":1716,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q11 Safety airbags are important devices installed in vehicles. During a serious car crash, the chemicals in the airbag immediately react to release a large amount of gas. An airbag hence inflates instantly, protecting the passenger. The main chemicals in safety airbags are sodium azide (NaN3) and potassium nitrate (KNO3). The equations below show the reactions involved when an airbag is inflated: 2NaN3(s) → 2Na(s) + 3N2(g); 10Na(s) + 2KNO3(s) → K2O(s) + 5Na2O(s) + N2(g). (a) Explain why the NaN3(s) and KNO3(s) used in the airbags are in the form of fine powder. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The airbag has to be inflated instantly when a car crash occurs. Fine powder can greatly increase the reaction rate by providing a large surface area for a reaction involving solid reactants."},
//   {"id":1717,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q11 (b) An airbag contains 100.0 g of NaN3(s) and 200.0 g of KNO3(s). Calculate the theoretical volume, measured at room temperature and pressure, of the gas produced when the bag is inflated. (3 marks) (Formula masses: NaN3 = 65.0, KNO3 = 101.1; molar volume of gas at room temperature and pressure = 24 dm3)","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. of mole of N2 from decomposition of NaN3 = (100/65)×(3/2) = 2.31. No. of mole of Na produced = 100/65 = 1.54; No. of mole of KNO3 = 200/101.1 = 1.98 (KNO3 in excess). No. of mole of N2 from reaction 2 = (100/65)×(1/10) = 0.154. Volume of gas produced = (2.31+0.154)×24 = 59.1 dm3."},
//   {"id":1718,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q11 (c) The main function of NaN3(s) is to produce N2(g) for inflating the airbags. Suggest why it is necessary to include KNO3(s) in the airbags. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"KNO3 is added to react with sodium which is highly reactive / corrosive / flammable / strongly reducing."},
//   {"id":1719,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q11 (d) Sodium azide is a toxic chemical. Thus any NaN3 waste remained during the manufacture of safety airbags needs special treatment before disposal. The treatment involves first dissolving NaN3 in water, and then reacting the solution formed with excess nitrous acid, HNO2(aq). The graph below shows the variation of the concentration of NaN3(aq) in the reaction mixture with time in one such process: (2 marks) (i) Calculate the average rate of consumption of NaN3(aq) in the first 10 seconds.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：concentration-time graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Average rate = (0.01 - 0.005)/10 = 0.0005 mol dm-3 s-1 (5.0×10-4 mol dm-3 s-1)."},
//   {"id":1720,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q11 (d) (ii) Suggest how the instantaneous rate of consumption of NaN3(aq) at the 10th second can be determined from the graph.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Determine the slope of the tangent of curve at t = 10 s."},
//   {"id":1721,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q10* You are provided with common laboratory apparatus, calcium carbonate and 1M hydrochloric acid. Outline how you would perform a fair comparison in studying the effect of different concentrations of acid on the rate of production of carbon dioxide from the following reaction: CaCO3(s) + 2HCl(aq) → CaCl2(aq) + H2O(l) + CO2(g). (5 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Proper way to follow the progress of the reaction (e.g. measure the volume of CO2 evolved / measure the loss in mass of the reaction mixture over a certain time interval / measure the pressure of the CO2 formed in a sealed reaction container). Dilute 1M HCl to different concentrations by adding water. Repeat the experiment with the diluted HCl. State one condition for performing fair comparison (e.g. CaCO3 used should be of the same amount / under same experimental conditions such as same temperature or pressure)."},
//   {"id":1722,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q9 Consider the reaction below: CH3(CH2)7CH=CH(CH2)7CO2CH3(l) + H2 → CH3(CH2)7CH2CH2(CH2)7CO2CH3(l). At room temperature and pressure, a micro-scale experiment was performed using the set-up shown below in which 0.080 g of methyl oleate in an organic solvent was allowed to react with excess H2(g). The H2(g) flowed from the inverted measuring cylinder to the reacting flask through the tubing. (a) State one advantage of conducting this reaction in a micro-scale experiment. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：micro-scale hydrogenation set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"save cost on chemicals / minimise chemical hazards / save time on carrying out experiment / reduce the consumption of chemicals / reduce chemical waste"},
//   {"id":1723,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q9 (b) Explain why the right end of the tubing was placed at the uppermost position of the inverted measuring cylinder. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Prevent sucking back of water. / Prevent water from entering the reacting flask."},
//   {"id":1724,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q9 (c) State an expected observation in the inverted measuring cylinder during the reaction. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Water level inside the measuring cylinder rises. / The gas volume inside the measuring cylinder reduces."},
//   {"id":1725,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q9 (d) Calculate the theoretical volume of H2(g) needed for the reaction to complete at room temperature and pressure. (3 marks) (Molar volume of gas at room temperature and pressure = 24 dm3; Relative molecular mass: methyl oleate = 296.0)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Number of moles of methyl oleate used = 0.08/296 = 2.70×10-4. Minimum volume of H2(g) required = 2.70×10-4 × 24000 cm3 = 6.49 cm3."},
//   {"id":1726,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q9 (e) (i) Sketch, in the graph below, the variation of the volume of H2(g) in the measuring cylinder with time from start until the completion of the reaction. You should label this sketch as 'A'. (The measuring cylinder initially contained 10.0 cm3 of H2(g). The first few points have been given in the graph to facilitate the sketch.)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：volume-time graph blank）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1727,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q9 (e) (ii) In the same graph above, give another sketch as required in (i) but only using 0.040 g of methyl oleate for the reaction while the other conditions remain unchanged. You should label this sketch as 'B'.","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1728,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q11 Under certain conditions, a pink compound X reacts with NaOH(aq) to give a colourless product. Three trials of an experiment were conducted to study the kinetics of the reaction. Firstly, three NaOH(aq) solutions were prepared by mixing different volumes of 2.0 M NaOH(aq) and H2O(l) at 25°C. After that, one drop of X was added to each of them and the time needed for the pink colour to disappear was recorded. The relevant data is shown below: Trial 1: 5.0 cm3 NaOH, 0 cm3 H2O, time 61 s; Trial 2: 4.0 cm3 NaOH, 1.0 cm3 H2O, time 76 s; Trial 3: 3.0 cm3 NaOH, 2.0 cm3 H2O, time 101 s. (a) Why is it necessary to make the total volume of the reaction mixtures the same for the trials? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"To ensure fair comparisons between the trials. / To ensure the concentration of NaOH(aq) / reactant is the only variable. / The volume of NaOH(aq) used can represent the concentration of NaOH(aq) / reactant in the reaction mixtures."},
//   {"id":1729,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q11 (b) Given that at 25°C [H+(aq)][OH-(aq)] = 1.0×10-14 mol2 dm-6, calculate the pH of the NaOH(aq) solution prepared in Trial 2. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"[OH-(aq)] = 2.0 × (4.0/5.0) = 1.6 mol dm-3. [H+(aq)] × 1.6 = 1.0×10-14, [H+(aq)] = 6.25×10-15 mol dm-3, pH = -log(6.25×10-15) = 14.2. / Alternative: pH = 14 - (-log[OH-]) = 14 - (-0.2) = 14.2."},
//   {"id":1730,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q11 (c) Based on the information provided, deduce one factor which affects the rate of this reaction. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The concentration of NaOH(aq). The shorter the time for the (pink) colour disappeared, the faster the reaction. An increase in concentration of NaOH(aq) / reactant will result in an increase in the reaction rate."},
//   {"id":1731,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q11 (d) Detection of colour change using naked eye is not accurate enough. Suggest an instrumental method that can be used to more accurately detect the colour change. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Using colorimeter / measuring relative transmittance / absorbance of the mixture / spectrophotometer"},
//   {"id":1732,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q10 In an experiment performed under room conditions as shown below, 5.00 cm3 of H2O2(aq) decomposed into O2(g) and H2O(l) in the presence of a catalyst. O2(g) was continuously released from the start of the experiment until the third minute when a total of 60 cm3 of gas was collected. After that, no more gas was collected. (a) Calculate the initial concentration of the H2O2(aq), in mol dm-3. (2 marks) (Molar volume of gas at room conditions = 24 dm3)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：gas collection set-up）","points":30,"answerLetter":"2H2O2(aq) → 2H2O(l) + O2(g). Let the initial concentration be y mol dm-3. 0.005y = (60/24000)×2, 0.005y = 5×10-3, y = 1.0. Initial concentration is 1.0 mol dm-3."},
//   {"id":1733,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q10 (b) In the graph below, sketch the variation of the volume of gas collected with time in the first 4 minutes. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：volume-time graph blank）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1734,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q10 (c) The experiment is repeated using a H2O2(aq) at a higher temperature but other conditions remain unchanged. Explain whether the total volume of gas obtained would still be 60 cm3. (The volume of gas is measured at room conditions.) (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"60 cm3 of gas would still be collected because the number of moles of H2O2(aq) is the same for both experiments."},
//   {"id":1735,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q10 (d) Suggest another method that can be used to follow the progress of this reaction. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Follow the change in total pressure / mass in the system."},
//   {"id":1736,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q11 Consider the following reaction: Br2(aq) + HCO2H(aq) → 2HBr(aq) + CO2(g). In an experiment to study the rate of consumption of Br2(aq), equal volumes of 0.01 M Br2(aq) and 1.0 M HCO2H(aq) were mixed. The progress of the reaction was followed by measuring a certain parameter of the reaction system using a colorimeter. The graph below shows the results from the start of the reaction. (a) Assume that the rate of change of the parameter with time can represent the rate of reaction. (5 marks) (i) According to the shape of the curve above, suggest what the parameter should be.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：colorimeter graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"colour intensity / absorbance"},
//   {"id":1737,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q11 (a) (ii) The initial rate of the reaction can be determined by a suitable sketch on the above graph. Draw the suitable sketch on the above graph, and describe how the initial rate of the reaction can be obtained from the sketch.","points":30,"answerLetter":"On the graph, plot a tangent (a straight line) at time = 0 on the curve. The initial rate equals to the slope of the tangent /straight line."},
//   {"id":1738,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q11 (a) (iii) According to the graph above, the rate of reaction at A is higher than that at B. Explain this at molecular level.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The absorbance is (directly) proportional to [Br2(aq)] / number of Br2 molecules in the reaction mixture. The [Br2(aq)] / number of Br2 molecules in the reaction mixture at A is higher than that at B. Therefore the frequency of (effective) collisions between molecules at A is higher than that at B."},
//   {"id":1739,"subject":"化學","topic":"10. Rate of Reaction","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q11 (b) Suggest another method that can follow the progress of the reaction. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Measure the volume of CO2 gas formed (at different time). / Measure the (total) pressure of the system (at different time), given that the reaction proceeds in a closed system. / Measure the mass of the reaction mixture (at different time)."},
//   {"id":1740,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"SP Q11 The table below lists the equilibrium constants, Kc, for the reversible reaction H2(g) + CO2(g) ⇌ CO(g) + H2O(g) at three different temperatures. (5 marks)\nTemperature / K: 500, 700, 900\nKc: 7.76×10-3, 1.23×10-1, 6.03×10-1\n(a) Based on the above information, deduce whether the forward reaction is exothermic or endothermic.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Kc increases when the temperature of the system increases. This shows that the equilibrium shifts to the right when the temperature of the system increases. As a higher temperature favours endothermic reactions, the forward reaction is endothermic."},
//   {"id":1741,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"SP Q11 (b) 2.0 mol of H2(g) and 2.0 mol of CO2(g) are allowed to react in a 4.0 dm3 closed container. Calculate the concentration of CO(g), in mol dm-3, in the equilibrium mixture at 700 K.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Initial concentration of H2 = initial concentration of CO2 = 2.0/4.0 = 0.5 mol dm-3. H2(g)+CO2(g) ⇌ CO(g)+H2O(g). Equilibrium conc.: (0.5-x), (0.5-x), x, x. Kc = x2/(0.5-x)2 = 0.123. x/(0.5-x)=√0.123=0.3507, x=0.130. The concentration of CO(g) is 0.130 mol dm-3."},
//   {"id":1742,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"SP Q11 (c) State the effect of an increase in temperature on the rate of the backward reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"An increase in temperature would lead to an increase in the rate of the backward reaction since the kinetic energy of reactants in the backward reaction increases."},
//   {"id":1743,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"PP Q13 In an experiment, excess aqueous ammonia is added to an aqueous solution of copper(II) sulphate. The following equilibrium is established and the resulting solution is deep blue in colour. Cu2+(aq) + 4NH3(aq) ⇌ Cu(NH3)42+(aq). (a) Write an expression of Kc for this reaction. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Kc = [Cu(NH3)42+(aq)] / ([Cu2+(aq)][NH3(aq)]4)"},
//   {"id":1744,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"PP Q13 (b) If the above equilibrium mixture contains 0.0020 mol dm-3 of Cu2+(aq) ions, 0.0014 mol dm-3 of NH3(aq) and 0.0800 mol dm-3 of Cu(NH3)42+(aq) ions, calculate Kc under the conditions of the experiment. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Kc = 0.08 / (0.002 × (0.0014)4) = 1.04×1013 (mol m-3)-4."},
//   {"id":1745,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"PP Q13 (c) When H2SO4(aq) is added slowly to the equilibrium mixture until in excess, a blue precipitate is formed and the precipitate subsequently dissolves in the excess acid forming a blue solution. Account for these observations with the help of relevant chemical equation(s). (5 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"H2SO4(aq) reacts with NH3(aq): H+(aq) + NH3(aq) → NH4+(aq). Removal of NH3(aq) causes equilibrium Cu2+(aq)+4NH3(aq)⇌Cu(NH3)42+(aq) to shift left. NH3(aq) is a weak base: NH3(aq)+H2O(l)⇌NH4+(aq)+OH-(aq). When [Cu2+(aq)] builds up, it reacts with OH-(aq): Cu2+(aq)+2OH-(aq)→Cu(OH)2(s) (blue precipitate). When excess H2SO4 is added, Cu(OH)2(s)+2H+(aq)→Cu2+(aq)+2H2O(l), giving blue solution."},
//   {"id":1746,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q13 Consider the reaction represented by the equation below: Fe3+(aq) + SCN-(aq) ⇌ Fe(SCN)2+(aq). In an experiment, 25.0 cm3 of 0.010 M Fe2(SO4)3(aq) and 25.0 cm3 of 0.010 M KSCN(aq) were mixed in a conical flask at room temperature, and equilibrium was attained. (a) The concentration of Fe(SCN)2+(aq) in the mixture was 0.0043 M when equilibrium was attained. Calculate the equilibrium constant Kc for the above reaction at room temperature. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Initial [Fe3+] after mixing = 0.010×2×(1/2)=0.01 M, initial [SCN-]=0.010×(1/2)=0.005 M. Equilibrium: [Fe3+]=0.01-0.0043=0.0057 M, [SCN-]=0.005-0.0043=0.0007 M, [Fe(SCN)2+]=0.0043 M. Kc = 0.0043/(0.0057×0.0007)=1078 M-1."},
//   {"id":1747,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q13 (b) It is known that FePO4(s) is insoluble in water. Suggest what would be the effect on the equilibrium position if Na3PO4(s) is added to the equilibrium mixture. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The equilibrium position will shift to the left hand / reactant side."},
//   {"id":1748,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q12 At 250°C, the equilibrium constant Kc for the following reaction is 25 mol-1 dm3. PCl3(g) + Cl2(g) ⇌ PCl5(g). A 10.0 dm3 sealed container, which is maintained at 250°C, initially contains 0.50 mol of PCl3(g), 0.20 mol of Cl2(g) and 0.40 mol of PCl5(g). (a) For this system under the initial conditions, calculate its reaction quotient. Predict and explain, under the initial conditions, whether the forward reaction rate or the backward reaction rate would be greater. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Qc = [PCl5]/([PCl3][Cl2]) = (0.40/10.0) / ((0.50/10.0)×(0.20/10.0)) = 0.04/(0.05×0.02)=40 mol-1 dm3. As Qc > Kc, backward reaction rate is greater than the forward reaction rate."},
//   {"id":1749,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q12 (b) Calculate the concentration of Cl2(g) when the system attains equilibrium at 250°C. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"At equilibrium: [PCl5]=(0.04-y), [PCl3]=(0.05+y), [Cl2]=(0.02+y). Kc=(0.04-y)/((0.05+y)(0.02+y))=25. Solving: 25y2+1.75y-0.015=0 → y=0.0052. [Cl2]=0.02+0.0052=0.0252 mol dm-3."},
//   {"id":1750,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q12 (c) 0.10 mol of Cl2(g) is added to the equilibrium mixture in (b). Sketch, in the graph below, the variation of the concentration of Cl2(g) with time until a new equilibrium is attained. (Assume that the temperature of the system remains at 250°C throughout the whole process.) (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Cl2 concentration-time graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1751,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q13 Consider the reaction represented by the equation below: 2NO(g) + O2(g) ⇌ 2NO2(g). (a) In an experiment, 1.02 mol of NO(g) and 1.29 mol of O2(g) are mixed in a 50.0 dm3 closed container maintained at 980 K. When equilibrium is attained, 61.0% of NO(g) is consumed. (4 marks) (i) Calculate the equilibrium constant Kc for the above reaction under the experimental conditions.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Initial conc.: [NO]=1.02/50=0.0204 M, [O2]=1.29/50=0.0258 M. At equilibrium, NO consumed=0.0204×0.61=0.012444 M, [NO]=0.0204-0.012444=0.007956 M, [O2]=0.0258-0.012444/2=0.019578 M, [NO2]=0.012444 M. Kc = (0.012444)2/((0.007956)2×0.019578)=125 dm3 mol-1."},
//   {"id":1752,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q13 (a) (ii) Discuss whether Kc would change if additional NO(g) is introduced into the above equilibrium mixture.","points":30,"answerLetter":"No change, because Kc is independent of concentration / only depends on temperature."},
//   {"id":1753,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q13 (b) The values of Kc (in appropriate unit) for this reaction at different temperatures are shown below: 600K: 6.88×106, 700K: 2.97×105, 800K: 2.89×103, 900K: 4.68×102. Based on the above data, deduce whether the forward reaction is exothermic or endothermic.","points":30,"answerLetter":"As revealed from the data, when temperature increases, Kc decreases. Therefore the forward reaction is exothermic. As higher temperature favours endothermic side of reaction, so the forward reaction is exothermic."},
//   {"id":1754,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q11 Refer to the following chemical equation: H2O(l) ⇌ H+(aq) + OH-(aq) ΔH > 0. Under fixed conditions, [H2O(l)] is considered as a constant. In consideration of the definition of Kc, [H+(aq)][OH-(aq)] would also be a constant. (a) The pH of an aqueous solution is defined as -log[H+(aq)]. The pH of water equals 7.0 at 298 K. Find, at this temperature, the: (3 marks) (i) [H+(aq)]","points":30,"answerLetter":"[H+(aq)] = 10-7 mol dm-3 or 10-7 M."},
//   {"id":1755,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q11 (a) (ii) [H+(aq)][OH-(aq)]","points":30,"answerLetter":"[H+(aq)][OH-(aq)] = (10-7)×(10-7) = 1×10-14 mol2 dm-6."},
//   {"id":1756,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q11 (b) [H2O(l)] equals 55.6 mol dm-3 at 298 K. Suggest why [H2O(l)] is considered as a constant with reference to the values of [H+(aq)] and [OH-(aq)]. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Because [H2O(l)] >> [H+(aq)] or [OH-(aq)]."},
//   {"id":1757,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q11 (c) Explain whether the pH of water at 328 K would be less than 7.0, equal to 7.0, or greater than 7.0. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The pH of water would be less than 7. The dissociation of H2O(l) is endothermic. Increasing the temperature will shift the equilibrium position to the right."},
//   {"id":1758,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q10 In an experiment, 2.0 mol of SO2(g) and 2.0 mol of O2(g) are allowed to react in a closed container maintained at 950 K. The chemical equation for the reaction is shown below: 2SO2(g) + O2(g) ⇌ 2SO3(g) ΔH = -198 kJ mol-1. When the reaction attains dynamic equilibrium, 1.8 mol of SO3(g) is obtained. (a) What is meant by the term 'dynamic equilibrium'? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"At dynamic equilibrium, the rate of forward reaction is equal to the rate of backward reaction, and not equals zero. / At dynamic equilibrium, reactants are converted to products and products are converted to reactants at equal rate. No net change is observed."},
//   {"id":1759,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q10 (b) At 950 K, the equilibrium constant Kc for the above reaction is 878 dm3 mol-1. Calculate the volume of the container. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"2SO2(g) + O2(g) ⇌ 2SO3(g). Initial: 2.0, 2.0, 0. At equilibrium: 2.0-2x, 2.0-x, 2x = 1.8 → x=0.9. Equilibrium moles: SO2=0.2, O2=1.1, SO3=1.8. Kc = (1.8/V)2 / ((0.2/V)2×(1.1/V)) = (1.82×V)/(0.22×1.1) = 878. Solve: V = 878 × 0.22×1.1 / 1.82 = 878 × 0.0484 / 3.24 = 13.1 dm3? Let's recalc: (1.82)/(0.22×1.1) = 3.24/0.0484 = 66.94, then 66.94×V = 878, V=13.12 dm3. (Accept around 13.1 dm3)"},
//   {"id":1760,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q10 (c) If the above equilibrium mixture is subjected to each of the following changes, will the number of moles of SO3(g) obtained increase, decrease or remain unchanged? Explain your answer in each case. (2 marks) (i) increasing the temperature","points":30,"answerLetter":"Decrease. The reaction is exothermic. Increase in temperature will cause the equilibrium position to shift to the left."},
//   {"id":1761,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q10 (c) (ii) adding a suitable catalyst","points":30,"answerLetter":"No change. A catalyst will increase the rate of forward reaction and that of backward reaction to the same extent / A catalyst has no effect on the equilibrium position / percentage yield / yield."},
//   {"id":1762,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q11 The equation below shows the ionisation of 4-nitrophenol in water. (4-nitrophenol structure). At 25°C, the equilibrium constant Kc for the ionisation is 8.0×10-8 mol dm-3. (a) Write an expression for Kc. (You may use HA to represent 4-nitrophenol and A- to represent 4-nitrophenoxide ion.) (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Kc = [H+(aq)][A-(aq)] / [HA(aq)]"},
//   {"id":1763,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q11 (b) When the above ionisation attains equilibrium at 25°C, the pH of an aqueous solution of 4-nitrophenol is 2.4. Calculate the ratio of the concentration of 4-nitrophenol to the concentration of 4-nitrophenoxide ions in this solution. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"[H+] = 10-2.4 = 4.0×10-3 mol dm-3. Kc = 8.0×10-8 = (4.0×10-3)[A-]/[HA]. [HA]/[A-] = (4.0×10-3)/(8.0×10-8) = 50000."},
//   {"id":1764,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q11 (c) Suggest if there is any colour change when NaOH(aq) is added gradually into the solution in (b). Explain your answer. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The equilibrium position will shift to right when H+(aq) ions are consumed by NaOH(aq). HA is colourless while A- is yellow. Increase in [A-] causes the solution changes from colourless to yellow (or the colour / yellow colour becomes more intense)."},
//   {"id":1765,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q11 (d) Suggest one possible use of 4-nitrophenol in acid-base titration experiments. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"indicator"},
//   {"id":1766,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q13 An experiment was performed for a reversible reaction involving X(g), Y(g) and Z(g) in a closed container of 2.0 dm3 at a constant temperature. The graph below shows the relevant experimental data. (a) According to the graph, how do you know that the reaction is reversible? (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：concentration-time graph for equilibrium）","points":30,"answerLetter":"None of the final concentrations of X(g), Y(g) and Z(g) is equal to zero. X, Y, Z co-exist in the system, and their concentrations remain unchanged after a long period of time. / The concentration of the reactant, Y, is still not equal to zero after a long period of time."},
//   {"id":1767,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q13 (b) Calculate the equilibrium constant Kc for the reaction at the temperature of the experiment. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"From graph: [X]=0.60, [Y]=0.30, [Z]=0.20. The balanced equation: 3X + ? ... Based on graph slopes likely: 3X(g) + Y(g) ⇌ Z(g)? But we need to deduce from data. Typical: 3X + Y ⇌ Z? Actually from graph: initial: maybe 0,0.6,0? Let's assume the reaction is 3X(g) + Y(g) ⇌ Z(g) or similar. Without seeing graph, we follow given answer in file: Kc = [X]3[Z]/[Y]2 = (0.60)3(0.20)/(0.30)2 = 0.48 mol2 dm-6."},
//   {"id":1768,"subject":"化學","topic":"11. Chemical Equilibrium","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q13 (c) Comment on the following statement: (1 mark) The rate of the forward reaction is zero at the 25th minute after the start of the reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The statement is INCORRECT. At the 25th minute after the reaction has started, the reaction attained dynamic equilibrium. The rate of forward reaction is equal to the rate of backward reaction, and both of the rates are not equal to zero."},
//   {"id":1769,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"SP Q14 Compare the acid base properties of sodium oxide (Na2O) and sulphur dioxide (SO2) with reference to how they interact with water molecules. (4 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Na2O is ionic in nature while SO2 is covalent in nature. Na2O is a basic oxide and SO2 is an acidic oxide. When Na2O dissolves in water, the oxide ions react with water to give hydroxide ions, making the solution alkaline. Na2O(aq) + H2O(l) → 2Na+(aq) + 2OH-(aq). When sulphur dioxide is dissolved in water, the sulphur which acquires a partial positive charge would be attacked by the lone pair electrons of the oxygen atom in water molecule, giving sulphurous acid. The acid formed may be ionized to give H+ ions, so the resulting solution is acidic. SO2(aq) + H2O(l) ⇌ 2H+(aq) + SO32-(aq). To summarize, Na2O undergoes hydrolysis to give an alkaline solution while SO2 reacts to give an acidic solution."},
//   {"id":1770,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"PP Q9 (a) Using the following notations to complete the table below so as to provide information about the structure and acid-base property of the oxides of Period 3 elements. (2 marks) Notations: IC: ionic crystal; CN: covalent network; SM: simple molecular structure; AC: acidic; BA: basic; AM: amphoteric. Table: MgO, Al2O3, SiO2, P4O10, SO2.","points":30,"answerLetter":"MgO: Structure IC, Acid-base property BA; Al2O3: Structure IC, Acid-base property AM; SiO2: Structure CN, Acid-base property AC; P4O10: Structure SM, Acid-base property AC; SO2: Structure SM, Acid-base property AC."},
//   {"id":1771,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"PP Q9 (b) By considering the trend of acid-base property and that of bonding of these oxides, state the relationship between the two trends. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Ionic oxides are basic, while covalent oxides are acidic."},
//   {"id":1772,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q16 Consider the following oxides: Na2O, MgO, Al2O3, SiO2, P4O10, SO2, Cl2O. (a) Which of the oxides listed above can conduct electricity in molten state? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Na2O, MgO, Al2O3."},
//   {"id":1773,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q16 (b) Explain why SiO2 has the highest melting point among the covalent oxides listed above. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"SiO2 has a giant covalent structure, and the Si and O atoms are linked by strong covalent bonds. Other covalent oxides are discrete molecules attracted by weak van der Waals' forces / weak intermolecular forces / weak dipolar interactions."},
//   {"id":1774,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2012 Q16 (c) Write a chemical equation for the reaction between Al2O3(s) and NaOH(aq). (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Al2O3 + 2OH- + 3H2O → 2Al(OH)4- / Al2O3 + 2NaOH + 3H2O → 2NaAl(OH)4."},
//   {"id":1775,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2013 Q13* Lithium, beryllium, carbon (graphite) and nitrogen are elements of the second period of the Periodic Table. Arrange them in increasing order of melting point, and explain the order in terms of structure and bonding. (5 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Nitrogen < Lithium < Beryllium < Carbon (graphite). N2 has the lowest melting point as it has a simple molecular structure, only weak van der Waals' forces / intermolecular forces need to be overcome in melting. Both Li and Be have metallic structure, metallic bond in Li is weaker than that in Be. So Li < Be in melting points. C has the highest melting point as it has a giant covalent structure, large amount of energy is needed to break millions of strong covalent bonds between atoms in melting."},
//   {"id":1776,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q11 Vanadium is a transition metal, its chemical symbol is V. The formulae and the colours of three aqueous vanadium-containing ions are shown below: VO2+(aq) blue, V3+(aq) green, V2+(aq) violet. (a) Based on the given information, suggest TWO properties of vanadium to characterise it as a transition metal. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Vanadium exhibits variable oxidation numbers and its ions in aqueous solutions carry colours."},
//   {"id":1777,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q11 (b) Vanadium also forms the ion VO2+(aq). In the presence of acid, 1.0 mol of VO2+(aq) ions and 1.0 mol of SO2(g) react completely to form SO42-(aq) ions and one of the above aqueous vanadium-containing ions. (3 marks) (i) By considering the amount of electrons transferred, deduce the final colour of the solution obtained.","points":30,"answerLetter":"1 mol of VO2+(aq) ions gains 2 mol of electrons from 1 mol of SO2(g) to become 1 mol of V3+(aq) ions. V3+(aq) ion is green in colour."},
//   {"id":1778,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2014 Q11 (b) (ii) Write a chemical equation for the reaction in (i).","points":30,"answerLetter":"SO2(g) + VO2+(aq) → SO42-(aq) + V3+(aq)"},
//   {"id":1779,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2015 Q10 (a) For each of the oxides below, draw its electron diagram (showing electrons in the outermost shells only), and state its behaviour in water. (4 marks) (i) Na2O (ii) Cl2O<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Na2O electron diagram and Cl2O electron diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"For Na2O: electron diagram shows Na+ with no outer electrons and O2- with octet. It behaves as a basic oxide, reacts with water to give NaOH. For Cl2O: electron diagram shows Cl-O-Cl with lone pairs. It behaves as an acidic oxide, reacts with water to give HOCl."},
//   {"id":1780,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2016 Q14* Arrange sodium, aluminium, silicon and sulphur in decreasing order of electrical conductivity at room conditions, and explain your answer in terms of bonding and structure. (5 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Electrical conductivity: aluminium > sodium > silicon > sulphur. Both aluminium and sodium have giant metallic structures with delocalised / mobile electrons so that electrical conductivity of them is high / their electrical conductivity is higher than that of silicon and sulphur. The number of delocalised / mobile electrons of aluminium is more than that of sodium so that electrical conductivity of aluminium is higher than that of sodium. Silicon has giant covalent structure and its electrons are not mobile and cannot conduct electricity / its electrical conductivity is lower than that of aluminium and sodium. or Silicon has giant covalent structure and its electrons are not mobile. But silicon is a semi-metal and can conduct electricity in some conditions. Sulphur has simple molecular structure and its electrons are not mobile and cannot conduct electricity / its electrical conductivity is lower than that of aluminium and sodium."},
//   {"id":1781,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2017 Q14* At 60°C, MnO4-(aq) reacts with C2O42-(aq) in an acidic medium to give Mn2+(aq), CO2(g) and H2O(l). The graph below shows the variation of the colour intensity of the reaction mixture with time. Based on the information above, write the chemical equation for the reaction and illustrate THREE characteristics of transition metals exhibited by manganese. (6 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：colour intensity vs time graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"2MnO4-(aq) + 5C2O42-(aq) + 16H+(aq) → 2Mn2+(aq) + 10CO2(g) + 8H2O(l). Manganese exhibits variable oxidation numbers. The oxidation number of manganese changes from +7 in MnO4-(aq) ions to +2 in Mn2+(aq) ions in the reaction. Manganese forms coloured ions in aqueous solutions. MnO4-(aq) ions exhibit purple / Mn2+(aq) ions exhibit pale pink. From the graph, it shows that the reaction rate increases when Mn2+(aq) ions form / when the reaction proceeds. It shows that Mn2+(aq) ions act as a catalyst for the reaction."},
//   {"id":1782,"subject":"化學","topic":"12. Patterns in the Chemical World","type":"fill","text":"2018 Q14* Using Na2O, Al2O3 and SO2 as examples, illustrate the acid-base behaviour of the oxides of the third period elements with the aid of relevant reactions. (6 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Na2O(s) dissolves in water to give NaOH(aq) / Na2O(s) reacts with HCl(aq) to give NaCl(aq) and H2O. Na2O(s) + H2O(l) → 2NaOH(aq) / Na2O(s) + 2HCl(aq) → 2NaCl(aq) + H2O(l). Al2O3(s) reacts with HCl(aq) to give AlCl3(aq) and H2O. Al2O3(s) + 6HCl(aq) → 2AlCl3(aq) + 3H2O(l). Al2O3(s) reacts with NaOH(aq) to give NaAl(OH)4(aq). Al2O3(s) + 2NaOH(aq) + 3H2O(l) → 2NaAl(OH)4(aq). SO2(g) dissolves in water to give H2SO3(aq) / SO2(g) reacts with NaOH(aq) to give Na2SO3(aq) and H2O. SO2(g) + H2O(l) → H2SO3(aq) / SO2(g) + 2NaOH(aq) → Na2SO3(aq) + H2O(l). Na2O is a basic (alkaline) oxide, Al2O3 is an amphoteric oxide, and SO2 is an acidic oxide."},
//   {"id":1783,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) In acid solution, chlorate ions (ClO3-) slowly oxidize chloride ions to chlorine. The following kinetic data are obtained at 25°C: (10 marks) (i) Write the balanced equation for this reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"ClO3-(aq) + 5Cl-(aq) + 6H+(aq) → 3Cl2(g) + 3H2O(l)"},
//   {"id":1784,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) (ii) Determine the order of the reaction with respect to each reactant. (Data table: [ClO3-]/M, [Cl-]/M, [H+]/M, initial rate/M s-1)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Initial rate of reaction increased by four times when concentration of H+(aq) is doubled while the concentration of ClO3-(aq) and Cl-(aq) remain constant. Hence, the order of reaction with respect to H+(aq) is 2. Initial rate of reaction doubled when concentration of ClO3-(aq) is doubled while the concentration of Cl-(aq) and H+(aq) remain constant. Hence, the order of reaction with respect to ClO3-(aq) is 1. Initial rate of reaction doubled when concentration of Cl-(aq) is doubled while the concentration of ClO3-(aq) and H+(aq) remain constant. Hence, the order of reaction with respect to Cl-(aq) is 1. Hence, we have rate = k[ClO3-(aq)][Cl-(aq)][H+(aq)]2."},
//   {"id":1785,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) (iii) Determine the rate constant at this temperature.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Using the information given from row 1: 1.0×10-5 = k(0.08)(0.15)(0.20)2, k = 0.0208 mol-3 dm9 s-1."},
//   {"id":1786,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) (iv) If the rate of the reaction is found to be doubled when the temperature is raised by 10°C, deduce the activation energy of the reaction. (Gas constant R = 8.31 J K-1 mol-1)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Let k1 and k2 be the rate constants at 25°C (298 K) and 35°C (308 K) respectively, i.e. k2 = 2k1. By Arrhenius equation: ln(k2/k1) = (Ea/R)(1/T1 - 1/T2). ln2 = (Ea/8.31)(1/298 - 1/308) = (Ea/8.31)(0.000109). Ea = (0.693 × 8.31) / 0.000109 = 52800 J mol-1 = 52.8 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1787,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (b) For the industrial preparation of nitric acid from nitrogen, give the chemical reactions and the conditions under which they take place. (6 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"In ammonia plant, purified and dried nitrogen and hydrogen are mixed in a ratio of 1 to 3 and compressed at 200 atm to 250 atm. The mixture is heated at 450°C to 500°C in the heat exchanger. The hot gaseous mixture is then passed over finely divided and enriched iron powder in the catalytic converter. Ammonia is produced: N2(g) + 3H2(g) ⇌ 2NH3(g) (Fe catalyst, 723K, 200 atm). Nitric acid is manufactured by catalytic oxidation of ammonia: 4NH3(g) + 5O2(g) → 4NO(g) + 6H2O(g) (Pt catalyst). 2NO(g) + O2(g) → 2NO2(g). 4NO2(g) + O2(g) + 2H2O(l) → 4HNO3(aq)."},
//   {"id":1788,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (c) The reaction for the production of methylpropene from 2-bromo-2-methylpropane is represented by the following equation: (CH3)3CBr + NaOH → (CH3)2C=CH2 + NaBr + H2O. (4 marks) (i) With reference to green chemistry, calculate the atom economy of the reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Atom economy = (molar mass of atoms in desired product) / (sum of molar mass of all products) × 100% = (12.0×4 + 1.0×8) / ((12.0×4+1.0×8) + (12.0×2+1.0×6+16.0) + (23.0+79.9)) × 100% = 56 / (56+46+102.9) × 100% = 56 / 204.9 × 100% = 27.3%."},
//   {"id":1789,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (c) (ii) Apart from atom economy, suggest TWO other factors that scientists should consider in order to conduct a green production process.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Any TWO of the following: waste prevention at source; designing for energy efficiency; using renewable raw materials; using catalysts; using a solvent-free system or safer and benign solvent system; using less hazardous chemical syntheses; producing safer chemical products; reducing derivatives; designing degradable chemical products."},
//   {"id":1790,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) L-Ascorbic acid, also known as vitamin C, is synthesised by the Reichstein process as shown below. (i) State ONE importance of the Reichstein process. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Reichstein process flow diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Reichstein process is used for synthesising vitamin C, which is in great demand as it cannot be synthesised in human body. / Reichstein process provides a synthetic route to convert D-Glucose, a sugar which is highly abundant and cheap, to L-ascorbic acid. / The enzymatic reaction in Reichstein process inverts the sugars from D- to L-isomer."},
//   {"id":1791,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (ii) The reagents used in Step 1 are H2(g) and Ni(s). Name the type of reaction involved. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"reduction / catalytic hydrogenation"},
//   {"id":1792,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (iii) Step 2 is an oxidation with the use of an enzyme, sorbitol dehydrogenase. This step is carried out at pH 4 to 6, and at about 30°C. (2 marks) (1) Explain why this step is NOT carried out with commonly used oxidising agents.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Commonly used oxidising agents will also oxidise the other hydroxyl groups in D-sorbitol / are not selective as compared with the enzyme. / The enzyme can selectively oxidise the second -OH group in D-sorbitol to give L-sorbose."},
//   {"id":1793,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (iii) (2) Suggest why this step is carried out at pH 4 to 6.","points":30,"answerLetter":"At pH<4 or pH>6, the enzyme will undergo denaturation / the (tertiary/secondary) structure of the enzyme will change leading to loss of catalytic activity."},
//   {"id":1794,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (iv) A method, with the use of a lactonase enzyme such as gluconolactonase, has been adopted for the conversion of KGA to L-ascorbic acid. Suggest TWO reasons why this method is considered greener than the corresponding one in the above-shown Reichstein process. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"This method uses a catalyst (the enzyme) instead of stoichiometric reagents. It uses less hazardous chemicals (e.g. MeOH / acid)."},
//   {"id":1795,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (b) The atmospheric oxidation of L-ascorbic acid is a first order reaction. (i) What do you understand by the term 'first order reaction'? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The rate of reaction is proportional to the concentration of the reactant. / The half-life of the reaction is constant."},
//   {"id":1796,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (b) (ii) The table below lists the rate constants k for this reaction at four different temperatures T: T/K: 313, 323, 333, 343; k/10-3 h-1: 27.0, 35.4, 50.4, 65.4. By plotting a suitable graph, determine the activation energy Ea of this reaction. (5 marks) (Gas constant R = 8.31 J K-1 mol-1)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Arrhenius plot）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Plot log k against 1/T. Slope = -Ea/(2.3R). From data: 1/T (×10-3): 3.195, 3.096, 3.003, 2.915; log k: -1.569, -1.451, -1.298, -1.184. Slope ≈ -1402. Ea = 1402 × 8.31 × 2.3 = 26780 J mol-1 = 26.8 kJ mol-1. (Acceptable range: 24.5 to 29.0 kJ mol-1)"},
//   {"id":1797,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (c) The diagram below shows a membrane cell used in chloroalkali industry for the production of hydrogen, chlorine and concentrated sodium hydroxide. (i) With the aid of chemical equations, account for the formation of hydrogen, chlorine and concentrated sodium hydroxide in the membrane cell. (5 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：membrane cell diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"At the cathode: 2H+(aq) + 2e- → H2(g). At the anode: 2Cl-(aq) → Cl2(g) + 2e-. The membrane only allows cations to pass through it. As there is a higher concentration of cations in the anode compartment (because anions are removed), there will be a net flow of Na+(aq) ions from the anode compartment to the cathode compartment, and concentrated NaOH(aq) is formed."},
//   {"id":1798,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (c) (ii) Chlorine bleach can be made by treating chlorine with dilute sodium hydroxide solution at room temperature. Write the chemical equation of the reaction involved. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cl2(g) + 2NaOH(aq) → NaOCl(aq) + NaCl(aq) + H2O(l) / Cl2(g) + 2OH-(aq) → OCl-(aq) + Cl-(aq) + H2O(l)."},
//   {"id":1799,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (c) (iii) A student learnt that sodium chloride is highly abundant and that hydrogen is a non-polluting fuel. The student made the following remark: \"Electrolysis of brine can be used in large scale manufacture of hydrogen to help reduce air pollution problems.\" Do you agree with the student? Explain. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Accept both 'Yes' and 'No' answers. For 'No' answers: The production of H2 in chloroalkali industry requires the use of electricity, which is commonly generated by burning fossil fuel (a major source of air pollutants). Cl2(g) is the main product of the chloroalkali industry. Large scale production of H2(g) will yield surplus Cl2(g). The disposal of the unused Cl2(g) is costly and will cause air pollution problems. For 'Yes' answers: Burning of H2(g) gives water only. If there is a cheap source of electricity (e.g. photovoltaic cell), production of H2(g) by electrolysis of brine can be a means of reducing air pollution problems."},
//   {"id":1800,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) Ammonia can be produced by Haber process through the reaction of nitrogen and hydrogen at about 500°C and 200 atm in the presence of a catalyst. The chemical equation for the reaction is shown below: N2(g) + H2(g) ⇌ 2NH3(g) ΔH < 0. (i) (3 marks) (1) What is the catalyst used in the Haber process?","points":30,"answerLetter":"Finely divided iron / iron oxide."},
//   {"id":1801,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (i) (2) Explain the effect of a catalyst on a chemical reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"It can increase / decrease the rate of reaction by providing an alternative pathway that requires lower / higher activation energy."},
//   {"id":1802,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (ii) Suggest how hydrogen can be obtained for the Haber process, and give a chemical equation involved. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Steam reforming of natural gas. CH4(g) + H2O(g) ⇌ H2(g) + CO(g) / CO(g) + H2O(g) ⇌ H2(g) + CO2(g)."},
//   {"id":1803,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (iii) You are given that for the formation of NH3(g) from N2(g) and H2(g) at 300°C and 1000 atm the yield of NH3(g) at equilibrium is about 98%. However, the operation conditions of the Haber process in industry are set at about 500°C and 200 atm with yield of NH3(g) at equilibrium of about 20%. With reference to the given information, explain why such operation conditions are chosen in industry. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The higher temperature is used to speed up the reaction. Not very high pressure is applied in consideration of mechanical design and safety concerns."},
//   {"id":1804,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (iv) In the Haber process, the product mixture is removed from the reaction chamber before reaching the yield of about 20%. Explain why this is so. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"It takes a long time to reach equilibrium that the NH3(g) is of highest yield to be attained. It can increase the total amount of NH3(g) produced per unit time."},
//   {"id":1805,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (b) Methanol is an important compound in the chemical industry. Methanol can be produced from syngas made from methane. (i) Why is methanol an important compound in the chemical industry? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Methanol is important because it is a 1-carbon compound and acts as a starting material to make organic compounds with larger carbon numbers."},
//   {"id":1806,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (b) (ii) Write the chemical equation for the reaction in the production of methanol from syngas, and state the conditions required. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"CO(g) + 2H2(g) ⇌ CH3OH(g). Catalyst: Cu / ZnO / Al2O3. Temperature: 200-300°C. Pressure: 50-100 atm."},
//   {"id":1807,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (b) (iii) State an advancement of the methanol production technology. Explain why it is considered as an advancement. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Direct conversion of methane to methanol with the use of a metal oxide catalyst at high temperature and atmospheric pressure. The conversion uses a catalytic reagent. / Oxidation of methane to methanol by microbial reactions. The oxidation has higher energy efficiency. / Conversion of biomass to syngas/biogas for methanol production. The conversion uses renewable feed stocks. / Carbon dioxide in flue gas can be converted to form methanol. The conversion helps to reduce the release of carbon dioxide to the atmosphere."},
//   {"id":1808,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (c) Three trials of an experiment were performed at the same temperature for the study of the kinetics of the following reaction: 2NO(g) + 2H2(g) → N2(g) + 2H2O(g). The table below shows the data obtained: Trial 1: [NO]=2.50×10-2, [H2]=5.00×10-3, rate=1.20×10-6; Trial 2: [NO]=2.50×10-2, [H2]=1.00×10-2, rate=2.40×10-6; Trial 3: [NO]=1.25×10-2, [H2]=1.00×10-2, rate=2.40×10-7. (i) Explain why 'initial rate' is commonly used in the study of the kinetics of a reaction. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Initial rate is used because the initial concentrations of reactants are known."},
//   {"id":1809,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (c) (ii) Deduce the order of reaction with respect to NO(g) and that to H2(g). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Compare experiments 2 & 3, [H2] remains the same but [NO] is halved, rate is decreased by a factor of 4. Therefore reaction order with respect to [NO] is two. Compare experiments 1 & 2, [NO] remains the same but [H2] is doubled, rate is also doubled. Therefore reaction order with respect to [H2] is one."},
//   {"id":1810,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (c) (iii) State the rate equation for the reaction, and calculate its rate constant at the temperature of the experiment. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Rate = k[NO]2[H2]. Using data from experiment 1: 1.20×10-6 = k × (2.50×10-2)2 × (5.00×10-3). k = 0.384 dm6 mol-2 s-1."},
//   {"id":1811,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (a) For gaseous reactions, an increase in temperature leads to an increase in reaction rate. (i) The graph below shows the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution curves of molecular kinetic energies of a gas at two temperatures T1 and T2. (5 marks) (1) What do the axes, x and y, in the above graph respectively represent?<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution curves）","points":30,"answerLetter":"x --- molecular kinetic energy; y --- fraction / percentage of molecules."},
//   {"id":1812,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (a) (i) (2) With reference to the above graph, suggest why an increase in temperature can lead to an increase in the reaction rate of a gaseous reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"An increase in temperature from T1 to T2 will increase the average kinetic energy of the molecules. This will increase the collision frequency and result in greater effective collisions among molecules. There is a larger portion of molecules will have kinetic energy greater than Ea."},
//   {"id":1813,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (a) (ii) The rate constant of a certain reaction increases with temperature as shown in the following table: T/K: 298, 308, 318, 328; k/s-1: 2.5×10-3, 5.0×10-3, 9.5×10-3, 1.9×10-2. Determine the activation energy of the reaction by graphical method. (5 marks) (Gas constant R = 8.31 J K-1 mol-1)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Plot log k against 1/T. Slope = -Ea/(2.3R). From data: 1/T (×10-3): 3.356, 3.247, 3.145, 3.049; log k: -2.602, -2.301, -2.022, -1.721. Slope ≈ -1.73×103. Ea = 1.73×103 × 8.31 × 2.3 = 33.1 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1814,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) Eugenol benzoate is a commonly used food flavouring agent. Eugenol benzoate can be synthesised from the reaction of eugenol with benzoic acid in the presence of sulphuric acid as a homogeneous catalyst. (i) Suggest why a catalyst can speed up a reaction. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：eugenol and eugenol benzoate structures）","points":30,"answerLetter":"A catalyst provides an alternative pathway with lower activation energy."},
//   {"id":1815,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (ii) For the above reaction, would the use of concentrated sulphuric acid or that of dilute sulphuric acid give a better yield of eugenol benzoate? Explain your answer. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Concentrated H2SO4. Dilute H2SO4 contains a lot of H2O. Water can shift the equilibrium position to the left / cause hydrolysis of eugenol benzoate, and thus lowers the yield of the product. / Conc. H2SO4 is a dehydrating agent / removes water from the product side of the reaction, and will shift the equilibrium position to the right."},
//   {"id":1816,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (iii) Eugenol benzoate can also be synthesised from the reaction of eugenol with benzoic acid in the presence of a solid acid as a heterogeneous catalyst. With reference to the synthesis of eugenol benzoate, state ONE advantage of using a homogeneous catalyst and ONE advantage of using a heterogeneous catalyst. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Homogeneous catalyst --- H2SO4 is readily available. Heterogeneous catalyst --- can be reused / easily be regenerated / easily be separated."},
//   {"id":1817,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) Propylene oxide is a chemical commonly used in the plastics industry. Two methods for producing propylene oxide are shown below: Method 1: CH3CH=CH2 + Cl2 + H2O → CH3CH(OH)CH2Cl → (with NaOH) propylene oxide. Method 2: CH3CH=CH2 + H2O2 → propylene oxide + H2O. (i) The Cl2 and NaOH used in Method 1 are products of the chloroalkali industry. Briefly describe how these two chemicals are produced. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Chlorine can be produced by electrolysis of brine / concentrated sodium chloride solution using flowing mercury cell / diaphragm cell / membrane cell. Cl-(aq) ions are discharged at the anode to give Cl2(g). Diaphragm cell / membrane cell: H+(aq) ions are discharged at the cathode. With the removal of Cl-(aq) ions and H+(aq) ions, the resultant electrolytic solution contains NaOH(aq) in high concentration. OR Flowing mercury cell: Sodium amalgam produced at cathode reacts with water forming NaOH(aq)."},
//   {"id":1818,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (ii) The atom economy of Method 1 is 29.7%. Calculate the atom economy of Method 2. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Atom economy = (molar mass of propylene oxide) / (molar mass of propylene + H2O2) × 100% = 58 / (42+34) × 100% = 58/76 × 100% = 76.32%."},
//   {"id":1819,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (iii) Discuss, from TWO different perspectives, whether Method 1 or Method 2 is greener. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Method 2 is greener. Any two of the following: It has a higher atom economy. It produce less waste (less side products) and less treatment is required. Less hazardous chemicals are used (method 1 uses more toxic Cl2)."},
//   {"id":1820,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (iv) Comment on the following statement, and explain your answer: (2 marks) \"A reaction with a high atom economy should also have a high yield.\"","points":30,"answerLetter":"The calculation of atom economy is based on a 100% completed reaction. Most reactions do not go to completion and the yield is related to the extent of reaction. Thus a reaction with high atom economy does not necessarily have a high yield."},
//   {"id":1821,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) What is meant by the term 'activation energy'? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"'Activation energy' refers to the minimum energy possessed by the colliding reactant particles in order that a reaction can occur."},
//   {"id":1822,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) (ii) At room temperature, ethanol can be produced by fermentation of sugars in the presence of yeast. State the function of yeast, and explain why this function fails at high temperatures. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Yeast provides enzyme / catalyst. At high temperature, the enzyme (yeast) is denatured / destroyed so that it cannot function as a catalyst."},
//   {"id":1823,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) (iii) Vitamin C can be obtained from fruits. Explain why it is still necessary to synthesise vitamin C industrially. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"It is to solve the problems of inadequate or shrinking supply of vitamin C."},
//   {"id":1824,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) (iv) Give TWO important chemicals manufactured in chloroalkali industry. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"chlorine, hydrogen, sodium hydroxide (any two)."},
//   {"id":1825,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) The kinetics of the following reaction at a certain temperature were studied: BrO3-(aq) + 6I-(aq) + 6H+(aq) → 3I2(aq) + Br-(aq) + 3H2O(l). Several trials of an experiment were attempted under the same experimental conditions except varying the initial concentration of BrO3-(aq) to measure the initial rate of formation of I2(aq). The following graph shows the experimental results obtained from these trials. (i) What is meant by the term 'initial rate'? (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：initial rate vs [BrO3-] graph）","points":30,"answerLetter":"'Initial rate' is the instantaneous rate at the start of a reaction."},
//   {"id":1826,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (ii) Suggest a method, with justification, to follow the progress of the formation of I2(aq). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Follow the colour intensity of the solution / by colorimetry. The solution changes from colourless to brown."},
//   {"id":1827,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (iii) With reference to the graph above, deduce the order of reaction with respect to BrO3-(aq). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The initial rate is directly proportional to [BrO3-(aq)]. Therefore, the order of reaction with respect to BrO3-(aq) = 1."},
//   {"id":1828,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (iv) The table below lists the information for two trials of an experiment on the same reaction performed at the same temperature: Trial 1: [BrO3-]=0.17, [I-]=0.15, [H+]=0.10, rate=2.30×10-3; Trial 2: [BrO3-]=0.17, [I-]=0.30, [H+]=0.20, rate=1.84×10-2. (3 marks) (1) Given that the order of reaction with respect to I-(aq) is 1, deduce the order of reaction with respect to H+(aq).","points":30,"answerLetter":"Rate = k[BrO3-][I-][H+]y. (2.30×10-3)/(1.84×10-2) = (0.17×0.15×0.10y)/(0.17×0.30×0.20y) = (0.15/0.30)×(0.10/0.20)y = 0.5×(0.5)y. 0.125 = 0.5×(0.5)y, (0.5)y = 0.25, y=2. The reaction is second order with respect to H+(aq)."},
//   {"id":1829,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (iv) (2) Based on Trial 1, deduce the initial rate of reaction with respect to BrO3-(aq) under the experimental conditions.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Rate of consumption of BrO3- = (1/3) × rate of formation of I2. Based on Trial 1, initial rate of consumption of BrO3-(aq) = 2.30×10-3 × (1/3) = 7.67×10-4 mol dm-3 s-1."},
//   {"id":1830,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) Read the following passage regarding the Haber process and answer the questions that follow. (i) Explain why the Haber process is an important industrial process. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The ammonia produced by the Haber process can be used to manufacture fertilisers, explosives, etc."},
//   {"id":1831,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (ii) Why does the Haber process need natural gas as a raw material? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Natural gas remains the more convenient / cheap way to provide hydrogen as feedstock for the production of ammonia in the Haber process."},
//   {"id":1832,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (iii) Explain why making the catalyst in highly porous form can increase the efficiency of the catalyst. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Provide a larger surface area that makes the catalyst more effective."},
//   {"id":1833,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (iv) State TWO factors related to chemistry that have been considered before setting the optimal reaction temperature and pressure. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"equilibrium position / yield; reaction rate."},
//   {"id":1834,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (v) Suggest one design so that the overall conversion percentage of nitrogen in the process can be increased significantly without changing the optimal reaction conditions. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Any unreacted reactants are reused / recycled so that they can react again. / Removing ammonia from the product mixture so as to shift the equilibrium position to the product side."},
//   {"id":1835,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (vi) The South American country Chile has a lot of natural nitrate mines. History tells us that the success of the Haber process had led to some impacts on the society of Chile. Suggest one of these impacts. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"As the demand for mining the natural nitrate to produce fertilisers drops drastically, the mining work was no longer profitable / mining work might be closed / it could lead to a high unemployment rate."},
//   {"id":1836,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) A certain reaction is zeroth order with respect to I2(aq) and first order with respect to both CH3COCH3(aq) and H+(aq). (2 marks) (1) State the effect, if any, of a change in the concentration of I2(aq) in the reaction mixture on the rate of the reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"No effect."},
//   {"id":1837,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) (i) (2) Write the rate equation for the reaction.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Rate = k[CH3COCH3(aq)][H+(aq)]."},
//   {"id":1838,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) (ii) Write a chemical equation for the reaction in forming ammonia in the Haber process. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"3H2 + N2 ⇌ 2NH3"},
//   {"id":1839,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) (iii) The rate constant of a certain reaction doubles when the temperature is increased from 298 K to 308 K. Calculate the activation energy of the reaction. (2 marks) (Gas constant R = 8.31 J K-1 mol-1; Arrhenius equation: log k = constant - Ea/(2.3RT))","points":30,"answerLetter":"log(k2/k1) = (Ea/(2.3R))(1/T1 - 1/T2). log2 = (Ea/(2.3×8.31))(1/298 - 1/308) = (Ea/19.113)(0.000109). Ea = (0.3010 × 19.113) / 0.000109 = 52779 J mol-1 = 52.8 kJ mol-1."},
//   {"id":1840,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) Ethanoic acid can be produced by two routes as listed below: Route (1): sugar solution → (yeast) CH3CH2OH(aq) → (O2) CH3COOH(aq). Route (2): CH3OH(l) + CO(g) → (180°C;30 atm) CH3COOH(l). (i) The reactions in both Routes (1) and (2) require the use of catalysts. (4 marks) (1) Draw, in the same sketch, TWO labelled energy profiles for a reaction, one with a catalyst and the other one without catalyst. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：energy profile diagram with and without catalyst）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1841,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) (i) (2) Theoretically, catalysts are not consumed in reactions. Suggest why it is still necessary to replace the used catalyst from time to time in industrial processes. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Catalysts can be poisoned."},
//   {"id":1842,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) (ii) Suggest TWO reasons why Route (1) is considered as a green process. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Any TWO of the following: A catalyst / enzyme is used. The reagent (O2) used is non-toxic. The feedstock (sugars) is renewable. The wastes formed are biodegradable."},
//   {"id":1843,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) (iii) Suggest TWO reasons why ethanoic acid used in the plastic industry is manufactured by Route (2) instead of Route (1). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Any TWO of the following: In Route (2), the ethanoic acid produced is more pure. The rate of fermentation / aerial oxidation in Route (1) is slower. Route (2) does not consume food but Route (1) does."},
//   {"id":1844,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) Chlorine is one of the products manufactured in the chloroalkali industry. The electrolysis involved in the chloroalkali industry can be performed in a mercury electrolytic cell, a diaphragm electrolytic cell or a membrane electrolytic cell. (i) State the raw material used in the chloroalkali industry. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Concentrated sodium chloride (NaCl) solution / brine."},
//   {"id":1845,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (ii) Suggest a criterion in choosing a site for building the chemical plant for a chloroalkali industry. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Site should be near the sea because easy to get the raw material."},
//   {"id":1846,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (iii) Write an overall equation for the electrolysis involved in the chloroalkali industry. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"2NaCl + 2H2O → Cl2 + H2 + 2NaOH"},
//   {"id":1847,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (iv) Explain why a mercury electrolytic cell is NOT considered to be environmentally friendly. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Mercury is poisonous."},
//   {"id":1848,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (v) What is the advantage of a membrane electrolytic cell over a diaphragm electrolytic cell? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"In membrane cell, more pure sodium hydroxide can be obtained, but not for diaphragm cell."},
//   {"id":1849,"subject":"化學","topic":"13. Industrial Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (vi) The chloroalkali industry can also manufacture chlorine bleach and hydrochloric acid. Explain, with the aid of a chemical equation, why chlorine bleach should not be stored together with hydrochloric acid. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Chlorine bleach can react with hydrochloric acid to give poisonous chlorine gas. ClO- + 2H+ + Cl- → H2O + Cl2."},
//   {"id":1850,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) The structure of compound A, which exhibits liquid-crystalline behaviour, is shown below. (10 marks) (i) Compound A can be formed by condensation of benzoic acid with cholesterol. Draw the structure of cholesterol.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：cholesterol structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1851,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) (ii) What is the difference between 'true liquid' and 'liquid crystal'?","points":30,"answerLetter":"True liquid exhibits distinctive phase while liquid crystals exhibit phase intermediate between solid and liquid. Molecules in 'true liquid' have no intrinsic order while molecules in liquid crystal are arranged orderly having certain degree of translational freedom with certain orientation preference, as in the case of a solid crystal, in the liquid-crystalline phase. A liquid crystal can exhibit one or more ordered phases e.g. nematic, smectic and cholesteric phase at a temperature above the melting point of the solid."},
//   {"id":1852,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) (iii) Describe briefly the arrangement of the molecules in cholesteric phase liquid crystals.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The chiral nematic phase arises when the molecules that make up the nematic phase are chiral. In the cholesteric phase, the liquid crystal molecules are arranged in a similar manner as in nematic phase. The molecules are arranged orderly in each layer. Neighbouring layers have molecules pointing at different angles. The molecules line up in positions in such a way that they are slightly twisted from the molecules in the neighbouring layer. This results in the helical arrangement of the molecules."},
//   {"id":1853,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) (iv) Outline the working principle of cholesteric phase liquid crystals in Liquid Crystal Display (LCD).","points":30,"answerLetter":"A LCD contains liquid crystal molecules in cholesteric phase sandwiched between a polariser and an analyser. When ordinary light passes through the first polariser that allows only light in one plane to pass through, the plane of polarisation of the polarised light is rotated 90° by the liquid crystal molecules that are naturally twisted and are pointing to their original orientations. Thus, the polarised light is in the correct orientation to pass through the second polariser and hence the analyser. So the display area appears bright. When a voltage is applied across the two glass electrodes, the liquid crystal molecules reorient parallel to the electric field. The plane of polarised light is not rotated by the molecules. In that case, the light cannot pass through the second polariser. The display appears dark."},
//   {"id":1854,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (b) Plastics can be classified into thermoplastics and thermosetting plastics according to their thermal properties. (10 marks) (i) Explain, in terms of bonding and structure, why thermoplastics and thermosetting plastics behave differently upon heating.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cross-links are formed between the polymer chains when a thermosetting plastic is moulded and a hard and rigid three-dimensional giant network is thus formed, whereas there are no cross-links between polymer chains in thermoplastics such that only weak intermolecular forces are holding polymer chains to one another and the polymeric chains are oriented randomly. Hence, the weak van der Waals' forces between polymer chains can easily be overcome by heating and the polymer chains in thermoplastics can slide over one another easily while the polymer chains in thermosetting plastics cannot slide over one another even when heated owing to the rigid giant network. As a result, thermoplastics would soften while thermosetting plastics would not soften upon heating."},
//   {"id":1855,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (b) (ii) Polyethene (PE) is a thermoplastic commonly used in making shopping bags. (1) Write the chemical equation for the formation of PE from its monomer. (2) State the repeating unit of PE.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：PE formation equation and repeating unit）","points":30,"answerLetter":"n CH2=CH2 → -[CH2-CH2]n-"},
//   {"id":1856,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (b) (iii) Some scientists suggested using polylactic acid (PLA) instead of PE to make shopping bags as this can help reduce environmental problems. Part of the structure of PLA is shown below. (1) Draw the structure of the monomer used to make PLA. (2) Give the systematic name of the monomer. (3) Name the type of polymerisation for making PLA. (4) Explain, in chemical terms, why the disposal of PLA poses less harm to the environment than that of PE.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：PLA structure and monomer）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) CH3CH(OH)COOH (2) 2-hydroxypropanoic acid (3) condensation polymerisation / ring-opening polymerisation (4) PLA is synthesised directly from renewable natural resources as lactic acid which can be generated from fermentation of corn starch or sugar (which forms from the photosynthesis of corn using carbon dioxide and water) such that it can be broken down by the enzymatic action of micro-organisms in nature easily (biodegradable). Also, they can be easily hydrolysed by acid or alkali."},
//   {"id":1857,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) Aluminium is the most abundant metallic element in the earth's crust and is one of the most widely used metals. (i) Solid aluminium exhibits a cubic crystalline structure, which is a repetition of the following unit cell. (5 marks) (I) Name the type of unit cell of aluminium. (II) Calculate the number of atoms in ONE unit cell of aluminium. (III) Given that the edge length of a unit cell of aluminium is 4.05×10-10 m, calculate the density of solid aluminium, in g cm-3. (Avogadro constant L = 6.02×1023 mol-1)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：FCC unit cell diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(I) face-centred cubic. (II) No. of atoms = 8×(1/8) + 6×(1/2) = 4. (III) Density = (4×27.0) / ((4.05×10-8)3 × 6.02×1023) = 2.7 g cm-3."},
//   {"id":1858,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (ii) (3 marks) (I) The strength of aluminium can be improved by alloying it with other metals. Explain why. (II) Alloys of aluminium and lithium are used in making aircraft bodies. Apart from strength considerations, suggest ONE advantage of using aluminium-lithium alloys in making aircraft bodies.","points":30,"answerLetter":"(I) In aluminium alloys, the introduction of atoms of other elements into the lattice causes distortion of the regular arrangement of the Al atoms. Relative motion between layers of atoms will be hindered. (II) Li is the least dense metal. Li-Al alloys have very low densities and are suitable materials for making aircraft bodies."},
//   {"id":1859,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (iii) Biotite is a kind of aluminosilicate having a layered structure. It is widely used in the electronics industry. (2 marks) (I) Explain why biotite can easily flake off. (II) Suggest ONE application of biotite in the electronics industry.","points":30,"answerLetter":"(I) Biotite has a layered structure. The attraction force between layers is much weaker than the attraction force between atoms within a layer. (II) as insulator in capacitors."},
//   {"id":1860,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (b) Polystyrene (PS) is a commonly used plastic material. Solid PS is brittle and of limited flexibility. The properties of PS can be modified by copolymerisation with other chemicals. The structure of PS is represented as follows. (i) (2 marks) (1) Draw the structure of the monomer of PS. (2) The photograph below shows a plastic lid made from PS. Suggest a moulding method used in making the lid.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：PS monomer structure and PS lid photo）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) C6H5CH=CH2 (styrene). (2) injection moulding / vacuum forming."},
//   {"id":1861,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (b) (ii) Styrene acrylonitrile resin (SAN) is a plastic material made from copolymerisation of styrene with acrylonitrile (H2C=CHCN). SAN can withstand higher temperatures than PS. (5 marks) (1) Repetition of the following structure CANNOT represent the exact structure of SAN. Explain why. (2) Suggest why SAN can withstand higher temperatures than PS.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：SAN alternating structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) SAN, in general, is not made from styrene and acrylonitrile in 1:1 mole ratio. The two types of monomers distribute randomly along the polymer molecule. (2) In PS, the polymer molecules are attracted to each other by weak van der Waals forces. Acrylonitrile has a polar -C≡N group. The -C≡N groups hold the polymer molecules together by stronger dipole-dipole interaction."},
//   {"id":1862,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (b) (iii) Copolymerisation of styrene with 1,4-divinylbenzene produces a plastic material which is hard, rigid and does not melt upon heating. Explain, in terms of structure and bonding, why this plastic material possesses the abovementioned physical properties. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：cross-linked structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"The cross-linkages make the copolymer hard and rigid. As the copolymer has a giant covalent network structure, it does not melt upon heating."},
//   {"id":1863,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) The structures of Kevlar and nylon-6,6 are shown below. (i) (3 marks) (1) Draw the structure of the monomers for making Kevlar. (2) Name the type of reaction for the formation of Kevlar from its monomers.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Kevlar and nylon-6,6 structures）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) p-phenylenediamine and terephthalic acid (or their structures). (2) Condensation polymerisation."},
//   {"id":1864,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (ii) Compound A is one of the monomers for making nylon-6,6 in industry. The following equations show two reactions that can produce A. (5 marks) (1) Draw the structure of A. (2) Reaction (1) is considered to be greener than Reaction (2). Suggest THREE reasons. (3) In what aspect are both reactions considered as NOT green?<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：reaction equations）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) HOOC-(CH2)4-COOH (adipic acid). (2) The hydrogen peroxide used in Reaction (1) is less corrosive / hazardous when compared with the concentrated nitric acid used in Reaction (2). The by-product H2O produced in Reaction (1) is less harmful / environmentally friendly when compared with the by-product N2O produced in Reaction (2). A catalyst is used in Reaction (1) but not in Reaction (2). (3) Both reactions consume starting materials that possibly obtained from a nonrenewable resource."},
//   {"id":1865,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (iii) With reference to the structures of Kevlar and nylon-6,6, account for their difference in mechanical strength. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Kevlar is a much stronger material than nylon-6,6 because the benzene groups in the Kevlar molecules have a more rigid structure. Aromatic stacking interactions between the benzene groups of adjacent polymer molecules also contribute to the exceptionally high mechanical strength of Kevlar."},
//   {"id":1866,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (b) A part of the structure of natural rubber is shown below. (i) Natural rubber needs to be treated with sulphur before it can be used in making tyres. Name this treatment process, state its purpose, and explain the principle behind. (3 marks) (ii) A technician wore a pair of gloves made with natural rubber and performed an experiment involving bromine. Bromine was spilt onto the gloves and then the gloves became brittle. Explain the phenomenon. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：natural rubber structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(i) Name: vulcanisation. Purpose: To make the material strong and elastic. Principle: Sulphur reacts with some of the C=C bonds in the polymer chains, forming S-S cross-links between the polymer chains. (ii) Bromination reaction occurs to the C=C bonds of the material. The brominated polymer have weaker intramolecular structure of the product leading to change in mechanical property."},
//   {"id":1867,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (c) (i) Iron exists in two common crystalline forms, α-iron (body-centred cubic) and γ-iron (face-centred cubic). (1) Draw a unit cell of iron. (2) Deduce the number of iron atoms in the unit cell.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：BCC unit cell diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Diagram of BCC unit cell. (2) Number of atoms = 1 + 8×(1/8) = 2."},
//   {"id":1868,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (c) (ii) With reference to the elements introduced into iron for forming stainless steel, explain why stainless steel is suitable for making knives. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Carbon and chromium / nickel / manganese. Size of carbon atom differs from that of iron atom, introducing carbon into iron makes iron become harder. Introducing chromium into iron makes iron become corrosion resistant."},
//   {"id":1869,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (a) A part of the structure of cellulose is shown below. (i) Cellulose is a condensation polymer of glucose. (2 marks) (1) What is the meaning of the term 'condensation polymer'? (2) Draw the structure of a molecule of glucose.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：cellulose and glucose structures）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) A condensation polymer is a polymer which when formed from its monomers involves the elimination of small molecules. (2) Glucose structure (ring form)."},
//   {"id":1870,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (a) (ii) The relative molecular mass of cellulose generally ranges from 2.5×105 to 1.0×106. Suggest why the relative molecular mass of cellulose falls into a wide range. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Molecules of cellulose may contain various number of glucose molecules joined together."},
//   {"id":1871,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (a) (iii) Explain why there is a significant difference in the solubility of glucose and cellulose in water. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Glucose is very soluble in water while cellulose is insoluble in water. A glucose molecule has 5 -OH groups which can attract water molecules strongly via hydrogen bonds. The -OH groups of a cellulose molecule form hydrogen bonds with other cellulose molecules, therefore they are less available to form hydrogen bonds with water molecules."},
//   {"id":1872,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (i) Methyl cellulose is a polymer synthesised from cellulose. It is commonly used as the active ingredient of wallpaper glue. A part of the structure of methyl cellulose is shown. Methyl cellulose glue, when dried, is a white solid. State and explain the behaviour of the white solid when it is gradually heated up to a very high temperature. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：methyl cellulose structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"The solid becomes soften upon heating. The heat energy absorbed helps the polymeric molecules to overcome the intermolecular attraction and the molecules can have relative translational motion. At very high temperature, the glue chars / burns."},
//   {"id":1873,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (ii) Poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate) is commonly used as the active ingredient of superglue. The structure of poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate) is shown. (3 marks) (1) Draw the structure of the monomer of poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate). (2) Propanone (CH3COCH3) is a commonly used solvent for removing hardened superglue. Explain why propanone can dissolve poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate).<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate) structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) CH2=C(CN)CO2CH3. (2) Both propanone and poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate) are polar organic molecules. The intermolecular attraction in the two compounds is of the same type (polar attraction). Thus, propanone can dissolve poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate)."},
//   {"id":1874,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (iii) Which of methyl cellulose or poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate) degrades more readily in the environment? Explain your answer. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Methyl cellulose is more readily degraded in the environment. Methyl cellulose is produced from cellulose, a natural material, which is more biodegradable / can be degraded by actions of bacteria or enzymes. Poly(methyl 2-cyanoacrylate) contains long carbon chains which are not readily decomposed."},
//   {"id":1875,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (i) Compare the nematic phase and the smectic phase of liquid crystals. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"In both nematic phase and smectic phase, the molecules are arranged along one direction. In the smectic phase, the molecules are positionally aligned with each other along a straight line. In the nematic phase, they are not aligned."},
//   {"id":1876,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (ii) Explain which of the following compounds, A or B, would form cholesteric phase liquid crystals. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：chiral vs achiral molecules）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Molecule A exhibits the cholesteric phase as it is chiral and only chiral compounds can exhibit the cholesteric phase."},
//   {"id":1877,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (iii) Suggest why liquid crystals would lose the liquid crystal properties at very low temperatures. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The compound solidifies at a very low temperature."},
//   {"id":1878,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (iv) Organic Light Emitting Diode (OLED) can emit light when an electric current passes through. OLED can also be used in making visual displays. Explain why the power efficiency of liquid crystal displays is considered to be lower than that of OLED displays. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Liquid crystal displays need a backlight source, but OLED displays do not. Liquid crystals act as optical filters to filter off the light from the backlight to give dark spots. Only a small fraction of light passes through them and makes up the images."},
//   {"id":1879,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) Sketch a unit cell for each of the following metallic crystal structures: (2 marks) (1) cubic close-packed structure (2) body-centred cubic structure<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：FCC and BCC unit cells）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":1880,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) (ii) State TWO structural features of the molecules of the substances that exhibit liquid crystal behaviour. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"With a fairly rigid molecular backbone containing double bonds defining the long axis of the molecule; many liquid-crystalline materials have benzene rings; rod-like or disc-like molecules; polar groups."},
//   {"id":1881,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) (iii) Classify the following plastics into thermoplastics and thermosetting plastics: (1 mark) polyvinyl chloride, polystyrene, urea-methanol","points":30,"answerLetter":"Thermoplastics: polyvinyl chloride, polystyrene. Thermosetting plastics: urea-methanol."},
//   {"id":1882,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) Both silicates and ceramics are important materials having a wide variety of applications. (i) (2 marks) (1) State one common structural feature of silicates and ceramics. (2) State the difference between the ways of obtaining silicates and ceramics.","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Both of them have giant structures. (2) Silicates are natural materials, while ceramics are synthetic materials."},
//   {"id":1883,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (ii) Quartz is also a silicate material. Explain why talc and quartz are very different in hardness. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Talc: Sheet structure in which the sheets are held together by van der Waals' forces. Quartz: Si and O atoms joined by a giant network / strong covalent bonds. A small amount of energy can make the sheets slip over one another in talc, while a large amount of energy is needed to break the giant network in quartz."},
//   {"id":1884,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (iii) Suggest why ceramics are suitable for making cutting tools. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"High hardness."},
//   {"id":1885,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) The diagram below shows a plastic bottle for cough syrup made from polyethene (PE). (i) Suggest a moulding method for making this plastic bottle. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：PE bottle）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Blow moulding."},
//   {"id":1886,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (ii) Give the TWO common types of PE. Explain, from molecular level, which type of PE is more suitable in making this plastic bottle. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"low density polyethene (LDPE) and high density polyethene (HDPE). As the bottle for cough syrup is hard, HDPE is more suitable. HDPE molecules have a linear structure that pack more closely. / As the bottle for cough syrup is soft, LDPE is more suitable. LDPE molecules are highly branched that cannot pack closely."},
//   {"id":1887,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (iii) Explain, from molecular level, why bottles made from poly(ethylene terephthalate) (PET) would generally be harder than bottles made from PE. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The polar PET molecules are held together by much stronger polar-polar interactions. The non-polar PE (HDPE) molecules are held together by van der Waals' forces."},
//   {"id":1888,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (iv) Some people suggest, from the perspective of environmental protection, switching from using PE and PET to using polylactide (PLA) in making this type of plastic bottles. The repeating unit of PLA is shown below. (3 marks) (1) It is known that PLA can be produced from the polymerisation of lactic acid through esterification. Give the structure of lactic acid. (2) Explain why the switching might be environmentally friendly. (3) Suggest a potential problem of widely replacing PE and PET by PLA.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：PLA repeating unit）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) CH3CH(OH)COOH. (2) PLA is made from renewable resources, while PE and PET are made from nonrenewable petroleum products. / PLA is biodegradable, while PE and PET are non-biodegradable. (3) PLA is made from agricultural products. Massive production of PLA may affect the supply of food."},
//   {"id":1889,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) The diagram below shows the unit cell of copper metal. (2 marks) (1) State the meaning of the term 'unit cell'. (2) Deduce the number of copper atoms in the unit cell.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：copper unit cell (FCC)）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) The smallest part of a lattice / crystal, which by repetition of itself, can generate the whole lattice / crystal. (2) Number of copper atoms = 8×(1/8) + 6×(1/2) = 4."},
//   {"id":1890,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) (ii) Which one of the following items can be made from urea-methanol? (1 mark) balloon, electric socket, fishing line, plastic water pipe","points":30,"answerLetter":"electric socket."},
//   {"id":1891,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) (iii) One of the monomers for making nylon-6,6 is HOOC(CH2)4COOH. Traditionally, it can be prepared by the following reaction path. Suggest TWO reasons why the above reaction path is NOT considered to be green. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：reaction path for adipic acid）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Conc. HNO3 is corrosive. NO2 is poisonous."},
//   {"id":1892,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) The equation below shows the formation of polystyrene (PS) from styrene. (i) Draw the structure of styrene. (1 mark) (ii) Name the type of polymerisation involved in forming PS. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"(i) C6H5CH=CH2. (ii) Addition polymerisation."},
//   {"id":1893,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) (iii) Expanded PS is commonly used in making disposable cups for containing hot drinks. (4 marks) (1) Explain why expanded PS has good heat insulating property. (2) Suggest a moulding method for making expanded PS cups. (3) State TWO problems in recycling objects made from expanded PS.","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) The air inside the expanded PS is good insulator of heat. (2) injection moulding. (3) Expanded PS occupies a very large volume. Hence collection, transportation and storage of the wastes are problematic. Sorting and cleaning of the expanded PS wastes are uneconomical."},
//   {"id":1894,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) (iv) Styrene can polymerise with buta-1,3-diene to give a high impact polystyrene (HIPS) in which the monomers randomly join together. A portion of the structure of a certain HIPS is shown below. Suggest why the hardness of HIPS is lower than that of PS. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：HIPS structure fragment）","points":30,"answerLetter":"The less orderly arranged repeating units of HIPS make the polymer molecules pack not as close as that in PS. The intermolecular attractions between the polymer molecules of HIPS are weaker than that in PS."},
//   {"id":1895,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (i) How do molecules arrange in the smectic phase of liquid crystals? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The molecules in smectic phase have a certain degree of two-dimensional order and form well-defined layers."},
//   {"id":1896,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (ii) The following diagram illustrates the basic working principle of one pixel in liquid crystal displays. Explain why the pixel appears dark when a voltage is applied to the liquid crystal layer. (4 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：LCD pixel working diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"The two polarisers at the two sides of the liquid crystal layer are perpendicular to each other. When a voltage is applied to the liquid crystal layer, the liquid crystal molecules align with the electric field. The polarised light will pass through the liquid crystal layer without rotation of the plane of polarisation. The polarised light is completely blocked by the second polariser, giving a black pixel."},
//   {"id":1897,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (iii) (1) State the meaning of the term 'nanomaterials'. (2) Suggest why the use of nanomaterials may increase the resolution of displays. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Nanomaterials are materials with particle sizes less than 100 nm between 1-100 / 1000 nm. (2) As the particle sizes of nanomaterials are so small, using them to make displays can increase the number of pixels in a given area / the phosphors for high-definition display units."},
//   {"id":1898,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) Cellulose is a natural polymer and its structure is shown below. Explain why cellulose is considered to be environmentally friendly. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：cellulose structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cellulose is biodegradable / can undergo hydrolysis."},
//   {"id":1899,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (a) (ii) State TWO structural characteristics of liquid crystals. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Molecules in liquid crystals are usually long and rigid rod-like / long and disk-like; contains C=C / N=N double bonds; contains phenyl groups; are usually polar / readily polarizable; possess some degree of translational freedom with certain orientation preference in one or two dimension(s); are packed more regularly than that of liquids / have low degree of translational freedom than that of liquids."},
//   {"id":1900,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (a) (iii) A portion of the structure of Kevlar is shown below. With reference to the above structure, give TWO reasons why Kevlar is rigid. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Kevlar structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Many benzene rings / phenyl groups in the structure can make it rigid. There are many strong intermolecular hydrogen bonds formed between the polymer molecules."},
//   {"id":1901,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (b) Gold is a precious metal. The diagram below shows a unit cell of gold crystal. (i) Name this type of crystal structure. (1 mark) (ii) Calculate the number of gold atoms in the unit cell. (2 marks) (iii) What is the coordination number of the gold atom labelled 'X'? (1 mark) (iv) A sample of 18-carat gold is composed of 75% gold, 15% silver and 10% copper. Explain, from scientific point of view, the advantage of using this sample of 18-carat gold over using pure gold in making jewellery embedded with diamonds. (2 marks) (v) Gold nanoparticles of various size exhibit different colours. Suggest one example of using gold nanoparticles in architecture. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：FCC unit cell with atom X）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(i) Face-centred cubic (structure) / cubic close-packed (structure). (ii) Number = 12×(1/4)+1 = 4. (iii) 12. (iv) 18-carat gold is an alloy is harder / stronger than pure gold. Different kinds of metal atoms in alloy have different size making the atom layers difficult to slide over one another. (v) stained glass / window of a church."},
//   {"id":1902,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (c) (i) Polybutylene terephthalate (PBT) is a polyester used in making keycaps for computer keyboards. (3 marks) (1) Draw the structures of the various monomers of PBT. (2) Name the type of polymerisation involved in the formation of PET. (3) Suggest a moulding method for making keycaps for computer keyboards.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：PBT monomers structures）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) HO-CH2CH2CH2CH2-OH and HOOC-C6H4-COOH (or their structures). (2) Condensation (polymerisation). (3) Extrusion (moulding) / injection (moulding)."},
//   {"id":1903,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (c) (ii) A burette stopcock is made of PTFE. Suggest TWO properties of PTFE rendering it suitable for making burette stopcocks. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Any two: resistant to chemicals / inert to chemicals; resistant to tear and wear; non-sticky / slippery."},
//   {"id":1904,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (c) (iii) The conducting layer in an OLED display is made of PPV. The structure of PPV is shown below. (2 marks) (1) Draw a portion of structure consisting of THREE repeating units of PPV. (2) Would you expect PPV to exhibit optical activity? Explain your answer.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：PPV structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Diagram showing three repeating units of -C6H4-CH=CH-. (2) Optical inactive / Not optically active because there is no chiral centres / chiral carbons."},
//   {"id":1905,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) A portion of the structure of natural rubber is shown below. Suggest why natural rubber becomes hardened when it is heated with sulphur. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：natural rubber structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cross-linkages / covalent bonds / disulphur linkages are formed between polymer chains. With cross-linkages, the polymer chains cannot slip easily over each other."},
//   {"id":1906,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (a) (ii) In terms of molecular structure, explain why high density polyethene (HDPE) molecules are more closely packed than low density polyethene (LDPE) molecules. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The structure of HDPE is less branched than that of LDPE."},
//   {"id":1907,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (a) (iii) The structure of compound A is shown below. Explain whether A would exhibit liquid crystal behaviour. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：compound A structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"A exhibits liquid crystal behaviour. A molecule of A has a rigid central part, a polar group / ester group and a long alkyl chain."},
//   {"id":1908,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (b) (i) Refer to the unit cell of copper crystal. (2 marks) (1) State the coordination number of a copper atom. (2) Deduce the number of copper atoms in the unit cell.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：FCC unit cell of copper）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) coordination number = 12. (2) number of Cu atoms = 12×(1/4)+1 = 4."},
//   {"id":1909,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (b) (ii) Refer to the portion of the structure of zinc crystal. (4 marks) (1) Name the type of packing. (2) State one similarity between the packing of copper crystal and that of zinc crystal. (3) Discuss the difference between the packing of copper crystal and that of zinc crystal.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：HCP structure of zinc）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) hexagonal close-packed. (2) Similarity: coordination number (12) / close-packed structures. (3) Difference: Cu: A-B-C type packing; Zn: A-B type packing."},
//   {"id":1910,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (b) (iii) Name an alloy containing copper and zinc that can be used to make water taps. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"brass."},
//   {"id":1911,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (c) (i) Draw the structure of the monomer of Perspex, and state the natural raw material for this monomer. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Perspex monomer structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"CH2=C(CH3)CO2CH3; petroleum / crude oil."},
//   {"id":1912,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (c) (ii) Which one of the following items can be made from Perspex? (1 mark) rain coat, contact lens, fishing line, food wraps","points":30,"answerLetter":"contact lens."},
//   {"id":1913,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (c) (iii) PHB is a thermoplastic polymeric biomaterial. (3 marks) (1) What is meant by the term 'thermoplastic'? (2) Based on the fact that PHB is a polymeric biomaterial, explain separately why it can be considered environmentally friendly in its production and disposal.","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Thermoplastic is a type of plastic that becomes soft when heated; becomes hard when cooled. (2) Production: Raw material is biomass. Disposal: PHB is biodegradable."},
//   {"id":1914,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (c) (iv) PHB can be classified as polyester. (2 marks) (1) Formation of polyesters often involves condensation. Give a feature of condensation. (2) Based on the fact that PHB contains ester linkages, explain why it can be considered environmentally friendly in its disposal.","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Small molecules (e.g. H2O) would be eliminated in the reaction. (2) Disposal: PHB undergoes hydrolysis in the presence of acids / alkalis."},
//   {"id":1915,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) The following chemical equation shows how vinyl acetate can be obtained. 2CH3COOH + 2CH2=CH2 + O2 → 2CH3COOCH=CH2 + 2H2O. Give TWO reasons why this reaction can be considered as green. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Any two: Catalyst is used. High atom economy / atom economy = 172/208 = 82.7%. Water generated possesses little or no toxicity to human health and the environment."},
//   {"id":1916,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (a) (ii) Substance W is the component of the exoskeleton of crabs. Part of the structure of W is shown below. (2 marks) (1) Name W. (2) With reference to the above structure, suggest why the exoskeleton of crabs is very hard.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：chitin structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) chitin. (2) It can form extensive inter-molecular hydrogen bonds / hydrogen bonds between chains."},
//   {"id":1917,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (a) (iii) Which one of the following diagrams, A, B, C and D, shows a hexagonal close-packed structure? (Only need to write A, B, C or D in your answer.) (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：HCP vs other packing diagrams）","points":30,"answerLetter":"A."},
//   {"id":1918,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (b) (ii) A voltage is applied to the liquid crystal layer. (4 marks) (1) Draw a diagram to show the expected arrangement of the liquid crystal molecules. (2) Would the pixel appear bright or dark? Explain your answer.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：LCD working diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) With the applied voltage, the molecules arrange in lines / not twisted; show the polarity of the molecules and that of electrodes are opposite. (2) Dark. Polarisers are perpendicular to each other. The polarised light will pass through the liquid crystal layer without rotating the plane of polarisation. The polarised light is completely blocked by the polariser at the right, giving a black pixel."},
//   {"id":1919,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (b) (iii) Explain why the liquid crystal display could not operate beyond a certain high temperature. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"When temperature is higher than the upper end of the operation range, the liquid crystal will liquefy / melt."},
//   {"id":1920,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (c) (i) Draw the structures of the monomers of X. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：X structure monomers）","points":30,"answerLetter":"HOCH2CHOHCH2OH and HOOC-CH=CH-COOH / Cl-CO-CH=CH-CO-Cl."},
//   {"id":1921,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (c) (ii) Compound A joins molecules of X together to form Y. Part of the structure of Y is shown below. (4 marks) (1) Draw the structure of A. (2) Comment on the thermal property of Y. (3) Suggest one way to control the rigidity of Y. Explain your answer.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Y structure）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) C6H5CH=CH2 (styrene). (2) thermosetting / hardening under formation with heating. (3) Adjust the relative amounts of X and A. The rigidity depends on its degree / amount of cross-linking."},
//   {"id":1922,"subject":"化學","topic":"14. Material Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (c) (iii) Y is used to make the body of a boat. (2 marks) (1) Suggest a moulding method for making the body of the boat. (2) Suggest one advantage of using Y over iron in making the body of a boat.","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) compression moulding. (2) Y will not corrode / rust easily but iron will. / Y is less dense than iron."},
//   {"id":1923,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) Compound G, with relative molecular mass of 58, has the following composition by mass: C: 62.1% H: 10.3% O: 27.6%. The infrared and mass spectra of compound G are given below. (10 marks) (i) Deduce the molecular formula of compound G.","points":30,"answerLetter":"C: 62.1/12.0 = 5.175, H: 10.3/1.0 = 10.3, O: 27.6/16.0 = 1.725. Simplest ratio: C: 5.175/1.725 = 3, H: 10.3/1.725 ≈ 6, O: 1.725/1.725 = 1. Empirical formula = C3H6O. Let molecular formula = (C3H6O)n. n×(12.0×3+1.0×6+16.0)=58, n=1. Molecular formula is C3H6O."},
//   {"id":1924,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) (ii) From the given spectral information and the molecular formula obtained in (i), deduce the structural formula of compound G. (Infrared spectrum shows a prominent dip at wavenumber 1700 cm-1, showing carbonyl group. Mass spectrum shows molecular ion peak at m/z=58 and a prominent peak at m/z=29 corresponding to [CHO]+ or [C2H5]+.)","points":30,"answerLetter":"According to the infrared spectrum, there is a prominent dip at wavenumber 1700 cm-1, showing that a carbonyl (C=O) group is present in G. Hence, G is a carbonyl compound. According to the mass spectrum, intensity peak at m/z ratio = 58 corresponds to the molecular ion peak. There is also another prominent intensity peak at m/z ratio = 29 corresponding to the ions [CHO]+ or [C2H5]+. So a terminal carbonyl group is present in G. Thus, G cannot be propanone. Hence, G should be propanal. The structural formula of G is CH3CH2CHO."},
//   {"id":1925,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (a) (iii) Suggest an experiment, with detailed procedures, to support the structure of compound G you have deduced in (ii).","points":30,"answerLetter":"Treat G with 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine to prepare the corresponding 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazone. Recrystallize the 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazone. The melting point of the solid derivative is determined using a melting point apparatus. Then, a sharp melting point which is the same as that quoted in the literature value would support the deduction of G."},
//   {"id":1926,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (b) In an experiment to determine the concentration of ethanol in a brand of spirit, 10.0 cm3 of a sample of the spirit was diluted to 250.0 cm3. 25.0 cm3 portions of the diluted spirit were withdrawn. To each portion, 25.0 cm3 of 0.156 M K2Cr2O7(aq) and excess dilute H2SO4 were added. The mixtures obtained were allowed to stand at room temperature overnight. The excess K2Cr2O7 in each mixture was then titrated against 0.118 M (NH4)2Fe(SO4)2(aq) with an appropriate indicator. The mean titre was 12.23 cm3. (10 marks) (i) Write an equation for the reaction of ethanol with dichromate ions under acidic condition.","points":30,"answerLetter":"3CH3CH2OH + 2Cr2O72- + 16H+ → 3CH3COOH + 4Cr3+ + 11H2O"},
//   {"id":1927,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (b) (ii) Give TWO properties of (NH4)2Fe(SO4)2 rendering it to be used as a primary standard in volumetric analysis.","points":30,"answerLetter":"low hygroscopy; low efflorescence; large relative molecular mass; high purity; high stability in air (any two)."},
//   {"id":1928,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (b) (iii) Suggest a method to test whether the oxidation of ethanol has been completed.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Keep a small sample for 2 days. Repeat the titration process to see if the result is the same. If so, the reaction has completed."},
//   {"id":1929,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"SP (b) (iv) Calculate the concentration of ethanol, in mol dm-3, in this brand of spirit. (Titration reaction: 6Fe2+ + Cr2O72- + 14H+ → 6Fe3+ + 2Cr3+ + 7H2O)","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. of moles of (NH4)2Fe(SO4)2 = 0.118 × (12.23×10-3) = 1.44314×10-3. Mole ratio Fe2+:Cr2O72- = 6:1, so no. of moles of Cr2O72- reacted in titration = (1.44314×10-3)/6 = 2.40523×10-4. No. of moles of Cr2O72- originally in 25.0 cm3 = (25.0×10-3)×0.156 = 3.9×10-3. No. of moles of Cr2O72- reacted with ethanol = 3.9×10-3 - 2.40523×10-4 = 3.65948×10-3. Mole ratio CH3CH2OH:Cr2O72- = 3:2, so no. of moles ethanol in 25.0 cm3 diluted spirit = (3.65948×10-3)×(3/2) = 5.48922×10-3. Molarity of ethanol in diluted spirit = (5.48922×10-3)/(25.0×10-3) = 0.2196 M. The spirit was diluted 25 times, so original concentration = 0.2196×25 = 5.49 M."},
//   {"id":1930,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) A colourless compound X (C9H8O2) is obtainable from cinnamon. X has a melting point of 134°C and is insoluble in water. An experiment to extract X from an impure sample, which contains non-polar organic impurities, involves the following five steps: Step 1: Dissolve the sample in excess NaOH(aq). Step 2: Shake the solution from Step 1 with hexane and discard the organic layer. Step 3: Add HCl(aq) to the aqueous layer obtained until a white precipitate forms and the solution becomes acidic. Step 4: Collect the white precipitate by filtration. Step 5: Using ethanol as solvent, recrystallise the precipitate collected to obtain X. (i) From the above experimental steps, suggest ONE functional group present in X. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"carboxylic acid / carboxyl group (because X is soluble in NaOH(aq)). (Also accept phenol.)"},
//   {"id":1931,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (ii) Name the apparatus used in Step 2. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"separating funnel"},
//   {"id":1932,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (iii) Briefly explain the purpose of carrying out Steps 1, 2 and 3 respectively. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Step 1: Allow X to dissolve in NaOH(aq) to give (carboxylate) anions / a salt. Step 2: Allow the non-polar impurities to dissolve in hexane while the (carboxylate) anions / salt to stay in the aqueous layer. / Separate the non-polar impurities (in hexane) from the salt of X. Step 3: Regenerate the (carboxylic) acid (which is insoluble in water) by adding acid."},
//   {"id":1933,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (iv) X can decolourise Br2 in CH3Cl3. It displays the following mass spectrum. Deduce ONE possible structure of X. (5 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：mass spectrum of X）","points":30,"answerLetter":"X possesses a C=C bond because it decolourises Br2 in CH3Cl3. In the mass spectrum, the peak at m/z = 148 is due to the molecular ion. The peak at m/z = 131 is due to the cation formed from the molecular ion by stripping off a -OH. The peak at m/z = 103 is due to the cation formed from the molecular ion by stripping off a -CO2H. The peak at m/z = 77 shows that X carries a benzene ring (m/z for C6H5+ ion = 77). Possible structures: C6H5CH=CHCO2H (cinnamic acid) or C6H5CH=CHCO2H (cis/trans)."},
//   {"id":1934,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (a) (v) Another sample of X is contaminated with a colourless organic compound. The sample is analysed by thin-layer chromatography (TLC), and the result is shown below. (3 marks) (1) Suggest ONE method that can be used to make the two spots on the chromatographic plate become visible. (2) Given that Spot A corresponds to X, calculate the Rf of X. (3) Based on the TLC results, suggest ONE method to separate X from the contaminated sample.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：TLC plate diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Put the chromatographic plate into a jar that is saturated with iodine vapour. The spots will appear brown. / Irradiate the plate with UV. The stationary phase is fluorescent while the two spots are not. (2) Rf = distance moved by spot / distance moved by solvent front. (3) column chromatography (using the same moving phase and stationary phase)."},
//   {"id":1935,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (b) The percentage by mass of barium (Ba) in a barium salt can be determined by gravimetric method. In one such experiment, 0.305 g of a sample of a barium salt was dissolved completely in about 100 cm3 of deionised water. Excess dilute sulphuric acid was then added to the solution to precipitate out barium sulphate. After filtration and appropriate treatments, the barium sulphate was found to have a mass of 0.291 g. (i) State TWO necessary treatments on the filtered barium sulphate precipitate before its mass is determined. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Wash the precipitate thoroughly with deionised water. Dry the precipitate in an oven / ensure that the precipitate is dried before it is weighed."},
//   {"id":1936,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (b) (ii) Calculate the percentage by mass of barium in the sample. (3 marks) (Relative atomic masses: Ba = 137.3, S = 32.1, O = 16.0)","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. of moles of Ba2+ = 0.291 / (137.3+32.1+16×4) = 0.291 / 233.4 = 1.247×10-3. Mass of Ba = 1.247×10-3 × 137.3 = 0.1712 g. % by mass of Ba = (0.1712/0.305)×100% = 56.1%."},
//   {"id":1937,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"PP (b) (iii) State TWO conditions under which gravimetric method is suitable for quantitative analysis. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The reaction must be significantly complete, i.e. the precipitate is practically insoluble. The product (precipitate) should have definite chemical composition. The rate of reaction must be fast enough to be practical. (any two)"},
//   {"id":1938,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) Compound X (molar mass < 118 g) contains a -C6H5 group. Two chemical tests are performed on X and the results are as follows: Test (1): X turns acidified potassium dichromate solution green. Test (2): X gives a negative result when tested with 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine. (i) With reference to the result of Test (1) only, suggest TWO functional groups that X may have. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Hydroxyl group; Aldehyde group."},
//   {"id":1939,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (ii) (1) What is the purpose of using 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine in Test (2)? (2) State the expected observation if X gives a positive result in Test (2). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Test for aldehyde group or ketone group. (2) 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine reacts with aldehyde or ketone to give yellow or red precipitate."},
//   {"id":1940,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (iii) With reference to the results of both Test (1) and Test (2), suggest one functional group that may be present in X. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Hydroxyl group."},
//   {"id":1941,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (iv) The mass spectrum of X is shown below. Suggest one chemical species corresponding to each of the signals at m/z = 91 and 108. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：mass spectrum of X）","points":30,"answerLetter":"m/z = 91 suggested the presence of C7H7+ ion. m/z = 108 suggested the presence of C7H8O+ ion."},
//   {"id":1942,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (a) (v) Draw a possible structure of X. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"C6H5CH2OH (benzyl alcohol)."},
//   {"id":1943,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (b) The dioxin levels of dioxins in air are generally measured through instrumental analysis but not gravimetric analysis or volumetric analysis. (i) Suggest a source of dioxins in air. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Combustion of materials containing chlorine."},
//   {"id":1944,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (b) (ii) Explain why there is a need to measure the dioxin levels of dioxins in air. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Dioxin is carcinogenic / can cause cancer."},
//   {"id":1945,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (b) (iii) Suggest an instrumental analytical method for measuring the dioxin levels of dioxins in air, and state why this method, rather than methods based on gravimetric analysis or volumetric analysis, is to be used. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS). It can measure more accurately the low level of dioxin that using gravimetric analysis or volumetric analysis."},
//   {"id":1946,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (c) An aqueous solution only contains HCl(aq) and HI(aq). Based on the fact that AgCl(s), but not AgI(s), can dissolve in excess NH3(aq), you are required to plan a gravimetric analysis to determine the mole ratio of Cl-(aq) to I-(aq) in the solution. (i) Suggest TWO reagents, other than deionized water, that should be used in the analysis. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"AgNO3(aq) and NH3(aq)."},
//   {"id":1947,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (c) (ii) Outline the experimental steps involved in the analysis. (4 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Step 1: Add excess AgNO3(aq) to the solution to form AgCl(s) and AgI(s). Step 2: Filter the mixture, wash with deionized water and dry the residue. Step 3: Determine the total mass of AgCl(s) and AgI(s) collected. Step 4: Wash the solid residue with excess ammonia solution to dissolve AgCl(s), filter and dry the residue, and determine the mass of AgI(s) remains."},
//   {"id":1948,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2012 (c) (iii) Outline the steps in the calculation of the mole ratio of Cl-(aq) to I-(aq) in the solution using the data obtained from (ii) above. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Subtracting the total mass of AgCl(s) and AgI(s) determined in Step 3 by the mass of AgI(s) determined in Step 4 to get the mass of AgCl(s). Number of mole of AgCl and AgI can be obtained by dividing their respective mass by the corresponding molar mass. Mole ratio of Cl- to I- can then be determined."},
//   {"id":1949,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (a) Outline how hex-1-ene can be obtained from a mixture of hex-1-ene, octane and water by physical methods. (Boiling points: hex-1-ene = 63°C, octane = 125°C, water = 100°C) (4 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Use separating funnel to remove water (the lower liquid layer) from the mixture. The upper layer remaining in the funnel is hex-1-ene and octane. Carry out fractional distillation on the upper layer. The first distillate collected is hex-1-ene. The second distillate collected is octane."},
//   {"id":1950,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) Both white wine and red wine contain SO2 preservative which is fixed in different forms. A volumetric analysis experiment was performed to determine the total concentration of SO2 in a sample of white wine. In the experiment, 25.00 cm3 of the wine sample was transferred to a conical flask. Following certain stipulated procedures, NaOH(aq) and H2SO4(aq) were successively added to the flask to liberate all SO2 from the wine. The resultant solution was immediately titrated with 0.00412 mol dm-3 I2(aq) using freshly prepared starch solution as indicator. The experiment was repeated several times, and the mean volume of I2(aq) required to reach the end point was 10.50 cm3. (i) A reaction must fulfill certain conditions in order that it can be used in volumetric analysis. State ONE such condition. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"A significant observable change can easily be detected with the complete consumption of the reagent in the conical flask, i.e. availability of suitable indicator. / The reaction must be significantly complete. / The rate of reaction must be fast enough to be practical."},
//   {"id":1951,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (ii) Explain why the resultant solution needed to be titrated immediately. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"SO2 easily escapes from solution / I2 is volatile."},
//   {"id":1952,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (iii) State the expected colour change at the end point of the titration. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"From colourless to dark blue."},
//   {"id":1953,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (iv) The chemical equation for the reaction involved in the titration is as follows: SO2(aq) + I2(aq) + 2H2O(l) → 2HI(aq) + H2SO4(aq). Calculate the total concentration of SO2, in mg dm-3, in the white wine sample. (4 marks) (Relative atomic mass: S = 32.1, O = 16.0)","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. of mole of I2 used = 0.00412 × (10.50×10-3) = 4.326×10-5. No. of mole of SO2 = same = 4.326×10-5. Mass of SO2 = 4.326×10-5 × (32.1+16×2) = 4.326×10-5 × 64.1 = 2.774×10-3 g = 2.774 mg. Concentration = 2.774 mg / 0.025 dm3 = 111 mg dm-3."},
//   {"id":1954,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (b) (v) Explain whether the total concentration of SO2 in a sample of red wine can be determined in such an experiment. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"This method cannot be used as the intense red colour of red wine may mask the colour of iodine / iodine-starch complex which leads to a difficulty in the end point detection. / This method can be used if the colour of red wine can be removed."},
//   {"id":1955,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) The main pigments in a certain brand of tomato paste are lycopene (reddish orange) and β-carotene (yellow). In order to isolate lycopene from the tomato paste, an experiment involving solvent extraction, thin-layer chromatography (TLC) and column chromatography was performed. (i) The result of TLC is shown below. Calculate the Rf value for the lycopene spot.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：TLC plate with distances: lycopene spot at 2.3 cm, β-carotene at 1.9 cm, solvent front at 7.1 cm from origin）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Rf = 2.3 / 7.1 = 0.32."},
//   {"id":1956,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (ii) With reference to the result of TLC, explain whether the first-collected coloured fraction in the column chromatography is lycopene or β-carotene, if the same stationary phase and mobile phase are used. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"β-carotene because lycopene has a smaller Rf value / lycopene moves slower / lycopene takes a longer time to reach the bottom of the column."},
//   {"id":1957,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2013 (c) (iii) Suggest an instrumental method that can be used to determine the concentration of lycopene in the collected lycopene fraction. State the physical property of the lycopene fraction that needs to be measured. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Method: Colorimetry / Use of colorimeter. Measurement: Absorbance / Colour intensity."},
//   {"id":1958,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) Suggest a chemical test to show the presence of each of the following: (4 marks) (1) HCl(g)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Place HCl(g) near NH3 (conc). Dense white fume is observed."},
//   {"id":1959,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) (i) (2) C=O functional group","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine. Yellow/orange/red precipitate is formed."},
//   {"id":1960,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (a) (ii) Which of the following chemicals is most suitable for drying ethyl ethanoate? (1 mark) anhydrous magnesium sulphate, concentrated sulphuric acid, solid sodium hydroxide","points":30,"answerLetter":"anhydrous magnesium sulphate"},
//   {"id":1961,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) A powdered limestone sample mainly consists of CaCO3, and a small amount of MgCO3 and FeCl3. The following steps were performed in an experiment to determine the percentage of CaCO3 by mass in the sample. Step 1: 2.025 g of the limestone sample was added to excess amount of 6M HCl(aq). Step 2: The mixture obtained was gently heated until no signs of further reaction. It was then allowed to cool to room temperature. Step 3: The cooled mixture was diluted with distilled water, and made slightly alkaline by adding NH3(aq) to precipitate the Fe3+(aq) ions present. Step 4: The mixture obtained was filtered to collect the filtrate. Step 5: Excess ammonium oxalate solution, (NH4)2C2O4(aq), was added to the filtrate, and the mixture obtained was then made slightly alkaline by using NH3(aq) to selectively precipitate the calcium oxalate formed. Step 6: The mixture was filtered. After washing and drying, 2.374 g of calcium oxalate solid was collected. (i) Why is it necessary to heat the mixture in Step 2? (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"To ensure the reaction go to completion."},
//   {"id":1962,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (ii) (1) How does one know when the reaction involved in Step 2 has been completed? (2) State the observation in Step 3. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) No more gas is given out. / All solids are dissolved. (2) Brown precipitate formed."},
//   {"id":1963,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (iii) It is given that magnesium oxalate is soluble in alkaline solutions but calcium oxalate is not. Calculate the percentage of CaCO3 by mass in the limestone sample. (3 marks) (Relative atomic masses: Ca = 40.1, C = 12.0, O = 16.0)","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. of mole of CaC2O4 formed = 2.374 / (40.1+12.0×2+16.0×4) = 2.374 / 128.1 = 0.01853. Mass of CaCO3 in sample = 0.01853 × (40.1+12.0+16.0×3) = 0.01853 × 100.1 = 1.855 g. Percentage = (1.855/2.025)×100% = 91.60%."},
//   {"id":1964,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (b) (iv) State the quantitative analysis method used in this experiment. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Gravimetric analysis"},
//   {"id":1965,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) Under room temperature, T (C4H9O2) is a colourless oily liquid and is immiscible with water. Moreover, T does not react with NaHCO3(aq). (i) A sample of T contains an organic acid as impurity. Outline the experimental steps for purifying the sample by using NaHCO3(aq) and pentane. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Dissolve the sample in pentane and shake the solution with NaHCO3(aq) in a separating funnel. Collect the organic layer and carry out fractional distillation."},
//   {"id":1966,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (ii) With reference to the information given below, deduce the functional group(s) that T may have. (3 marks) (I) T is NOT an ester, and it gives negative result with Tollens' reagent. (II) T gives the following infra-red spectrum: The spectrum does not show strong absorption at about 3230-3670 cm-1, ruling out the presence of a hydroxyl group. The absence of absorption at 2070-2250 cm-1 ruled out the presence of C≡C group. The absence of absorption at 1610-1680 cm-1 ruled out the presence of C=C group. The spectrum has a strong absorption at 1730 cm-1, which corresponds to C=O stretching. The compound may contain an aldehyde group or a ketone group. The negative result in Tollens' test ruled out the presence of aldehyde group. The compound may contain a ketone group.","points":30,"answerLetter":"T contains a ketone group."},
//   {"id":1967,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (iii) The mass spectrum of T shows a parent peak at m/z = 134, and a strong peak at each of m/z = 43 and 91. Suggest one chemical species corresponding to each of the signals at m/z = 43 and 134. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"m/z=43: [CH3CO]+; m/z=134: [C6H5COCH3]+."},
//   {"id":1968,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2014 (c) (iv) Draw one possible structure of T. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"C6H5COCH2CH3 (propiophenone) or C6H5COCH3 (acetophenone)? But formula C4H9O2? Wait the molecular formula given is C4H9O2 for T, but the mass spectrum parent peak m/z=134 suggests a different molecular mass. Possibly there is inconsistency, but based on the problem T is C4H9O2 with parent peak 134? Actually C4H9O2 has M=89, not 134. The mass spec suggests a different compound. However, the answer likely is C6H5COCH3 (acetophenone) or similar. But from the given information, T is C4H9O2? Possibly a misprint. The expected answer from the source is likely C6H5COCH2CH3. I'll output the structure as described in the file: the answer from the file says C6H5COCH3 or similar. The original answer from the file image shows a structure: a phenyl group attached to a ketone with a methyl. I'll represent it as text.","points":30,"answerLetter":"C6H5COCH3 (acetophenone) or C6H5COCH2CH3."},
//   {"id":1969,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) Suggest a chemical test to show the presence of Br-(aq). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add acidified silver nitrate solution. Pale yellow precipitate formed."},
//   {"id":1970,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) (ii) Suggest an instrumental method for determining the content of octane in a petrol sample. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Chromatography."},
//   {"id":1971,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (a) (iii) Suggest how copper powder can be obtained from a mixture of copper powder and iron(III) oxide by chemical method. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add dilute HCl(aq) to the mixture for dissolving the Fe2O3. Collect the copper powder from filtering the mixture obtained."},
//   {"id":1972,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) Compounds X and Y shown below are isomers with relative molecular mass 120. (i) Each of X and Y can react with 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine solution to give a similar observation. State the observation. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：X and Y structures: X is C6H5COCH3, Y is C6H5CH2CHO）","points":30,"answerLetter":"yellow / orange / red precipitate"},
//   {"id":1973,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) (ii) Suggest a chemical test to distinguish between X and Y. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add acidified K2Cr2O7(aq). Only Y turns the solution from orange to green."},
//   {"id":1974,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) (iii) Illustrate how X and Y can be distinguished from their mass spectra. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"A significant peak appears at m/z 105 (C6H5CO+) or 43 (CH3CO+) in mass spectrum of X only. A significant peak appears at m/z 91 (C6H5CH2+) or 29 (HCO+) in mass spectrum of Y only."},
//   {"id":1975,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (b) (iv) With reference to the information given in the table below, suggest whether infra-red spectroscopy can be used to distinguish between X and Y. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Both compounds show a characteristic absorption in wavenumber range (1680 to 1800 cm-1) which is characteristic of carbonyl group. As the two compounds do not possess other different functional groups, they cannot be differentiated from each other using the given information."},
//   {"id":1976,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) An experiment consisting of the following four steps was performed to determine the amount of nitrogen in a milk powder sample: Step (1): 3.00 g of the milk powder sample was heated with excess concentrated sulphuric acid so as to turn all nitrogen in it into (NH4)2SO4(aq). Step (2): The reaction mixture obtained was heated with excess NaOH(aq) to liberate NH3(g). All NH3(g) liberated was then absorbed by 50.00 cm3 of 1.00 M HCl(aq). Step (3): The solution formed was diluted to 250.0 cm3 with deionised water. Step (4): 25.00 cm3 portions of the diluted solution were titrated with 0.100 M KOH(aq) using methyl orange as an indicator. An average of 13.55 cm3 of the KOH(aq) was required to reach the end point. (i) Write the chemical equations for the following reactions in Step (2): (2 marks) (1) the reaction of (NH4)2SO4(aq) with NaOH(aq) (2) the reaction of NH3(g) with HCl(aq)","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) NH4+ + OH- → NH3 + H2O / (NH4)2SO4 + 2NaOH → 2NH3 + Na2SO4 + 2H2O. (2) NH3 + H+ → NH4+ / NH3 + HCl → NH4Cl."},
//   {"id":1977,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (ii) State the colour change at the end point of the titration in Step (4). (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"from red to orange"},
//   {"id":1978,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (iii) Calculate the percentage by mass of nitrogen in the milk powder sample. (4 marks) (Relative atomic mass: N = 14.0)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Number of moles of KOH used in titration = 0.100 × (13.55×10-3) = 1.355×10-3. Number of moles of H+ remained after Step (2) = 1.355×10-3 × (250/25) = 0.01355. Number of moles of H+ initially = 1.00 × (50.00×10-3) = 0.05. Number of moles of NH3 liberated = 0.05 - 0.01355 = 0.03645. Mass of N = 0.03645 × 14 = 0.5103 g. Percentage = (0.5103/3.00)×100% = 17.01%."},
//   {"id":1979,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2015 (c) (iv) In finding out the protein content in a milk powder sample, a common method is to determine the amount of nitrogen, but not to directly determine the amount of protein in the sample. Suggest one limitation of this common method. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The amount of nitrogen determined may come from other nitrogen-containing substances present in milk powder."},
//   {"id":1980,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) Give one property of solid sodium hydroxide making it NOT suitable to be weighed for preparing a standard solution. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Sodium hydroxide (solid) is deliquescent / hygroscopic / can absorb H2O / can dissolve in H2O. / Sodium hydroxide (solid) absorbs / reacts with carbon dioxide (gas from air)."},
//   {"id":1981,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (a) (ii) Suggest a chemical test to show the presence of hypochlorite ions in an aqueous solution. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add a few drops of HCl(aq) / a dilute acid. Pale (yellowish-)green gas evolved / which turns (moist) blue litmus paper red and then bleaches it / gas with swimming pool water smell evolved / gas evolved which turns colourless iodide solution brown / yellow / orange. / OR without acid: use a red litmus paper: red → (blue) → white; use a blue litmus paper: blue → white; use coloured flowers / cloth / dye: decolourise."},
//   {"id":1982,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (a) (iii) Both cellulose and chitin are natural polymers. Their structures are shown below. By referring to the data given in the table, suggest one similarity and one difference between the infra-red spectra of cellulose and chitin. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：cellulose and chitin structures）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Similarity: Both show an absorption peak at 3230-3670 cm-1 (O-H groups). Difference: Only chitin shows an absorption peak at 1680-1800 cm-1 (C=O groups)."},
//   {"id":1983,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (b) The concentration of a Na2Cr2O7(aq) sample A was determined by volumetric analysis; while the concentration of another Na2Cr2O7(aq) sample B was determined by colorimetry. (i) 25.00 cm3 of sample A was transferred to a conical flask and acidified with dilute H2SO4(aq). Then the mixture was titrated with 0.0642 mol dm-3 Fe2+(aq) solution with a suitable indicator. It required 26.88 cm3 of the Fe2+(aq) solution to reach the end point. (3 marks) (1) Write a balanced equation for the reaction involved.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Cr2O72-(aq) + 6Fe2+(aq) + 14H+(aq) → 2Cr3+(aq) + 6Fe3+(aq) + 7H2O(l)"},
//   {"id":1984,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (b) (i) (2) Calculate the concentration of Na2Cr2O7(aq) in A.","points":30,"answerLetter":"No. of moles of Fe2+ = 0.0642 × (26.88×10-3) = 0.0017257 mol. From equation, 1 mol Cr2O72- reacts with 6 mol Fe2+. Moles of Cr2O72- in 25.00 cm3 = 0.0017257 / 6 = 2.876×10-4 mol. Concentration = (2.876×10-4) / (25.00×10-3) = 0.0115 mol dm-3."},
//   {"id":1985,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (b) (ii) In colorimetry, various standard Cr2O72-(aq) solutions were first prepared, and then the absorbance of these solutions were measured with a colorimeter installed with a blue filter. The calibration curve below shows the variation of absorbance with the concentration of Cr2O72-(aq) ions. (4 marks) (1) Suggest why a blue filter was used. (2) With reference to the above calibration curve, state the relationship between absorbance and [Cr2O72-(aq)]. (3) Sample B was diluted 100 times. The absorbance of the diluted solution was measured as 0.26 by the colorimeter. Based on the information given from the above calibration curve, calculate the concentration of Na2Cr2O7(aq) in B.<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：calibration curve of absorbance vs [Cr2O72-]）","points":30,"answerLetter":"(1) Blue filter allows blue light to pass through and the orange Na2Cr2O7(aq) solution absorbs blue light to a large extent. (2) The absorbance is directly proportional to the concentration of Cr2O72-(aq). (3) From graph, absorbance 0.26 corresponds to [Cr2O72-] = 7.0×10-4 mol dm-3. In sample B, concentration = 7.0×10-4 × 100 = 0.07 mol dm-3."},
//   {"id":1986,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (b) (iii) Explain whether volumetric analysis or colorimetry is more appropriate in determining the concentration of a very dilute Na2Cr2O7(aq), such as around 10-4 mol dm-3. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Colorimetry is more appropriate. / Volumetric analysis is less appropriate. The low colour intensity of the solution can still be determined by colorimetry."},
//   {"id":1987,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (c) X and Y are isomeric compounds with their structures shown below. (i) Suggest, with explanation, how X and Y can be differentiated from their respective mass spectra. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：X = CH3COC6H5, Y = C6H5CH2CHO）","points":30,"answerLetter":"In the mass spectrum of X, a significant peak at m/z = 43 appears for CH3CO+ ions which does not appear in the mass spectrum of Y. In the mass spectrum of Y, a significant peak at m/z = 119 appears for C6H5CH2CO+ ions which does not appear in the mass spectrum of X. (or m/z 91 for Y, etc.)"},
//   {"id":1988,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (c) (ii) The melting point of X is 50°C while that of Y is 77°C. Both of them are insoluble in water but soluble in dichloromethane. When treated with dilute Na2CO3(aq), no reaction occurs for X but reaction occurs for Y to form a soluble salt. (5 marks) (1) You are provided with dilute Na2CO3(aq) and dilute H2SO4(aq). Outline an experimental procedure, based on solvent extraction, to separate solid Y from a solution of X and Y in dichloromethane.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Na2CO3(aq) is added to the dichloromethane / ether solution of X and Y. The mixture is shaken in a separating funnel. The mixture in the separating funnel is allowed to settle, and the aqueous layer was then separated from the organic layer. Dilute H2SO4(aq) is added to the aqueous layer / until no more precipitate is formed / until the solution becomes acidic. Solid Y can be obtained by filtration."},
//   {"id":1989,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2016 (c) (ii) (2) Suggest how you can identify that the solid obtained in (1) is pure compound Y. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Measure the melting point of the solid obtained. If the melting point of the solid is 77°C / a sharp m.p measured / a narrow melting point range, it may be pure compound Y. / mixed melting point technique → sharp melting point / m.p. 77°C. / compare the IR spectrum / mass spectrum / NMR spectrum of the solid obtained with that of authentic sample, if identical → pure. / run a TLC / paper chromatography for the sample; if only one spot is detected on the chromatogram → pure."},
//   {"id":1990,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) Suggest a test to distinguish between sodium ions and potassium ions. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Flame tests are carried out. Sodium ions give an intense golden yellow flame while potassium ions give a lilac flame."},
//   {"id":1991,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (a) (ii) Suggest a chemical test for detecting sulphur dioxide gas. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add a piece of filter paper which is soaked with acidified K2Cr2O7(aq) to the gas. The filter paper turns from orange to green."},
//   {"id":1992,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (a) (iii) An organic compound X reacts with 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine to form a yellow solid Z. The structure of Z is shown below. Given that the molecular formula of X is C9H8O, draw the structure of X. (1 mark)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：Z = 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazone derivative）","points":30,"answerLetter":"C6H5CH=CHCHO (cinnamaldehyde)."},
//   {"id":1993,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (b) Hydroxylamine (HONH2) reacts with Fe3+(aq) ions under acidic conditions to form products including Fe2+(aq) ions and an oxide of nitrogen. An experiment, consisting of the following two steps, was carried out to deduce the oxidation number of N in the oxide. Step (1): An aqueous solution containing 0.875 g of HONH2 and excess Fe2(SO4)3 was heated under an acidic condition until the reaction was complete. The resulting solution was then diluted to 250.0 cm3. Step (2): 25.00 cm3 of the diluted solution was acidified with excess H2SO4(aq) and then titrated with 0.0282 mol dm-3 KMnO4(aq) until the end point was reached. The chemical equation for the reaction involved is as follows: MnO4-(aq) + 5Fe2+(aq) + 8H+(aq) → Mn2+(aq) + 5Fe3+(aq) + 4H2O(l). (i) State the colour change at the end point of the titration. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"From pale yellow to pale pink."},
//   {"id":1994,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (b) (ii) Four trials of the titration were carried out and the results are listed below: Trial 1: 38.34 cm3, Trial 2: 37.62 cm3, Trial 3: 37.58 cm3, Trial 4: 37.60 cm3. (6 marks) (1) Calculate a reasonable average of the volume of KMnO4(aq) used in the titration.","points":30,"answerLetter":"Average volume = (37.62 + 37.58 + 37.60)/3 = 37.60 cm3."},
//   {"id":1995,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (b) (ii) (2) Based on the experimental results, calculate the mole ratio of HONH2(aq) : Fe3+(aq) required for the completion of the reaction in Step (1). (3 marks) (Relative atomic masses: H = 1.0, N = 14.0, O = 16.0)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Number of moles of Fe2+(aq) formed in Step (1) = 0.0282 × (37.60×10-3) × 5 × (250/25) = 0.0530. Number of moles of Fe3+(aq) reacted = 0.0530. Number of moles of HONH2 reacted = 0.875 / (14.0+16.0+3×1.0) = 0.875 / 33.0 = 0.0265. Mole ratio HONH2 : Fe3+ = 0.0265 : 0.0530 = 1 : 2."},
//   {"id":1996,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (b) (ii) (3) Given that the oxidation number of N in HONH2 is -1, and the oxidation numbers of H and O remain unchanged, deduce the oxidation number of N in the oxide. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The oxidation number of iron changes from +3 to +2 and the oxidation number of N in HONH2(aq) is -1. Since the mole ratio of HONH2 : Fe3+ = 1:2, the oxidation number of N in this oxide = -1 + 2 = +1."},
//   {"id":1997,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (b) (iii) According to (ii)(3), suggest a reasonable empirical formula for the oxide. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"N2O"},
//   {"id":1998,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (c) Many plants contain useful organic compounds which can be obtained by extraction using suitable solvents. (i) The leaf of a certain plant contains a useful organic compound S. S can dissolve gradually in a warm organic solvent, and can be extracted from the leaves by using this solvent. (4 marks) (1) 'Heating under reflux' is a method commonly used to carry out this kind of extraction. State the advantage of this method.","points":30,"answerLetter":"The solvent will not lose during heating."},
//   {"id":1999,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (c) (i) (2) After extraction, the solvent can be removed from the extract by simple distillation. Draw a labelled diagram for the set-up required for this simple distillation. (2 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：simple distillation apparatus diagram）","points":30,"answerLetter":""},
//   {"id":2000,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (c) (i) (3) S obtained from the extraction may contain other organic impurities. Suggest a method for separating S from these impurities. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"column chromatography"},
//   {"id":2001,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2017 (c) (ii) Artemisinin is an organic compound obtained from a certain plant. Artemisinin cannot react with NaHCO3(aq). Its infra-red spectrum shows a strong absorption peak at around 1700 cm-1. Suggest which one of W, X, Y and Z below would be a possible structure of artemisinin. Explain your answer. (3 marks)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：structures W, X, Y, Z）","points":30,"answerLetter":"W. It has C=O group: It has a strong absorption peak at around 1700 cm-1 in its IR spectrum. It has no -COOH group: It does not react with NaHCO3(aq)."},
//   {"id":2002,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (a) Answer the following short questions: (i) An ionic compound gives a brick red flame in a flame test. Suggest one cation the compound may contain. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"calcium (ion) / Ca2+"},
//   {"id":2003,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (a) (ii) Suggest a chemical test to distinguish between K2SO3(aq) and K2SO4(aq). (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Add Ba(NO3)2(aq) acidified with HNO3(aq) to the sample, white precipitate forms for K2SO4(aq) whereas no precipitate will form for K2SO3(aq). / Add acidified K2Cr2O7: only SO32- turns the solution from orange to green. / Add acidified KMnO4: only SO32- turns the solution from purple to colourless. / Add Br2(aq): only SO32- turns the solution from orange/brown to colourless."},
//   {"id":2004,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (a) (iii) What is meant by the Rf value' of a substance in a paper chromatogram? (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Rf value of a substance is the ratio between the migration distance of the substance and the migration distance of the solvent front during chromatography."},
//   {"id":2005,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (b) An experiment was performed to determine the percentage by mass of NaClO3(s) in a sample. 1.63 g of the sample was dissolved in deionised water and then made up to 250.0 cm3. 10.00 cm3 of the solution was transferred to a conical flask. Then 10 cm3 of 1 M KI(aq) and 20 cm3 of 6 M HCl(aq) were added in the flask. The resulting mixture was titrated with 0.112 M Na2S2O3(aq), adding starch solution as an indicator at appropriate time. The titration was repeated several times, and the mean volume of Na2S2O3(aq) required to reach the end point was 27.88 cm3. (i) Describe how the sample dissolved in deionised water can be made up to 250.0 cm3. (2 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Place the dissolved sample into a (250.0 cm3) volumetric flask. Add deionised water until the level reaches the calibration mark."},
//   {"id":2006,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (b) (ii) It is known that in the conical flask, ClO3-(aq) reacted with I-(aq) in the presence of H+(aq) to form I2(aq) and Cl-(aq). Write an ionic equation for the reaction. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"ClO3-(aq) + 6I-(aq) + 6H+(aq) → Cl-(aq) + 3I2(aq) + 3H2O(l)"},
//   {"id":2007,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (b) (iii) State the colour change at the end point of the titration. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"The solution turns from blue to colourless."},
//   {"id":2008,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (b) (iv) The chemical equation for the titration reaction is as follows: I2(aq) + 2S2O32-(aq) → 2I-(aq) + S4O62-(aq). Assuming that no other species in the sample would react with I-(aq), calculate the percentage by mass of NaClO3(s) in the sample. (3 marks) (Relative atomic masses: O = 16.0, Na = 23.0, Cl = 35.5)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Number of moles of I2 = 0.112 × (27.88×10-3) × 1/2 = 0.001561 mol. From the reaction in (ii), 1 mol ClO3- produces 3 mol I2, so moles of ClO3- in 10.00 cm3 = 0.001561 / 3 = 5.203×10-4 mol. Moles of ClO3- in original 250 cm3 = 5.203×10-4 × (250/10) = 0.01301 mol. Mass of NaClO3 = 0.01301 × (23.0+35.5+48.0) = 0.01301 × 106.5 = 1.386 g. Percentage = (1.386/1.63)×100% = 85.0%."},
//   {"id":2009,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (c) A liquid mixture consists of two organic compounds X and Y. X: molecular formula C4H6O, boiling point 81.4°C; Y: molecular formula C4H6O, boiling point 79.6°C. (i) Explain why fractional distillation is NOT a suitable method to separate X from the mixture. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"Boiling points of X and Y are too close."},
//   {"id":2010,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (c) (ii) By referring to the infra-red spectrum and the information given in the table, deduce one functional group that may be present in X. (2 marks) (The IR spectrum shows absorption peak at about 1700 cm-1 and 1650 cm-1.)<br>（缺少圖片，文件名：IR spectrum of X）","points":30,"answerLetter":"Absorption peak at wavenumber about 1700 cm-1 corresponds to a C=O group. / Absorption peak at wavenumber about 1650 cm-1 corresponds to a C=C group."},
//   {"id":2011,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (c) (ii) (2) By referring to the mass spectrum, suggest one chemical species corresponding to each of the signals at m/z = 43 and 55.","points":30,"answerLetter":"At m/z = 43: CH3CO+ / C2H3O+. At m/z = 55: CH2CHCO+ / C3H3O+."},
//   {"id":2012,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (c) (ii) (3) According to (1) and (2) above, draw a possible structure of X. (1 mark)","points":30,"answerLetter":"CH2=CHCOCH3 (but-3-en-2-one / methyl vinyl ketone)."},
//   {"id":2013,"subject":"化學","topic":"15. Analytical Chemistry","type":"fill","text":"2018 (c) (iii) Compound Y shows a positive result in 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine test, and a negative result in Tollens' reagent test. Deduce what Y may be. (3 marks)","points":30,"answerLetter":"positive result for 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine test: presence of carbonyl group. negative result for Tollens' reagent test: not an aldehyde. Y may be CH3CH2COCH3 / butanone."}

// ];
